{Welcome to my third Chessable course, where I will provide you with a whole repertoire for Black after d4 d5 c4 e6 , which is the famous Queen's Gambit Declined.  I am Adrien Demuth, a Grandmaster from France. I have been a chess professional for a few years, coaching, and being a second in the French National Team during the Olympiads, and you might already know me from the opening books I wrote, or from the first Chessable course I published, in two parts, about 1.d4 with White. I am a chess enthusiast, I particularly love studying theory!} 1. d4 ({A lot of different authors and players have their own vision and ideas regarding} 1. d4 {. I have always liked flexible lines, seeking variations that are easier to play from White's side, and it seems to me that it's easier to get these types of lines with d4 rather than e4 . Nowadays, Black doesn't only just try to reach equality and often wants to take the advantage after the opening, if the opponent helps a little.}) 1... d5 ({That is the most natural way to reach the Queen's Gambit Declined. But it already seems important to mention that it's possible to reach it with a different move order:} 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 {. Black plays in the spirit of the Nimzo-Indian. It could be a good idea to try to provoke} 3. Nf3 {(as many people fear the Nimzo after Nc3} Bb4+ {) . Then d5 transposes into the lines of our repertoire with Nf3 .  And if White prefers} 4. Nc3 {instead, you can of course opt for the Nimzo-Indian Defense, but you can also simply} d5 {transposing into the Queen's Gambit Declined, after having bluffed Nimzo-Indian ideas. There is no drawback to this move order if your repertoire is flexible and you are prepared to face other opening systems.}) 2. c4 ({The Queen's Gambit! Even if it's a bit weird to me to call it a gambit, as White generally gets the pawn back very fast if we take with dxc4 . Instead of} 2. c4 {, White has a few options, the main one being the London System (with Bf4 played now or after Nf3 ) . But I am not going to cover all the sidelines, and instead, only focus on the text move.}) {Now, dxc4 leads to the Queen's Gambit Declined, while c6 is the Slav Defense. Other sidelines are also possible for Black, but that's not my preference.} 2... e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! One of the oldest openings of modern theory. Black is glad to protect the pawn on d5 with another pawn. In general, White develops one of the two knights. It has been played for ages, and it will probably always remain as one of the soundest openings for Black against the Queen's Gambit.} 3. Nc3 {This will be the subject of our first part. White simply develops and brings more forces to the center.} (3. Nf3 {is the other way to develop. I would say that it probably means White wants to continue with 4.g3 , to reach the Catalan Variation, but it's not necessarily true.} Nf6 {, again, Black keeps some flexibility and starts by developing the knight on the most natural square. It could be the starting position if you prefer the Nimzo-Indian move-order, after d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {.  Now, as I said before, g3 leads to the Catalan Variation, e3 can lead to various types of Colle Systems (sometimes played with c4 delayed) , Bg5 would like to transpose into the normal lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined while avoiding the many possibilities Black has after Nc3 , which transposes into Nc3 Nf6 Nf3 .}) 3... Nf6 ({Black develops in the same way. We will of course have a look at various sidelines, but also the 3 main continuations, which are cxd5 exd5 , the Exchange Queen's Gambit Declined, Bg5 , the old main line, which tries to keep our bishop blocked on c8 , and Nf3 that can also be played via Nf3} 3... Nf6 {Nc3 . After Be7 , White usually continues with} 4. Bf4 {or Bg5 .  I have tried to focus on a repertoire that is easy to understand, sound, and with a global homogeneity, to make it easier for you to remember. I hope you will enjoy it, and I can't wait to show you my variations. ;)}) *


