1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. We are going to go through various lines of the repertoire, chosen to show the general ideas and have a good taste of the repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. a3 {Not a great move. It obviously prevents ... Bb4 , but such a waste of tempo doesn't justify this.} dxc4 {In modern chess, Black tries to fight for the advantage before even thinking about equality. That's what we can try to achieve with this move. Black could play normally, but that's much more convincing and dangerous for White. Throughout the lines, you will see that I have often chosen variations where Black takes on c4 when it's possible.} 5. e4 c5 6. Nf3 b5 {That's bad news for White. Black is not willing to give up the c4 -pawn so easily. White should accept the b-pawn at the price of a quick counterattack for Black.} 7. Nxb5 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Nxe4 {Again, Black has an extra pawn, but the pawn on c4 is condemned. For more information, see the dedicated section .} *


