1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. We are going to go through various lines of the repertoire, chosen to show the general ideas and have a good taste of the repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. g3 {This is in the spirit of the Catalan, but with Nc3 instead of Nf3 . That makes a big difference, and it enables Black to get a direct reaction in the center.} c5 {It's already hard for White to meet this move.} 5. cxd5 {That's the principled reaction, trying to create an isolated pawn for Black, but we have an intermediate move.} cxd4 {A very similar idea to the Schara-Hennig Gambit, but with g3 and ... Nf6 included. This can only be a better version for Black!} 6. Qa4+ {Usually, White includes this move in order to bring Black's bishop to d7 , so that there is no pin on the d5 -pawn.} Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 8. Nf3 (8. Nxd5 {instead hands Black a powerful initiative after} Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qd1 Rd8 {, when the material gain won't compensate for White's suffering.}) 8... Nc6 9. Qd3 {It's probably slightly better than the Qxd4 variation, but it's not enough for White.} Qb6 {Black has an active position .} *

