1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. We are going to go through various lines of the repertoire, chosen to show the general ideas and have a good taste of the repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. c5 {This is premature due to:} b6 {The center is immediately challenged.} 5. cxb6 ({If White needs to take so fast, it means that c5 was simply not good.} 5. b4 {seems logical but only makes things worse . For this move to work, White already needs to have developed the bishop in order to have the rook on a1 protected.}) 5... axb6 {Black is already better.} 6. e3 c5 7. Nf3 Be7 {Black has a great center .} *


