1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. We are going to go through various lines of the repertoire, chosen to show the general ideas and have a good taste of the repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bf4 dxc4 {It's clearly logical in view of the rest of our repertoire against sidelines. Especially with the bishop on f4 , that can fall on the attack of a knight coming to d5 .} 5. e3 ({Clearly the most critical. White would like to get the pawn back and doesn't expose the pawn too far, as in the} 5. e4 {variation.}) 5... c5 {In the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black immediately throws a pawn to the center, while White is focused on the c4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 {Solid and secure.} cxd4 (6... Nd5 {is a very logical possibility, as the knight is untouchable (or c4 would be safely protected). But White can keep a slight initiative thanks to a better development with} 7. Bxc4 {and I prefer to avoid that.}) 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 {White is hoping that better development can bring something. But that's not clear how exactly! Now, Black has at least a couple of good options, and the choice will depend on your style.} Nbd7 ({The risky choice!} 8... a6 {is the safest approach , simply preventing any Nb5 .}) 9. Ndb5 e5 {The right reaction! Black attacks the bishop and shouldn't be afraid of the fork. White can't really take the rook, otherwise, we would take the bishop, and then the knight is trapped on a8 . And if the bishop moves, Black goes ... Kd8 and then chases the knight with ... a6 . This position is analyzed extensively in the relevant chapter .} *

