1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. We are going to go through various lines of the repertoire, chosen to show the general ideas and have a good taste of the repertoire.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Nf3 ({A very important line. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({I like to start immediately with ... h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) 6. Bxf6 ({Clearly less popular than} 6. Bh4 {, but it sometimes contains some venom when White comes with aggressive plans, such as O-O-O .}) 6... Bxf6 ({Now, in case of e3 (which is the most played move), this transposes into e3 h6} 6... Bxf6 {that we will analyze later. Instead, we deal here with the early alternatives.}) 7. cxd5 {This move decides the structure of the center; it becomes harder for Black to react there, but easier to develop the c8 -bishop.} exd5 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 {Definitely the main line, and a logical developing move, but Black has a strong reaction available.} c5 10. dxc5 Bxc3+ {This makes things clear, Black will fight for the pawn structure and prevents any idea of Na4 . The pawn on c5 has no chance of survival.} 11. bxc3 Nd7 ({One way or another, Black gets his pawn back. For instance, O-O Nxc5 Bc2} 11... b6 {. The plan is not to do a fianchetto, the bishop would be stuck on b7 . Instead, it will probably reach e6 or a6 , but the real idea is simply to stabilize the knight on c5 .}) *

