1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {We are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in a standalone chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at other options first!} 4. Qc2 {This move is relatively flexible, and it contains some potential transpositions into other lines where White plays an early Qc2 .} dxc4 {In general, I am not afraid of the variations where White needs to get the queen to c4 to take the pawn back. That's not an exception (and it's even better like this when White didn't play Qa4 + because we don't have to protect against the check with a move we don't necessarily want to play so early).} 5. Qxc4 a6 ({Black prepares ... b5 . It's useless to play a4 , as} 5... b5 {works anyway. But Black can also prefer to use the weakness of the c4 -square, with Nc6 .}) 6. Bf4 {White attacks the c7 -pawn.} Bd6 {Black is intending to trade bishops.} 7. Bg3 ({Instead, if} 7. Bxd6 {, then} cxd6 {is a good move, bringing another pawn to the center. The position is balanced.}) 7... b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. e3 ({It's complicated for White to play} 10. e4 {, because of} Bb4 {attacking it and preparing ... c5 and ... Rac8 .}) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 h6 {Black doesn't take any risk.} 12. O-O Rc8 {The idea is to bring the bishop back to e7 , and then push ... c5 . Black will take over the initiative if we manage this.} ({If White gets overly ambitious and plays e4? , after} 12... Bxg3 13. hxg3 c5 {, we can say thank you for the help, as White's center crumbles.}) *

