1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. b3 {That's the classical way of handling the Colle System with White. I am going to focus on the main system for White, as the rest is not so dangerous. White can play in many different ways.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {I would like to clarify things in the center directly.} 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. exd4 {White is ready to accept a hanging pair of pawns in the center because that brings dynamic play. This is the reason why we won't take on c4 immediately, we do it only if we have a reason to. As long as we keep the pawn on d5 , White isn't able to push d4 - d5 .} b6 9. O-O Bb7 ({The bishop is ready to come into play, we will just wait for the right time to take on c4 . Now, I think both Nc3 or Nbd2 are equally important systems, played as often. Let's mention that Qe2 has no independent value, as after} 9... Nbd7 {, White has to transpose into other lines with} 10. Nc3 {or Nbd2 .}) 10. Nc3 {A logical move. White puts pressure on d5 .} Nbd7 ({As against 10.Nbd2 , I prefer this move instead of} 10... Nc6 {, which is the main line, for the same reasons: it can go to f8 at some point, it doesn't bother the b7 -bishop, and it protects the knight on f6 .  If the bishop was on d6 instead of e7 , I might see things differently, as ... Nc6 allows the knight to go to e7 and potentially f5 . But that's not the case here, and I don't want to spend a tempo playing ... Bd6 .}) 11. Qe2 {White improves the queen, controls e5 , and enables the rooks to come to the center.} Qc7 {There is no rook on c1 , so Black brings the queen here immediately. It also provokes Rac1 , but that's not forced and White may understand Black's plan.} 12. Ne5 {White prevents ... Qf4 but allows our usual reply.} dxc4 13. bxc4 Nxe5 {Forcing the weakening of the c5 -square.} 14. dxe5 Nd7 {And the knight heads towards c5 . As usual, the variation is analyzed further in the main course.} *

