1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. Nc3 ({The main position, and a transposition into} 5. Nc3 {Be7 e3 too.}) 5... O-O {White has tried a wild variety of moves here, as on the previous move, and some are similar.} 6. Bd3 {By far the main move here. I must admit that it's a bit strange to me because Black can so easily reach a good version of a Queen's Gambit Accepted...} dxc4 {Of course, the bishop has to move again.} 7. Bxc4 {Usually in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, White is supposed to take back on c4 in one move, with the bishop directly on f1 . That's a loss of a full tempo. Also, the knight isn't necessarily well-placed on c3 . The reason is that Black usually tries to push ... a6 and ... b5 (if we are allowed to).  When White would like to challenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. O-O b5 {Usually, in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black starts with ... c5 before ... b5 . But here, I think it's better to start with ... b5 .} ({It gives better chances to use the extra tempo (because of the line} 8... c5 9. dxc5 {, where the e7 -bishop will have to move again to take back on c5 , losing the extra tempo (it usually takes back from f8 ). Here, if Black manages ... c5 , we will take back with the knight in most cases. White has now 3 possible retreats for the bishop.}) 9. Bd3 {This is the main continuation. White controls the center, and allows the queen to come to e2 .} Bb7 10. e4 {The most ambitious try, taking over the center immediately, but Black has just the time to react in the center.} c5 {When the d4 -pawn disappears, White's center is less impressive. Black is at least equal. Further details are provided in the relevant section .} *

