1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. e4 {White takes control of the center, which makes a lot of sense, obviously. But e5 isn't a real threat, so we have time to react in the center.} c5 (5... b5 $5 {is also an interesting option for Black. But White has developed the following interesting line recently:} 6. a4 c6 7. Nc3 Qb6 8. Be2 {. White can castle quickly followed by d4 - d5 ideas. The position is tense and complicated.}) 6. Nc3 {White develops and protects the e4 -pawn once more.} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 {Black needs to prevent Ndb5 , with annoying threats on c7 , and this also prepares ... b5 , to develop actively.} 9. Bxc4 h6 10. Bh4 (10. Bxf6 {just gives us the bishop pair and a comfortable position after} gxf6 11. O-O Bc5 {followed by ... Bd7 , ... Nc6 , ... Ke7 , etc.}) 10... b5 11. Be2 g5 12. Bg3 Bb7 13. O-O Nbd7 {The position remains roughly balanced, but I feel Black has interesting prospects with our active pieces.} ({Instead of finishing development,} 13... Nxe4 {would be severely punished, as White gets a deadly initiative after} 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bh5 {(threatening Nxe6 )} Ke7 16. Rfe1 {and with the other rook coming to c1 , Black will have to shed material soon.}) *

