1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 at the beginning of the Quickstarter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the subject of the latter trainables, and e3 was already covered . Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. Qc2 {Even if that's usually the right square for the queen, it doesn't mean that it should go there immediately! Here, it's probably too soon to say it's safe. Black immediately fights back in the center.} c5 6. dxc5 {This has been played in most of the games, but I feel it's dangerous for White to allow Black's next move.} d4 {An ambitious move, to disrupt White's piece harmony.} 7. Nb5 {White attacks d4 , and sometimes aims for d6 . Now, taking back on c5 is an option, but pushing in the center is even stronger.} e5 {The idea is to give a pawn in exchange for quick development, and also to chase the knight away with ... a6 while it can't take on d4 .} 8. Nxe5 a6 9. Na3 ({A sad move, but probably the best.} 9. Nd6+ $4 {It's good to know that it is a big blunder.} Bxd6 10. cxd6 Qa5+ {wins a piece for Black. It occurred in two games!}) 9... Bxc5 {Black has the initiative for a pawn, while White has poor development. See here a possible continuation.} (9... O-O {is another possible continuation for Black, even if I prefer the text move, but there is a game I would like to analyze.} 10. g3 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxc5 12. Nd3 Qc6 {and Black is better as in the game that it will be analyzed in the Model Games section: 0-1 Khalifman-Topalov, Dubai 2002.}) *

