to push directly in the center when White hasn't played e3 yet.}) 6... c5 {A direct reaction in the center for Black!} 7. dxc5 Na6 {Black intends to take back on c5 while developing a piece.} 8. e3 Nxc5 {White has several ways to develop now. The most logical is Be2 , but placing a rook on d1 also makes sense.} 9. Be2 dxc4 {White just moved the bishop, which is often a signal to take on c4 .} 10. Bxc4 a6 {Black wants to continue with ... b5 and ... Bb7 , so White should prevent it.} 11. a4 {Since this move weakens b4 , Black is profiting from the inclusion of ... a6 / a4 .} Qa5 12. O-O b6 {Black keeps a solid and active position .} *

