1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. e3 {By far the main move. White protects the center and gets ready to develop the second bishop before castling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taking immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. Bd3 {Developing the bishop is still the main move. White wants to castle next so let's try to prevent this.} Qa5+ {White obviously can't interpose the check with the queen, so White has to move the king or retreat with the knight.} 10. Nd2 {The main move, but engines tend to think the position is already slightly preferable for Black!} Ba6 {Again, Black doesn't want to allow White to castle.} 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black prefers to push ... c5 over preventing the castle.} 12. O-O c5 {Black will bring the rooks into play and has an active position .} *

