1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Qc2 ({In the same spirit as} 7. Nbd2 {, White would like to continue with Nbd2 and e4 , to open up the center.}) 7... b6 {Black prevents the ideas with e4 .} 8. cxd5 {I'm not a big fan of this approach for White. Once this trade is made, it's no longer possibile to play e4 , as it would create a weak d4 -pawn. Also, it opens Black's e-file.} exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Nb5 {The only way to justify 8.cxd5 .} Nc6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 {The best option! Black doesn't want to lose some time with the queen (especially since Bf4 was coming), and gains great control of the central squares. True, the isolated pawns are ugly, but Black will bring a knight to e4 , and chasing it is hard, while taking it undoubles the pawns.} 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Rfe1 a5 {A new move. Black wants to bring the pawn as far as possible, to get new squares for the knight (such as the c4 -square, if White pushes a3 when we play ... a4 )} 14. Rac1 a4 {With the pawn on a4 , Black tries to secure the c4 -square (as b3 would help us get some play on the a-file or b4 -square.} 15. Qd3 Ne4 16. Nd2 Ba6 17. Qe3 Bb7 {A real engine move! The bishop goes back to be able to protect the (possibly future) pawn on e4 . The battle is tense and complicated.} *

