1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. b3 {The last sideline we will check, and a very natural one. White protects the c4 -pawn and intends to develop slowly.} b6 ({My preference, as against many of the sidelines we checked. In opposition to the main line, after} 7... Nc6 8. Bb2 {, Black is unable to react in the center with ... e5 at some point, as it's well-controlled by White.}) 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. Nc3 ({Instead,} 9. Nbd2 {is just a transposition into the 7.Nbd2 move order .}) 9... Nbd7 10. Rc1 Re8 {After some logical developing moves, White has to decide on which plan to adopt. Black is ready for the opening of the position and could be willing to push ... c5 soon.} ({We are not ready for} 10... c5 {yet since after} 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. cxd5 {, White gets the upper hand. Now} exd5 {can be met by} 13. Nh4 {or Nb5 , while Nxd5 Nxd5 Bxd5 b4 Ne4 Qd3⩲ followed by Nh4 is not so much fun either for Black.}) 11. Qc2 Rc8 12. Rfd1 {Here, White tries to anticipate ... c5 and to prevent it. Black can still improve the position and wait for a better occasion.} a6 {Preventing Nb5 .} 13. Nd2 {White can try to push e4 .} Bf8 {Black retreats the bishop first so it won't come under attack. We will push ... c5 soon, and the position is balanced .} *

