1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. e3 {We are not really going to deal with this move here. As soon as White plays Nf3 , it transposes into the chapter about the Colle System.} Be7 {It is best to follow the same pattern as in the lines where White plays e3 on the 5th move, with the bishop already committed on e7 .} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Nge2 {This has been played a bit recently. I don't think it can be very dangerous. White's plan is probably to organize an attack on the kingside or the center (by means of f3 followed with either g4 or e4 , depending on the plan chosen).} b6 {Black prepares ... Bb7 to improve the control over the center.} 8. O-O Bb7 9. Nf4 Re8 10. Qf3 c6 {Black solidly protects the d5 -pawn. On the other hand, Black is no longer playing for ... c5 , but I prefer to be able to develop the knight to d7 , or c7 via a6 .} 11. Qh3 Na6 {Black is reorganizing the pieces, and I don't trust White's attack.} *

