1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. a3 {Not a great move. It obviously prevents ... Bb4 , but such a waste of tempo doesn't justify this.} dxc4 {In modern chess, Black tries to fight for the advantage before even thinking about equality. That's what we can try to achieve with this move. Black could play normally, but that's much more convincing and dangerous for White. Throughout the lines, you will see that I have often chosen variations where Black takes on c4 when it's possible.} 5. e3 {Not very challenging. The position looks like a very bad Queen's Gambit Accepted for White.} c5 6. Bxc4 a6 {Black wants to follow up with ... b5 and ... Bb7 . There is no need to take too early on d4 , I prefer to keep more options alive.} 7. Nf3 b5 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. b4 {Not a very ambitious play, but White keeps equality here (even though with poor scores in practice).} Be7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qb3 Qb8 {The queen is safe from White's rooks here, leaving the b6 -square available to the knight, and sometimes getting ideas of ... e5 or even ... Ng4 , attacking h2 .} 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15. Rac1 Ne5 {The knight on f3 is a good defender, so Black trades it.} 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 ({There are no tactics for White, as} 16... Nd5 {Bxd5 wins immediately, as well as} 17. Nxb5 {Qg5 , that threatens mate.}) *

