1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. a3 {Not a great move. It obviously prevents ... Bb4 , but such a waste of tempo doesn't justify this.} dxc4 {In modern chess, Black tries to fight for the advantage before even thinking about equality. That's what we can try to achieve with this move. Black could play normally, but that's much more convincing and dangerous for White. Throughout the lines, you will see that I have often chosen variations where Black takes on c4 when it's possible.} 5. e3 {Not very challenging. The position looks like a very bad Queen's Gambit Accepted for White.} c5 6. Bxc4 a6 {Black wants to follow up with ... b5 and ... Bb7 . There is no need to take too early on d4 , I prefer to keep more options alive.} 7. Nf3 b5 8. Ba2 {At least from here the bishop doesn't bother any other pieces.} Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {We are probably at the most important position of the 4.a3 line. White has tried several moves; a few of them are interesting, and Black should be careful.} 10. e4 {Almost a new move, but quite interesting! I wouldn't recommend accepting the gift because the opening of the e-file with d4 - d5 , and Re1 at some point, comes fast.} cxd4 (10... Nxe4 $6 {would be inaccurate due to the following sequence:} 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Ng5 $1 {Suddenly, there are several threats, especially toward f7 and e6 .} Bb7 13. d5 e5 14. Re1 c4 15. b3 $1 Be7 16. bxc4 {( h4 instead is also interesting.)} Bxg5 17. c5 {and the engine seems to see very nice compensations for White.}) 11. Nxd4 {The threat e4 - e5 is prevented, and Black can continue development.} Bc5 12. Be3 O-O 13. f3 {The logical move.} Ne5 14. Bf2 {1-0 Hoi-Petursson, Reykjavik 1981.} Nh5 {This would have improved on an old game, enabling Black to get closer to f4 and the white king.} *

