1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. g3 {This is in the spirit of the Catalan, but with Nc3 instead of Nf3 . That makes a big difference, and it enables Black to get a direct reaction in the center.} c5 {It's already hard for White to meet this move.} 5. cxd5 {That's the principled reaction, trying to create an isolated pawn for Black, but we have an intermediate move.} cxd4 {A very similar idea to the Schara-Hennig Gambit, but with g3 and ... Nf6 included. This can only be a better version for Black!} 6. Qxd4 Nc6 {Thanks to the pin, Black gains an important tempo on the queen.} 7. Qa4 exd5 {A great version of an isolated pawn, and ... d4 is coming.} 8. Nf3 {This careless move allows Black to develop a nice initiative.} d4 9. Nb1 Bc5 {The game 0-1 Andersen-Fridman, Helsingor 2011 will be analyzed in the Model Games section.} *

