1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bf4 dxc4 {It's clearly logical in view of the rest of our repertoire against sidelines. Especially with the bishop on f4 , that can fall on the attack of a knight coming to d5 .} 5. e3 ({Clearly the most critical. White would like to get the pawn back and doesn't expose the pawn too far, as in the} 5. e4 {variation.}) 5... c5 {In the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black immediately throws a pawn to the center, while White is focused on the c4 -pawn.} 6. Bxc4 {White allows a good version of an isolated pawn for Black.} cxd4 7. exd4 Bd6 8. Bg5 Nc6 9. Nf3 h6 10. Bh4 g5 {A nice way to get rid of the bishop.} 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 g4 13. Ne5 Qxd4 {White loses a pawn and needs to fight for equality.} *

