1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {. In this first part, we will focus on 3.Nc3 , starting here with the sidelines on move 4.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bf4 dxc4 {It's clearly logical in view of the rest of our repertoire against sidelines. Especially with the bishop on f4 , that can fall on the attack of a knight coming to d5 .} 5. e3 ({Clearly the most critical. White would like to get the pawn back and doesn't expose the pawn too far, as in the} 5. e4 {variation.}) 5... c5 {In the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black immediately throws a pawn to the center, while White is focused on the c4 -pawn.} 6. Nf3 {Solid and secure.} cxd4 (6... Nd5 {is a very logical possibility, as the knight is untouchable (or c4 would be safely protected). But White can keep a slight initiative thanks to a better development with} 7. Bxc4 {and I prefer to avoid that.}) 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 {White is hoping that better development can bring something. But that's not clear how exactly! Now, Black has at least a couple of good options, and the choice will depend on your style.} Nbd7 {The risky choice!} 9. Ndb5 e5 {The right reaction! Black attacks the bishop and shouldn't be afraid of the fork.} 10. Nc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 {I would say this position is quite unlikely to happen, but as it's critical according to the engine, I will add a few ideas.} exf4 {Right now, Black is an exchange down for a pawn, but with decent chances to catch the knight on a8 , or at least to make it a hard task to escape.} 12. Bxc4 fxe3 13. fxe3 Bd6 {Black covers the c7 -square and prepares to get the rook into the game.} 14. O-O Ne5 ({Starting with} 14... Ke7 {is inaccurate, as it gives White time to harass us with} 15. Nb5 {or play Rac1 since now} Ne5 {no longer wins a tempo due to Nd5+ Nxd5} 16. Bd5 {and Black landed in a worse position.}) 15. Bb3 Ke7 {The king finds a safe spot on the semi-open line. If we can move the c8 -bishop and take on a8 , we are winning, so White has to hurry to get counterplay.} 16. Nb5 Bb8 17. Rac1 Bd7 {In all these 'engine lines', it seems that there are different paths to equality. One of them would be the following:} 18. Nac7 Kd8 {Black has to make sure that the white knights cannot retreat. Currently, the knight on c7 still needs to protect b5 so cannot move.} ({After} 18... a6 $2 19. Nd4 {, this is no longer true so White is winning, while} Bc6 {looks possible, but White can keep an edge with} 20. Rf5 {.}) ({The best is} 18... Kd8 {because it immobilizes both knights, escapes from possible knight checks on d5 and threatens ... a6 .}) 19. Rc5 a6 20. Rxe5 axb5 {Thanks to the pin, the knight is lost.} 21. Rxb5 Bxc7 {White will grab b7 , but equal doesn't mean boring, and clearly anything can happen in the endgame. Indeed, the material is slightly in White's favor, but be careful with White once the bishops develop to their best squares! ... Kc8 and ... Re8 will probably follow for Black.} *

