1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Qc2 {In many chapters, we have to check this early possibility of Qc2 . I am not sure it's great because White will continue with Nf3 or e3 anyway, but Black can punish this move.} dxc4 6. e3 c5 {A logical novelty. By answering quickly in the center, the queen might not fit well on c2 ; the c-file is opening, and the knight can arrive quickly at c6 .} 7. Rd1 cxd4 8. Rxd4 Qa5 ({Black gains a tempo on the bishop and threatens to continue with ... b5 . For instance, Nf3} 8... b5 {is much better for Black.}) 9. Rxc4 {White counterattacks on the c8 -bishop.} Nc6 10. Nf3 Bd7 {Black has the safer development, the rook on c4 is awkwardly placed, and Black has no weakness at all. Also, the threat is ... b5 , chasing the rook to a bad square, and getting the c-file back after ... Rc8 .} *

