 have to check this early possibility of Qc2 . I am not sure it's great because White will continue with Nf3 or e3 anyway, but Black can punish this move.} dxc4 6. e3 c5 {A logical novelty. By answering quickly in the center, the queen might not fit well on c2 ; the c-file is opening, and the knight can arrive quickly at c6 .} 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Rd1 {White avoids losing a pawn, but I don't like this development.} Qc7 9. Rxd4 a6 {Black prevent Bb5 and prepares ... b5 .} 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Rd2 b5 12. Be2 Bb7 {In a few moves, Black has caught up with development. The position is relatively symmetrical, but I like the placement of the bishop on b7 . Its diagonal will open soon, and the pawns on the queenside are also more active than White's.} *

