1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. cxd5 ({We are going to check this move in many variations in this chapter. The reason is that if we take back on d5 at some point, Black has failed to transpose into the} 5. cxd5 {chapter. However, now that the dark-squared bishops are looking at each other, it's interesting and safe to take back on d5 with the knight.}) 5... Nxd5 {To my eyes, that's how Black should take advantage. White will have to trade the bishops, which is usually Black's aim.} 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {We are okay to keep the knight on d5 . Here, we are going to have a look only at e4 , because other moves seem slow. Anyway, Black can play similarly (and in some cases, it will be analyzed from different move orders).} 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 ({This position is looking very similar to the Semi-Tarrasch Defense ( cxd5 Nxd5 e4 Nxc3 bxc3} 8... c5 {), but with the dark-squared bishops already traded, it's a better version for Black!}) 9. Bb5+ {Trading even more pieces isn't helping White. Logically, with more space, White should try to keep more pieces on the board.} Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nf3 O-O 12. O-O {This position has been reached in 0-1 Hasman-Shapiro, chess.com 2021, and Black can simply increase his pressure on the center while not taking on d4 yet.} Rfd8 13. Qe2 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Nf6 {Black has less space, obviously, but the position is more solid and White's center is under pressure. If Black manages ... cxd4 followed by ... Qa3 , we will also have good control over the c-file.} *

