1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. cxd5 ({We are going to check this move in many variations in this chapter. The reason is that if we take back on d5 at some point, Black has failed to transpose into the} 5. cxd5 {chapter. However, now that the dark-squared bishops are looking at each other, it's interesting and safe to take back on d5 with the knight.}) 5... Nxd5 {To my eyes, that's how Black should take advantage. White will have to trade the bishops, which is usually Black's aim.} 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {We are okay to keep the knight on d5 . Here, we are going to have a look only at e4 , because other moves seem slow. Anyway, Black can play similarly (and in some cases, it will be analyzed from different move orders).} 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 ({This position is looking very similar to the Semi-Tarrasch Defense ( cxd5 Nxd5 e4 Nxc3 bxc3} 8... c5 {), but with the dark-squared bishops already traded, it's a better version for Black!}) 9. Nf3 O-O {White needs to choose the best square for the bishop. Black's plan will depend on this decision!} 10. Bd3 Nc6 {Now that the bishop is already on d3 protecting e4 , I prefer to put pressure on d4 .} 11. O-O ({Now, we should be careful, Rd8 could be met by} 11. d5 {, with some tactics, such as Bxh7 +, that secure the d5 -pawn.}) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Rd8 13. d5 ({It's hard to find anything else for White, as} 13. Bc2 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 e5 {looks good for Black.}) 13... Nb4 {The knight attacks both the bishop and the pawn on d5 .} 14. Bc4 {This logical-looking move was played once, but it is bad for White.} exd5 15. exd5 Nxd5 {The tactic works for Black because of the pin.} 16. Bxd5 {The logical try is to take it, but White loses the bishop.} Be6 17. Re1 Qf6 {White has no trick anymore and loses the bishop on d5 , while Black ends up with an extra pawn and an amazing bishop.} *

