milar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. cxd5 ({We are going to check this move in many variations in this chapter. The reason is that if we take back on d5 at some point, Black has failed to transpose into the} 5. cxd5 {chapter. However, now that the dark-squared bishops are looking at each other, it's interesting and safe to take back on d5 with the knight.}) 5... Nxd5 {To my eyes, that's how Black should take advantage. White will have to trade the bishops, which is usually Black's aim.} 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {We are okay to keep the knight on d5 . Here, we are going to have a look only at e4 , because other moves seem slow. Anyway, Black can play similarly (and in some cases, it will be analyzed from different move orders).} 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 ({This position is looking very similar to the Semi-Tarrasch Defense ( cxd5 Nxd5 e4 Nxc3 bxc3} 8... c5 {), but with the dark-squared bishops already traded, it's a better version for Black!}) 9. Nf3 O-O {White needs to choose the best square for the bishop. Black's plan will depend on this decision!} 10. Bd3 Nc6 {Now that the bishop is already on d3 protecting e4 , I prefer to put pressure on d4 .} 11. O-O ({Now, we should be careful, Rd8 could be met by} 11. d5 {, with some tactics, such as Bxh7 +, that secure the d5 -pawn.}) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Rd8 13. d5 ({It's hard to find anything else for White, as} 13. Bc2 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 e5 {looks good for Black.}) 13... Nb4 {The knight attacks both the bishop and the pawn on d5 .} 14. Re1 {The only way to keep the balance.} Nxd3 15. Qxd3 exd5 16. exd5 Qd6 {The threat will quickly become ... Be6 . Black should just need to be careful about Ng5 , but we will have time to prevent this with ... h6 . I don't think the pawn on d5 is a real danger, the position is equal.} *

