eck this move in many variations in this chapter. The reason is that if we take back on d5 at some point, Black has failed to transpose into the} 5. cxd5 {chapter. However, now that the dark-squared bishops are looking at each other, it's interesting and safe to take back on d5 with the knight.}) 5... exd5 {However, if you prefer to keep playing in the spirit of the chapter where White takes on d5 on move 4, you can also take back with the pawn, and the position is very likely to transpose. There are just sidelines with Qc2 , which will be different.} 6. e3 h6 {Also here, White could take on f6 , leading to slightly different positions than in the corresponding chapter.} 7. Bh4 c6 {Finally, we transposed .} *

