1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Nf3 ({A very important line. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bxf6 ({Clearly less popular than} 6. Bh4 {, but it sometimes contains some venom when White comes with aggressive plans, such as O-O-O .}) 6... Bxf6 ({Now, in case of e3 (which is the most played move), this transposes into e3 h6} 6... Bxf6 {that we will analyze later. Instead, we deal here with the early alternatives.}) 7. Qc2 {White prepares O-O-O and also keeps the option of playing e4 at some point to open the center.} O-O 8. O-O-O c5 {There is no time to waste. Black opens the center but also the diagonal of the f6 -bishop, directly targeting the white king.} 9. dxc5 Na6 {Almost a novelty, it has been played only once! Black wants to take back with the knight and doesn't really care about the d5 -pawn. White more or less needs to take it, but that means no more attacks, as some files will open in front of the king.} 10. cxd5 Nxc5 ({Again, Black doesn't seem to care about the center and is giving up another pawn on e6 with tempo on the queen! In case of Kb1} 10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 {Ne4 followed by ... exd5 is better for Black!}) 11. dxe6 Qe8 {That's really a deep engine idea. White should better not take another pawn on f7 , otherwise, Black's activity becomes too powerful.} 12. exf7+ {A bad idea because it accelerates our counterplay.} Rxf7 {The rook can quickly reach c7 if necessary, to attack the king on c1 . White should try to develop quickly.} 13. e3 Bxc3 {The idea is to be able to quickly bring the bishop into play.} 14. Qxc3 Be6 {Black protects the knight on c5 thanks to the ... Rc8 pin. Also the pawn on a2 is hanging, so bringing the king to b1 seems most logical.} ({Instead, Bc4 loses on the spot due to} 14... Ne4 {followed by ... Bxc4 , winning a piece.}) 15. Kb1 ({Logical, but probably another bad attempt. Instead, White should try to give the queen for some material with} 15. Qxc5 {, but Black is better anyway.}) 15... Ne4 16. Qc2 Rc8 17. Qe2 Qa4 {There's way too much pressure to handle for White, who will get mated soon.} *

