ne. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bxf6 ({Clearly less popular than} 6. Bh4 {, but it sometimes contains some venom when White comes with aggressive plans, such as O-O-O .}) 6... Bxf6 ({Now, in case of e3 (which is the most played move), this transposes into e3 h6} 6... Bxf6 {that we will analyze later. Instead, we deal here with the early alternatives.}) 7. Qc2 {White prepares O-O-O and also keeps the option of playing e4 at some point to open the center.} O-O 8. O-O-O c5 {There is no time to waste. Black opens the center but also the diagonal of the f6 -bishop, directly targeting the white king.} 9. dxc5 Na6 {Almost a novelty, it has been played only once! Black wants to take back with the knight and doesn't really care about the d5 -pawn. White more or less needs to take it, but that means no more attacks, as some files will open in front of the king.} 10. cxd5 Nxc5 ({Again, Black doesn't seem to care about the center and is giving up another pawn on e6 with tempo on the queen! In case of Kb1} 10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 {Ne4 followed by ... exd5 is better for Black!}) 11. dxe6 Qe8 {That's really a deep engine idea. White should better not take another pawn on f7 , otherwise, Black's activity becomes too powerful.} 12. e7 {White attracts the queen to e7 to follow with a fork on d5 .} Qxe7 13. Nd5 Qe4 {The right square for the queen. It's a very hard move, as White has many options, and the knight on c5 is hanging.} 14. Nxf6+ {A logical intermediate move.} gxf6 15. Nd4 ({One of the few moves that holds for White. Instead,} 15. Qxc5 Bf5 {is winning for Black due to the many threats such as ... Rac8 and ... Qb1 +, or sometimes ... Qc2 with mate!}) 15... Rd8 16. e3 Bg4 {Black accelerates the development of the a8 -rook. Trading queens is complicated, as the knight would immediately threaten to take on f2 . The position is complicated but roughly balanced.} *

