ne. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bxf6 ({Clearly less popular than} 6. Bh4 {, but it sometimes contains some venom when White comes with aggressive plans, such as O-O-O .}) 6... Bxf6 ({Now, in case of e3 (which is the most played move), this transposes into e3 h6} 6... Bxf6 {that we will analyze later. Instead, we deal here with the early alternatives.}) 7. cxd5 {This move decides the structure of the center; it becomes harder for Black to react there, but easier to develop the c8 -bishop.} exd5 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 {Definitely the main line, and a logical developing move, but Black has a strong reaction available.} c5 10. dxc5 Bxc3+ {This makes things clear, Black will fight for the pawn structure and prevents any idea of Na4 . The pawn on c5 has no chance of survival.} 11. bxc3 Nd7 {One way or another, Black gets the pawn back. For instance:} 12. O-O Nxc5 13. Bc2 b6 {The plan is not to do a fianchetto, the bishop would be stuck on b7 . Instead, it will probably reach e6 or a6 , but the real idea is simply to stabilize the knight on c5 .} *

