It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Nf3 ({A very important line. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bh4 {There is no need to argue, this is the main line for White, who doesn't want to release the pressure.} O-O {Now, in case of the usual e3 , this is a transposition into the other main line, starting with 5.e3 . So we will only look at secondary possibilities.} 7. Rc1 {Often a useful move, as the c-file is going to open at some point.} b6 {The Tartakower System will be our choice against most of White's move orders. Now, again, it case of e3 Bb7 , we transpose to the main variation.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {As usual in the chapter, you will realize that we want to take back with the pawn on d5 , as White delayed cxd5 , now that the dark-squared bishop can be traded.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 *

