1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Nf3 ({A very important line. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bh4 {There is no need to argue, this is the main line for White, who doesn't want to release the pressure.} O-O {Now, in case of the usual e3 , this is a transposition into the other main line, starting with 5.e3 . So we will only look at secondary possibilities.} 7. Qc2 ({Also a useful waiting move that we are going to meet in the same way as} 7. Rc1 {.}) 7... b6 {There is no reason to wait before bringing the bishop to b7 .} 8. cxd5 ({Instead,} 8. e3 {will be analyzed in the main line with Qc2 .}) 8... Nxd5 {Black trades the minor pieces.} 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Rc1 {White tries to put immediate pressure on the c-pawn and hopes that will prevent us from pushing it. But as White is far from securing the king, we are glad to open the center.} c5 {It's hard not to take it, otherwise, the pawn goes even further, with a nice initiative on the queenside.} 12. dxc5 Bg4 {A nice move. Black sacrifices a pawn, but it's not so realistic for White to take it. cxb6 axb6 , and Black attacks the a2 -pawn as well as getting ideas such as ... Rc8 or ... Qb4 +. White's king isn't safe.} 13. e3 Bxf3 {Damaging White's kingside for a long time.} 14. gxf3 Rc8 {Black manages to get the pawn back.} 15. Qd2 Rxc5 16. Rxc5 Qxc5 17. Bg2 Nd7 {Black brings the knight to f6 in order to secure the d5 -pawn.} 18. O-O Rc8 19. Rd1 Nf6 {The game ½-½ Onischuk-Akobian, Saint Louis 2016 ended in a draw. The position is equal, as Black will intrude on c2 soon, not leaving White with the option to quietly attack the d5 -pawn.} *

