1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. Nf3 ({A very important line. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bh4 {There is no need to argue, this is the main line for White, who doesn't want to release the pressure.} O-O {Now, in case of the usual e3 , this is a transposition into the other main line, starting with 5.e3 . So we will only look at secondary possibilities.} 7. cxd5 {White can also decide to take now on d5 . As usual, when this happens so late, Black can take back with the knight to simplify the position.} Nxd5 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 ({Now, once again, Nxd5 exd5 e3} 8... b6 {can lead to the main line of the chapter, but Black also has other options than b6 now that is already free to develop the light-squared bishop. Instead, we will look at some of White's other options.}) 9. g3 {In the spirit of the Catalan, White tries to bring the bishop on the long diagonal. Unfortunately, Black can simply do the same.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 {Before White fianchettoes on g2 , Black should get ready to fianchetto on b7 .} 11. Bg2 Bb7 12. O-O {Now, Black plans to organize some counterplay in the center, especially against d4 !} Rd8 13. Qa4 Nd7 14. e3 c5 {I don't really see how White can use the extra pawn in the center, there isn't any target in Black's camp.} 15. Rfd1 Nf6 {Finally, the knight comes to control the light squares too. Black's plan could be to organize an expansion on the queenside with ... a6 , ... b5 , and then be able to bring the second rook to c8 . Black won in 0-1 Sarana-Sargissian, chess.com 2019.} *

