ne. It can also happen via other move orders, such as Nc3 Nf6} 5. Nf3 {Be7 Bg5 . We are going to deeply analyze this line, and it's also important to understand that it can often transpose into the lines with e3 . And when a transposition occurs, we will have a look at it via 5.e3 .}) 5... h6 ({Similarly to a latter chapter, I like to start immediately with ...h6 . I would say it's slightly more accurate to do it straight away, at least Black knows exactly how White will react to the attack. If you compare with} 5... O-O {, Black doesn't show the place of the king immediately.}) {Also, let's mention that there is no real need to analyze Bf4 , it's just a transposition to the chapter on Bf4 , with ... h6 already played, and that's a better version for Black. Black can play similarly.} 6. Bh4 {There is no need to argue, this is the main line for White, who doesn't want to release the pressure.} O-O {Now, in case of the usual e3 , this is a transposition into the other main line, starting with 5.e3 . So we will only look at secondary possibilities.} 7. cxd5 {White can also decide to take now on d5 . As usual, when this happens so late, Black can take back with the knight to simplify the position.} Nxd5 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 ({Now, once again, Nxd5 exd5 e3} 8... b6 {can lead to the main line of the chapter, but Black also has other options than b6 now that is already free to develop the light-squared bishop. Instead, we will look at some of White's other options.}) 9. Qb3 {White tries to provoke ... Nxc3 , but there is no rush. White can't really take twice on d5 anyway because of the ... Qb4 +possibilities.} c5 {A nice reaction on the center.} 10. e3 {This looks logical but is in fact quite passive.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6 {The bishop comes to b7 and will dominate the position.} *

