1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bf4 {I don't think this can be great for White, as ... h6 is often a useful move for Black.} O-O 7. Nf3 ({The most usual move. And even in other lines, it's difficult to play without this move soon. It means the position is identical to the chapter on} 7. Nf3 {Nf6 Nc3 Be7 Bf4 , except that Black already has played ... h6 . Can this be only an advantage for Black?}) 7... c5 ({The answer is no, or at least, not as in the line we will play in the aforementioned chapter! If we play similarly,} 7... b6 {, then White has the strong reply} 8. g4 $1 {, using the fact that the pawn on h6 helps White open the g-file with g5 coming. Also, after} Nxg4 9. Rg1 Nf6 {, White has} 10. Bxh6 {.}) ({So White scores well with 8.g4 , and we should avoid this. Instead, if we play} 7... c5 {, Black transposes to the variation where ... h6 is super useful, and we often play this move sooner or later.}) 8. cxd5 {The problem of this move is that it's opening the diagonal in front of White's king when the knights are traded, so it's too dangerous for White.} Nxd5 {We don't let White force an isolated pawn on d5 , we take back with pieces!} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The threat is now ... cxd4 followed by ... Bb4 +.} 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. a3 {A sad necessity. Black's threat was ... Qa5 +, and now it can be answered with b4 . Obviously, the problem is the slowness of this move.} Rd8 12. Qc1 {Probably best, in order to try to release the tension, but we won't accept so easily.} Qf5 {There is no reason for Black to trade queens. While White will castle, Black can quickly develop with ... Bd7 , ... Nc6 , and ... Rac8 .} *

