e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bf4 {I don't think this can be great for White, as ... h6 is often a useful move for Black.} O-O 7. Nf3 ({The most usual move. And even in other lines, it's difficult to play without this move soon. It means the position is identical to the chapter on} 7. Nf3 {Nf6 Nc3 Be7 Bf4 , except that Black already has played ... h6 . Can this be only an advantage for Black?}) 7... c5 ({The answer is no, or at least, not as in the line we will play in the aforementioned chapter! If we play similarly,} 7... b6 {, then White has the strong reply} 8. g4 $1 {, using the fact that the pawn on h6 helps White open the g-file with g5 coming. Also, after} Nxg4 9. Rg1 Nf6 {, White has} 10. Bxh6 {.}) ({So White scores well with 8.g4 , and we should avoid this. Instead, if we play} 7... c5 {, Black transposes to the variation where ... h6 is super useful, and we often play this move sooner or later.}) 8. dxc5 {The main line in the same position without ... h6 , and also the best move here, probably.} Bxc5 9. a3 {White prepares b4 , but we can allow it and instead, develop quickly.} Nc6 10. b4 Be7 11. Be2 dxc4 {As usual, when the bishop moves, it's the right time to take on c4 .} 12. Bxc4 Nh5 {The bishop on f4 has to accept the trade against a knight, and this frees the f6 -square for the bishop at some point.} 13. Bg3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Qc7 {Black threatens ... Nxb4  (because the bishop is hanging on c4 ), or ... Rd8 .} 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. O-O Rd8 17. Qc2 a6 {Black chases the knight and will be able to develop the bishop soon, on d7 or b7 after ... b5 .} *

