f3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bf4 {I don't think this can be great for White, as ... h6 is often a useful move for Black.} O-O 7. Nf3 ({The most usual move. And even in other lines, it's difficult to play without this move soon. It means the position is identical to the chapter on} 7. Nf3 {Nf6 Nc3 Be7 Bf4 , except that Black already has played ... h6 . Can this be only an advantage for Black?}) 7... c5 ({The answer is no, or at least, not as in the line we will play in the aforementioned chapter! If we play similarly,} 7... b6 {, then White has the strong reply} 8. g4 $1 {, using the fact that the pawn on h6 helps White open the g-file with g5 coming. Also, after} Nxg4 9. Rg1 Nf6 {, White has} 10. Bxh6 {.}) ({So White scores well with 8.g4 , and we should avoid this. Instead, if we play} 7... c5 {, Black transposes to the variation where ... h6 is super useful, and we often play this move sooner or later.}) 8. dxc5 {The main line in the same position without ... h6 , and also the best move here, probably.} Bxc5 9. Qc2 {White keeps the option to castle on the queenside and also actively waits to develop the f1 -bishop. So ... dxc4 isn't so appealing anymore.} Nc6 10. a3 Qa5 {This position is well-known with the pawn on h7 . We will soon see the big difference it makes!} 11. O-O-O {White solves the problem of the pinned knight, but it's dangerous to have the king on the queenside. Black should open the files in front of the white king.} dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxa3 {A concrete sacrifice.} 13. bxa3 e5 {This intermediate move enables Black to develop the c8 -bishop. White has no choice but to retreat with the bishop.} 14. Bg3 Qxa3+ 15. Qb2 Qc5 {Black has great compensation. I think White should settle for a repetition after:} 16. Qb5 Qa3+ *

