e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bf4 {I don't think this can be great for White, as ... h6 is often a useful move for Black.} O-O 7. Nf3 ({The most usual move. And even in other lines, it's difficult to play without this move soon. It means the position is identical to the chapter on} 7. Nf3 {Nf6 Nc3 Be7 Bf4 , except that Black already has played ... h6 . Can this be only an advantage for Black?}) 7... c5 ({The answer is no, or at least, not as in the line we will play in the aforementioned chapter! If we play similarly,} 7... b6 {, then White has the strong reply} 8. g4 $1 {, using the fact that the pawn on h6 helps White open the g-file with g5 coming. Also, after} Nxg4 9. Rg1 Nf6 {, White has} 10. Bxh6 {.}) ({So White scores well with 8.g4 , and we should avoid this. Instead, if we play} 7... c5 {, Black transposes to the variation where ... h6 is super useful, and we often play this move sooner or later.}) 8. dxc5 {The main line in the same position without ... h6 , and also the best move here, probably.} Bxc5 9. cxd5 {White creates an isolated pawn on d5 and will try to play against it.} Nxd5 {Trading the knights enables Black to threaten ... Bb4 + or ... Qa5 +.} 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 {If White doesn't care about ... Bb4 +, Black tries to get rid of the weak pawn.} Bb4+ 12. Nd2 d4 {The only ambitious option is to keep the pawns on the board.} 13. e4 Nc6 14. O-O f5 {Black immediately fights back in the center as in 0-1 Kockum-Ostlund, Tylosand 2023. It seems obvious that the pawn on d4 is more a strength than a weakness, now that it's passed and well-protected.} *

