e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Bd3 dxc4 {Black can open the position.} 9. Bxc4 c5 {It's clear that the bishop on f6 is now feeling better, as the long diagonal is about to open.} 10. dxc5 Nd7 {If Black simply gets the pawn back, for sure we have no problem.} 11. c6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 bxc6 {Black continues with ... Nb6 , ... c5 , and ... Bb7 , with a very active position.} *

