e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Qb3 {White puts pressure on the d5 -pawn. So either we protect it with ... c6 , which is a bit passive, or we trade to open the center even if White didn't spend a tempo moving the bishop.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 {I prefer the active option. The queen on b3 is useful, it protects the knight on c3 and leaves the d1 -square to the rook, but it's also sometimes exposed.} 10. dxc5 Nd7 {Black uses the placement of the queen on b3 .} 11. Qa3 Qc7 12. b4 a5 {It's too optimistic to believe that White will keep the extra pawn, as the queenside is just too weak.} 13. Nd4 Rb8 {A necessary move since the pawn on a5 was pinned.} 14. O-O axb4 15. Qxb4 Qxc5 {Black trades queens and has a safe position.} *

