1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Qc2 ({Slightly similar to} 8. Qb3 {− the queen is less exposed but also doesn't put any pressure against d5 . We can open the center while not taking first on c4 (so, we don't ease the development of the bishop on f1 ).}) 8... c5 {Before White castles or organizes anything, Black wants to open the center.} 9. O-O-O {White's king is far from being safe here, while the files are easy to open for Black.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {I prefer to keep the pawn on c4 as long as possible, not to help the bishop on f1 to develop.} 11. h4 {White can try a direct attack but here is how we prevent anything.} g6 12. g4 Bg7 {Black can close the kingside if White pushes any pawn. I don't see how White will continue the attack, especially since the dark-squared bishop left the premises a long time ago.} 13. Kb1 Bd7 {Black prepares ... Rc8 and has a nice initiative.} *

