e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Qc2 ({Slightly similar to} 8. Qb3 {− the queen is less exposed but also doesn't put any pressure against d5 . We can open the center while not taking first on c4 (so, we don't ease the development of the bishop on f1 ).}) 8... c5 {Before White castles or organizes anything, Black wants to open the center.} 9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 {Black also wants to get the pawn back. Then, ... Qa5 can help if necessary, but I think White's best chance is to weaken our queenside.} 11. c6 bxc6 12. O-O Rb8 {As against, Qb3 , Black develops quickly.} 13. Rfd1 Qb6 14. b3 Rd8 15. Rac1 c5 {Black activates and opens the diagonal for the c8 -bishop.} 16. Be2 Bb7 ({Black has enough activity to compensate for the isolated c-pawn. Na4 is not something we should worry about since after} 16... Qa5 {, White cannot grab the pawn on c5 , as that would yield Black a preferable position due to the hanging pawn on a2 at the end of the line.}) *

