e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Qd2 {Here, White keeps the pressure on the d-pawn, and it can be a problem if we start immediately with ... c5 . So, I prefer to take on c4 first.} dxc4 {First, we trade pawns, and then we open the center.} 9. Bxc4 c5 {The usual follow-up.} 10. dxc5 {White fully opens the position. As we already saw, the best is to try to get the pawn back with the knight.} Nd7 11. Ne4 Be7 ({Now, White isn't able to protect the pawn with b4 because of} 11... a5 {.}) 12. O-O {Logical too, but it trades many pieces.} Nxc5 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Rfd1 Qxd2 15. Rxd2 Be7 {The endgame is equal; Black will try to slowly bring the rooks into play. If ... Rd8 isn't allowed, we can start with ... Bf6 , ... b6 , and ... Bb7 .} *

