e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't want to spend any time moving the bishop away. I am not a big fan of this option for White, as the opening of the position will now favor Black thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxf6 7. Nf3 ({Starting with} 7. Rc1 {makes no difference, as after} O-O {, there is no other real option than} 8. Nf3 {.}) 7... O-O {This position could have been reached in this chapter via Nf3 h6 Bxf6 . White has tried several moves here.} 8. Rc1 {This time White brings another rook into play, instead of trying to improve the queen. I think it's a better idea, and it's not curious that it's the main line.} c6 {For now, Black doesn't decide what the c-pawn will do in the future. We protect the center but can still push ... c5 later (it's not necessarily a loss of time because White will have to develop the bishop at some point, before taking back on c4 ).} (8... dxc4 {, I don't like this option anymore. After} 9. Bxc4 c5 10. dxc5 Qa5 11. O-O Nd7 12. Be2 {, White would remain slightly better, with nice chances to push a3 and b4 on the queenside. However, it's also playable for Black.}) 9. Bd3 {White develops most logically.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 11. O-O {This position has been reached many times. Black can choose whether to break with ... c5 or ... e5 .} c5 {Clearly less played, but employed regularly by Hikaru Nakamura. Black aims for a symmetrical pawn structure.} (11... e5 {is the main option for Black, and it's also solid. After} 12. d5 Nb6 13. b3 cxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxc4 15. bxc4 {, the position is equal but slightly easier to play for White, who won in 1-0 Radjabov-So, chess24.com 2021.}) 12. Qe2 {This allows Black to force an isolated pawn.} cxd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bd3 g6 {Black prepares ... Bg7 against Ne4 .} 15. Be4 {Black would like to play ... Bd7 but should first protect the pawn on b7 .} Rb8 16. Rfd1 Bd7 17. Ne5 ({Pushing} 17. d5 {leads nowhere, Black can trade and follow with ... Re8 .}) 17... Qe7 18. Qf3 Be8 {It's clear that Black plays slowly, as we need some time to organize. Right now, we protect the g6 -pawn.} 19. g3 Bg7 20. h4 h5 {White doesn't have a threat. In the game ½-½ Radjabov-So, chess24.com 2021, Black brought the knight to c8 and d6 , to reach f5 at some point, and was fine.} *

