e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. cxd5 {Black hasn't even played ... b6 yet, so this can't be dangerous. The right decision is again to trade some pieces.} Nxd5 {Trading a few pieces before eventually taking back with the pawn.} 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Nxd5 exd5 {Black has sometimes the possibility to annoy White on the queenside with ... Qb4 +.} 10. Bd3 ({In case of} 10. Nf3 b6 {, we transpose back into the main line , but Black can also develop the bishop directly to g4 , with a good position.}) 10... c5 {Before White has castled, we should immediately try to seek active counterplay.} 11. Ne2 (11. Nf3 {instead doesn't change much since after} c4 {, White keeps having the same issues as in the main line.}) 11... c4 {Black expands on the queenside.} 12. Bc2 Nc6 13. O-O Bg4 {Black threatens ... Bxe2 followed by ... Nxd4 . White lacks activity, and the long-term plan for Black is to push all the pawns on the queenside, and at some point create a passed pawn.} *

