e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Rc1 b6 {In the same spirit as the main line, Black wants to bring the bishop to b7 .} 8. Bxf6 {Slightly illogical now that White has already played Bh4 a few moves earlier. But the idea is concrete: now that Black has played ... b6 , White wants to force us into a position where we keep a pawn on d5 .} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Qf3 ({Instead, after} 10. Nf3 Bb7 {, see the main line with Rc1 .}) 10... Bb7 11. Bc4 {White forces ... c6 .} c6 12. Bb3 Na6 {The knight heads toward e6 .} 13. Nge2 Nc7 14. O-O Ne6 {Black attacks the d4 -pawn, which prevents e3 - e4 . We will bring the rook into play, and then we might bring the knight to g5 and e4 .} *

