e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Rc1 b6 {In the same spirit as the main line, Black wants to bring the bishop to b7 .} 8. Bxf6 {Slightly illogical now that White has already played Bh4 a few moves earlier. But the idea is concrete: now that Black has played ... b6 , White wants to force us into a position where we keep a pawn on d5 .} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Qf3 ({Instead, after} 10. Nf3 Bb7 {, see the main line with Rc1 .}) 10... Bb7 11. Bd3 c5 12. Nge2 {Be careful here, you can't push ... c4 because the bishop takes on c4 and uses the pin on the d5 -pawn.} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 {Black wants to fix the structure and bring the knight to attack d4 .} 14. exd4 Nc6 {It gains a tempo on the d4 -pawn.} 15. Qf5 {White tries to weaken our kingside.} g6 16. Qf4 Re8+ 17. Kd1 Kg7 {The king is relatively safe on d1 . White has the better bishop, but with the king on d1 , White can't dream of an advantage.} ({Against moves like Nb5 , threatening Nd6 or Nc7 , or attacking attempts such as h4 , Black can rely on} 17... Re6 {followed by ... Rf6 or ... Qf6 , when d4 and f2 would be hanging after the queen trade.}) *

