e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Rc1 b6 {In the same spirit as the main line, Black wants to bring the bishop to b7 .} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 {Don't be tempted to take on h4 , because c7 is hanging.} exd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bd3 ({Instead,} 11. Nf3 Be6 {is a transposition to the main line .}) 11... c5 {Black goes for the hanging pair of pawns in the center. Our activity will be enough to compensate for this relative weakness.} 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Ne2 Nd7 {Black's plan is easy: developing the pieces while protecting the pawns.} 14. O-O Bb7 15. Ng3 Rfd8 {A new move (so logical) in the position. If White pushes b3 , to prevent the c-pawn from advancing, Black will push the a-pawn to weaken the b3 -pawn. Another plan can be to bring the knight to e4 and try to push ... d4 at the right moment, to open the position.} *

