e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Rc1 b6 {In the same spirit as the main line, Black wants to bring the bishop to b7 .} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 {Don't be tempted to take on h4 , because c7 is hanging.} exd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bd3 ({Instead,} 11. Nf3 Be6 {is a transposition to the main line .}) 11... c5 {Black goes for the hanging pair of pawns in the center. Our activity will be enough to compensate for this relative weakness.} 12. Ne2 {From here, the knight will be capable of attacking the d5 -pawn soon, that's the difference with Nf3 .} c4 {Black clarifies the situation in the center. This is justified because it's going to be tough for White to play e3 - e4 , while Black has the long-term plan of pushing the queenside pawn majority with ... b5 - b4 .} 13. Bb1 Nd7 {The knight comes to protect d5 as well as the h7 -square.} 14. O-O Nf6 15. Nc3 Rb8 {Black prepares the advance of the queenside. White can't prevent it because a4 and ... a6 only help Black open some files there.} 16. Re1 b5 17. f3 b4 18. Na4 Rd8 {Black temporarily allows the knight to come to c5 , but it would be easy to trade it with ... Nd7 . Black has the more pleasant game, even if anything can happen in these double-edged positions.} *

