1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Qc2 {As often, this is a useful move, but only with a low independent value because of the transpositions.} b6 {Here, the best is probably to return to the main line with Nf3 because the main alternative isn't great.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Rc1 {That's not great, White should develop the kingside instead.} c5 {No need to passively protect the pawn, Black opens up the center.} 12. dxc5 d4 {A strong intermediate move. The threat on e3 prevents White from continuing the frenzy with the c-pawn.} 13. Nf3 dxe3 14. Be2 {This occurred in the game ½-½ Pesorda-Steflitsch, Austria 2010, and now Black should have simply taken the pawn on f2 .} exf2+ {It's strange that Black didn't opt for this move in the game, as it seems so natural.} 15. Kxf2 Nd7 {... Nxc5 should be allowed, with a great position for Black, if White doesn't want to have something even worse.} 16. cxb6 (16. c6 {doesn't help either because of the same} Nf6 {, when Black's initiative is crushing.}) 16... Nf6 {The threats of ... Ng4 + followed by ... Qe3 are too dangerous, Black is winning.} *

