1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Bxf6 {We have already checked a few similar occurrences of this trade. Black is willing to take back on f6 with the bishop.} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 ({Now, Qb3} 9... Bb7 {or} 10. Rc1 {Bb7 would transpose to the variations of 8.Qb3 and 8.Rc1 respectively. But Black can also try to take advantage of White’s move order by playing Be6 instead, with a nice position anyway.}) 10. Be2 {The bishop is probably less active here than on d3 .} Be6 {With the pawn already on d5 , I would rather avoid placing the bishop on b7 , on a blocked diagonal. But be reassured, the ... b6 move won’t remain useless, as it will help us push ... c5 soon.} 11. O-O c5 {Black develops play in the center.} 12. Rc1 Nc6 {Black would be glad to reach a hanging pair of pawns in the center, which would prove to be very active, with quick options of ... d4 for Black.} 13. Qa4 cxd4 14. exd4 {The position is now symmetrical in the center.} Qd6 15. Bb5 Nb4 {Black intends ... a6 on the next move no matter what!} 16. a3 a6 17. axb4 axb5 18. Qxb5 Rfc8 {Black has temporarily lost a pawn, but the pawn on b4 is in bad shape, and it should be easy to take it back by chasing the queen or with ... Be7 .} *

