e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Bxf6 {We have already checked a few similar occurrences of this trade. Black is willing to take back on f6 with the bishop.} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 ({Now, Qb3} 9... Bb7 {or} 10. Rc1 {Bb7 would transpose to the variations of 8.Qb3 and 8.Rc1 respectively. But Black can also try to take advantage of White’s move order by playing Be6 instead, with a nice position anyway.}) 10. Bd3 c5 11. dxc5 {If Black takes back immediately on c5 , then we lose the d5 -pawn.} Bxc3+ {That's why we need to get rid of the knight. It also weakens White's queenside.} 12. bxc3 bxc5 13. O-O Nd7 14. c4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Qe7 {Black ends up with an isolated pawn on c5 , but that provides us some play, and it's not easy for White to attack it.} *

