1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Qb3 {White targets the d5 -pawn. It's the start of a plan where White prevents ... c5 .} Bb7 9. Bxf6 ({White clarifies the center. If White develops the bishop instead, it's okay to take on c4 :} 9. Be2 dxc4 {.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {Again, ... c5 has been prevented, but it is not so easy to come up with a plan for White.} Re8 12. Be2 c6 {Black reinforces the center and frees the c7 -square for the knight after a potential ... Na6 - c7 - e6 maneuver.} 13. O-O Na6 {I like this follow-up, Black brings the knight to c7 . This is more accurate than the other route to e6 via d7 and f8 , which hands White the option of Rfe1 followed by e4 .} ({To illustrate that, after} 13... Nd7 14. Rfe1 Nf8 15. e4 {, Black cannot play} dxe4 $2 {due to} 16. Bc4 $1 exf3 17. Bxf7+ Kh8 18. Rxe8 {. In the same variation but with the knight on c7 instead, the rook on e8 would be protected, so White has to find a different plan altogether. Small nuances, big differences!}) 14. Rfe1 Nc7 15. Bf1 {White is preparing e4 and has great activity in the center.} Ne6 {The knight controls the center, and it can reach g5 to be traded.} 16. e4 dxe4 17. Rxe4 Ng5 {Black trades some pieces and keeps a solid position; ... c5 will come sooner or later to open the long diagonal.} *

