e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Qc2 ({This is similar to} 8. Qb3 {or Rc1 , White waits before developing the f1 -bishop.}) 8... Bb7 9. cxd5 {That's a common imprecise move. Black easily solves the problems here and can keep the long diagonal open.} Nxd5 {Again, not allowing White to close our diagonal for the light-squared bishop.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Be2 c5 {Here too, there is no reason to wait any longer; ... Rc8 will always enable Black to take back, with a good pawn structure.} 13. dxc5 Rc8 ({White isn't able to protect the pawn with b4 because of} 13... a5 {and the b4 -pawn is in trouble while Black activates the a8 -rook too. Obviously,} 14. a3 {axb4 doesn't help since the rook is hanging on a1 .}) *

