1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Qc2 ({This is similar to} 8. Qb3 {or Rc1 , White waits before developing the f1 -bishop.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop pair to eliminate the defender of the d5 -pawn. After a subsequent cxd5 , we are forced to recapture with the pawn, when White hopes to get attacking ideas following O-O-O or g4 .} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {In case of slow play from White, say Be2 followed by O-O , we can confidently enter the hanging pawns structure with the natural moves ... Qe7 and ... c5 .} ({A sample line is Be2} 10... Qe7 {O-O c5 , and if White keeps the tension with Rfd1 Rd8} 11. Rc1 {, we have options. We can either play} Nd7 {and enter a favorable isolated pawn position after dxc5 Nxc5 , or we can add more pressure on d4 with Nc6 since dxc5 d4! exd4 Nxd4 Nxd4 Bxd4 cxb6 Bxb6 yields Black enough compensation for the pawn due to the open position and strong bishop pair.}) 11. O-O-O ({This attacking move has been played more than 300 times! Instead,} 11. g4 {leads to the variation after} c5 12. O-O-O {.}) 11... c5 {Now that Black has castled, it's logical to open the c-file even if the center isn't entirely protected.} 12. dxc5 {White tries to use the pressure on the d-file thanks to the rook on d1 . But Black can also open a file that will help us get the initiative.} Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Nd7 {Black brings the rook into play, ... Rc8 will be the next move in most cases.} 14. c6 Bxc6 ({The bishop is taboo: Qxc6} 14... Rc8 {and the queen drops.}) 15. Kb1 Rc8 16. Qd4 {You may think that White is better thanks to the d4 -square, but it's not going to last very long.} Nc5 17. Bd3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qf6 {White can't move the knight because of the pawn on f2 . It seems that Black's king is safer here.} *

