e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Qc2 ({This is similar to} 8. Qb3 {or Rc1 , White waits before developing the f1 -bishop.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop pair to eliminate the defender of the d5 -pawn. After a subsequent cxd5 , we are forced to recapture with the pawn, when White hopes to get attacking ideas following O-O-O or g4 .} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {In case of slow play from White, say Be2 followed by O-O , we can confidently enter the hanging pawns structure with the natural moves ... Qe7 and ... c5 .} ({A sample line is Be2} 10... Qe7 {O-O c5 , and if White keeps the tension with Rfd1 Rd8} 11. Rc1 {, we have options. We can either play} Nd7 {and enter a favorable isolated pawn position after dxc5 Nxc5 , or we can add more pressure on d4 with Nc6 since dxc5 d4! exd4 Nxd4 Nxd4 Bxd4 cxb6 Bxb6 yields Black enough compensation for the pawn due to the open position and strong bishop pair.}) 11. O-O-O ({This attacking move has been played more than 300 times! Instead,} 11. g4 {leads to the variation after} c5 12. O-O-O {.}) 11... c5 {Now that Black has castled, it's logical to open the c-file even if the center isn't entirely protected.} 12. h4 cxd4 {Since White's expansion ideas on the kingside are no longer a secret, we need to create counterplay of our own by striking in the center.} 13. exd4 Nc6 14. g4 {White has to be fast and threatens to continue with g5 .} Bc8 {An accurate move. This bishop comes to g4 .} (14... g6 $5 {is the main move, but I find it dangerous after the following sequence:} 15. g5 hxg5 16. hxg5 Bxg5+ 17. Kb1 {and White has decent compensation thanks to the opening of the kingside.}) 15. g5 Bg4 {That's the point for Black.} 16. gxf6 Qxf6 {Even stronger than to take on f3 , the knight has to move.} 17. Ne1 Bxd1 18. Qxd1 Nxd4 {The material is fine for Black, and more importantly, White's attack is stopped, who remains with a few weaknesses on the kingside. Black is simply going to bring the rooks into play.} *

