,} 11. g4 {leads to the variation after} c5 12. O-O-O {.}) 11... c5 {Now that Black has castled, it's logical to open the c-file even if the center isn't entirely protected.} 12. h4 cxd4 {Since White's expansion ideas on the kingside are no longer a secret, we need to create counterplay of our own by striking in the center.} 13. exd4 Nc6 14. g4 {White has to be fast and threatens to continue with g5 .} Bc8 {An accurate move. This bishop comes to g4 .} (14... g6 $5 {is the main move, but I find it dangerous after the following sequence:} 15. g5 hxg5 16. hxg5 Bxg5+ 17. Kb1 {and White has decent compensation thanks to the opening of the kingside.}) 15. g5 Bg4 {That's the point for Black.} 16. Be2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxd4 {Black continues to play accurately, grabs a pawn, and wants to take on f3 while still not moving the bishop.} 18. Qd3 Nxf3 19. gxf6 ({After} 19. Qxf3 Bxc3 20. bxc3 {, we can close down the kingside with} h5 {since} 21. Qxh5 Rc8 {brings White more trouble than the material gain, or continue with the more concrete Qd6 followed by ... Qa3 + and only afterwards push ... h5 . Black is slightly preferable in both cases.}) 19... Ne5 {Saving the knight before taking back on f6 .} 20. Qf5 Qxf6 {Black has temporarily two extra pawns and is fine trading queens if that means the king survives.} 21. Qxf6 gxf6 22. f4 Nd7 23. Nxd5 Rac8+ 24. Kb1 {And a draw was agreed is the correspondence game ½-½ Bjuhr-Proof, ICCF email 2009. Black's extra pawn is weak, so it's not enough to dream of anything.} *

