1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Be2 ({As we decide to take on c4 , the option of} 8. Bd3 {is identical to Be2 , as White now loses a tempo having already moved the bishop.}) 8... dxc4 {This avoids a further possibility like Bxf6 followed by cxd5 .} 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {Black got what we wanted: Black waited for the f1 -bishop to move, before trading on c4 , and has opened the diagonal for our bishop. The next idea is to push ... c5 to level the control of the center.} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 {This move doesn't prevent ... c5 at all, so let's go for it.} c5 {Of course!} 12. Qe2 Nd5 {Black is trying to trade a few pieces in order to release the tension.} 13. Bxe7 {That makes Black's life easier because the queen will have a safe spot on e7 .} Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Qxe7 15. Rd1 Rfd8 {Black will take on d4 at some point, and the position will be symmetrical. It's even perhaps easier for Black thanks to the bishop on b7 that it is stronger than its homolog on c4 .} *

