e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. Be2 ({As we decide to take on c4 , the option of} 8. Bd3 {is identical to Be2 , as White now loses a tempo having already moved the bishop.}) 8... dxc4 {This avoids a further possibility like Bxf6 followed by cxd5 .} 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {Black got what we wanted: Black waited for the f1 -bishop to move, before trading on c4 , and has opened the diagonal for our bishop. The next idea is to push ... c5 to level the control of the center.} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rc1 {This move doesn't prevent ... c5 at all, so let's go for it.} c5 {Of course!} 12. Qe2 Nd5 {Black is trying to trade a few pieces in order to release the tension.} 13. Bg3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 cxd4 {Black immediately trades to occupy nice squares with the pieces.} 15. Nxd4 ({After} 15. exd4 Nf6 {, White doesn't get the needed initiative that an isolated pawn requires since the d5 -square is under our control.}) 15... Bf6 {Black will bring the queen to e7 and the knight to c5 at some point.} *

