e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. cxd5 {The most played move in the position, but I don't really think it can be a big problem. We have seen so many move orders transposing into this line that I just think it should remain as the main variation.} Nxd5 {As usual, Black takes back with the knight to trade a few pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Be2 {To my eyes, this is too passive, and Black easily gets a fine game. The bishop is worse than on the d3 -square, and we can play similarly.} (10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {is analyzed via the 5.Nf3 move order .}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bb7 {The next step for Black is to push ... c5 .} 12. O-O c5 {Black plans to get some activity on the queenside, especially along the c-file. So the next moves could be ... Nd7 , ... Rfc8 , ... Rc7 , ... Rac8 , to open the c-file at the right time and try to invade there.} *

