e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. cxd5 {The most played move in the position, but I don't really think it can be a big problem. We have seen so many move orders transposing into this line that I just think it should remain as the main variation.} Nxd5 {As usual, Black takes back with the knight to trade a few pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Rc1 {This move contains different ideas from the other ones. Now, White wants to take back with the rook on c3 . I don't think there is anything wrong with Black's position, which means there is no rush.} (10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {is analyzed via the 5.Nf3 move order .}) 10... Bb7 11. Nxd5 (11. Be2 Rc8 12. O-O c5 {will transpose to 11.Nxd5 quickly.}) (11. Bd3 {, with the bishop on b7 enjoying an open diagonal, I think White should place the bishop on e2 instead, to keep protecting the f3 -knight.} Rc8 12. O-O c5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 {, any moment Black has a free move, we can develop quietly with ... Nd7 , to improve the position. After} 14. dxc5 Rxc5 15. Rxc5 Qxc5 {, White has to think about the f3 -knight here, and Black is just fine.}) 11... Bxd5 12. Be2 Rc8 {This feels like the easiest move to me, to quickly push ... c5 and take back with the rook.} 13. O-O c5 14. dxc5 Rxc5 15. Rxc5 Qxc5 {Quite a few games have reached this position. Any move looks equal, and Black has no problem here.} *


