1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 {From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times.} (3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. Bg5 ({Historically, this is considered to be the main line. For some reason, people tended to refrain from} 4. cxd5 {(probably not to allow the bishop on c8 to be able to develop). But recently, it's becoming less popular, and I think White prefers to clarify the center (with cxd5 ) . However, we should be very cautious with this line. It's still played all the time in high-level games, and the theory evolves quickly.}) 4... Be7 ({That's the logical continuation if you want to play the Orthodox Variation. Also, transpositions can occur with 3.Nf3 in case White now plays Nf3 , so we have to check these lines anyway. Nonetheless, I would also like to mention an alternative that is becoming popular recently:} 4... dxc4 {. It clearly deserves some consideration, and it can sometimes be similar to the chapter on} 5. Nf3 {Nf6 Bg5 dxc4 .}) 5. e3 ({This is obviously the most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. cxd5 {The most played move in the position, but I don't really think it can be a big problem. We have seen so many move orders transposing into this line that I just think it should remain as the main variation.} Nxd5 {As usual, Black takes back with the knight to trade a few pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 (10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {is analyzed via the 5.Nf3 move order .}) 10... exd5 {A position that is important to understand, especially since it can be reached via several move orders.} 11. Rc1 {It will always be useful for White to bring the rook here. Also, Black can't push ... c5 yet because the d5 -pawn would be hanging. So first, Black needs to decide the place for the bishop.} Be6 {We usually prefer this square instead of b7 because the bishop has potentially other prospects on the diagonal (on f5 or g4 ), and it leaves the b-file opened for a rook (whenever White trades on c5 , making the b6 -pawn disappear).} 12. Bd3 ({This is a very logical move too, to develop and castle. It seems more logical to me than} 12. Be2 {, which is less active.}) 12... c5 13. dxc5 {White forces the hanging pair of pawns in the center before ... c4 can be played.} bxc5 14. O-O Nd7 {The most logical square for the knight. It simply protects the c5 -pawn.} 15. e4 {A concrete approach, and the main move in the position.} d4 {Of course. Taking on e4 would leave a very weak pawn on c5 .} 16. Nd2 {The main move in the position, but that's too slow. White is willing to secure the c4 -square and to push f4 soon.} Ne5 17. Bb1 c4 {Very strong. The only debate is to know whether the pawn will be safe there. White would like to achieve f4 to chase the knight and take on c4 , but unfortunately, that is not possible now because ... Ng4 - e3 is too dangerous.} 18. h3 {Threatening f4 .} Rab8 {A very powerful novelty. Black isn't afraid of the concrete lines.} 19. f4 (19. b3 {is the proof that White is much worse. After} c3 20. Nf3 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Rfd8 {, the two pawns are way too strong.}) 19... Rxb2 {A huge blow. The rook invades the position at the cost of the knight, but it's worth it.} 20. fxe5 Qb4 21. Nf3 d3 {There is nothing concrete yet, but Black is completely winning. White isn't able to sacrifice the bishop back against the two pawns because ... Rd8 would come to collect it and save the c-pawn. White is objectively hopeless and has no play at all; our pawns are too strong.} *

