e most natural move, but} 5. Nf3 {is at least as important because of the many transpositions that lead to this position. Here after e3 , White protects the c4 -pawn but also keeps the possibility to bring the knight to e2 .}) 5... h6 {For the same reason as against Nf3 , my choice is to ask immediately about White's plans for the bishop. As usual, coming back to h4 will be the answer most of the time, but the two other replies also need to be considered.} 6. Bh4 {The most logical move.} O-O {Here too, White has a wide choice. The most obvious would be to develop the knight, but White can also trade on d5 , or improve the queenside with a semi-waiting move such as Rc1 .} 7. Nf3 {Objectively, this is probably the most important position of our chapter, as it can occur via so many move orders.} b6 {The beginning of the Tartakower Variation, which we met several times in this chapter already. Black brings the bishop to b7 and hopes to open the diagonal at some point if White allows us to do so (but it happens only rarely).} 8. cxd5 {The most played move in the position, but I don't really think it can be a big problem. We have seen so many move orders transposing into this line that I just think it should remain as the main variation.} Nxd5 {As usual, Black takes back with the knight to trade a few pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 (10. Bd3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {is analyzed via the 5.Nf3 move order .}) 10... exd5 {A position that is important to understand, especially since it can be reached via several move orders.} 11. Rc1 {It will always be useful for White to bring the rook here. Also, Black can't push ... c5 yet because the d5 -pawn would be hanging. So first, Black needs to decide the place for the bishop.} Be6 {We usually prefer this square instead of b7 because the bishop has potentially other prospects on the diagonal (on f5 or g4 ), and it leaves the b-file opened for a rook (whenever White trades on c5 , making the b6 -pawn disappear).} 12. Qa4 {The queen targets a7 and c6 . There is no reason to wait for pushing the pawn, but Rc8 is also a safe option for Black.} c5 13. Qa3 {That's the point. To avoid taking on c5 , White pins the pawn.} Rc8 14. Be2 a5 {The main continuation. Black starts the expansion on the queenside. It can always be useful to have the possibility to break with ... a4 if White plans on holding with b3 .} 15. O-O Kf8 {I like this straightforward approach. Black simply protects the queen, and the idea is to push ... c4 on the next move and to bring the game into an endgame, with a nice majority on the queenside.} 16. dxc5 {White doesn't want to see that happen and should take, to force a hanging pair of pawns.} bxc5 17. Rc3 c4 {This move forces an endgame.} 18. Qxe7+ Kxe7 19. b3 Nc6 20. bxc4 dxc4 {White can't take on c4 due to the multiples threats after ... Nb4 . Black is active here.} *

