nd c6 . There is no reason to wait for pushing the pawn, but Rc8 is also a safe option for Black.} c5 13. Qa3 {That's the point. To avoid taking on c5 , White pins the pawn.} Rc8 14. Be2 a5 {The main continuation. Black starts the expansion on the queenside. It can always be useful to have the possibility to break with ... a4 if White plans on holding with b3 .} 15. O-O Kf8 {I like this straightforward approach. Black simply protects the queen, and the idea is to push ... c4 on the next move and to bring the game into an endgame, with a nice majority on the queenside.} 16. dxc5 {White doesn't want to see that happen and should take, to force a hanging pair of pawns.} bxc5 17. Rc3 c4 {This move forces an endgame.} 18. Qxe7+ Kxe7 19. e4 {The only game that reached this position brings even more trades.} dxe4 20. Nd4 Nd7 21. Nxe6 fxe6 {Taking back with the king is also an option, but it's slower.} 22. Bxc4 Ne5 23. Rfc1 Nxc4 24. Rxc4 Rxc4 25. Rxc4 Rd8 {A concrete way to hold. The rook intrudes on the second rank.} 26. Rc7+ Kf6 27. Kf1 Rd2 28. Rb7 a4 {Black is safe here thanks to the piece activity as in the game ½-½ Hovhannisyan-Pashikian, Yerevan 2014.} *

