1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. cxd5 {We don't need to analyze this move order, but it seems interesting to mention that this move has been tried recently by elite players. It's rather strange to me, as it seems to offer more options for Black later (in particular if we want to develop the c8 -bishop fast).} ({However, it also prevents a few ideas, such as the Hennig-Schara Gambit(} 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 {) or the Accelerated Semi-Tarrasch ( Nc3 Nf6 cxd5 Nxd5 ) . But as these lines are not our repertoires, I suggest not to bother so much, and to simply transpose into our lines.}) 3... exd5 4. Nc3 {White doesn't have any other real options here.} Nf6 ({Transposing is the simplest, but other moves, such as} 4... c6 {, also make sense.}) *

