1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. g3 {This move is a king of Catalan Variation, but with cxd5 and ... exd5 already played. It may seem like a minor difference, but it's a pretty major one. Usually, in the Catalan, when Black doesn't take on c4 , the long-term plan is to organize e4 , with Nc3 or Nbd2 , Qc2 , etc.  Here, if White manages e4 , Black will just take on e4 , and White will remain with an isolated pawn on d4 . So, as e4 is not a real option, the bishop on g2 will be stuck on the d5 -pawn. That's just a bad plan to play a fianchetto!} Bd6 {Again, Bg5 is quite harmless (after protecting d5 , we will play ... h6 , and Bh4 is no longer playable to keep the pin).} 6. Bg2 c6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {Black has secured a safe position. Let's examine a possible continuation.} 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Re1 Nf8 {The knight is headed towards e6 or g6 , which is often the case in the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 11. Bg5 Bg4 12. e4 {Despite being a controversial move, I think it's necessary if White wants to do something, taking advantage of the pin on the f6 -knight.} dxe4 13. Rxe4 {This leads to massive trades.} Rxe4 14. Nxe4 Be7 15. Nxf6+ {There is not much else for White to try.} Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 {The position is equal, but if Black quickly manages ... Rd8 and ... Ne6 , it will be hard for White to keep the pawn.} *

