ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. g3 {This move is a king of Catalan Variation, but with cxd5 and ... exd5 already played. It may seem like a minor difference, but it's a pretty major one. Usually, in the Catalan, when Black doesn't take on c4 , the long-term plan is to organize e4 , with Nc3 or Nbd2 , Qc2 , etc.  Here, if White manages e4 , Black will just take on e4 , and White will remain with an isolated pawn on d4 . So, as e4 is not a real option, the bishop on g2 will be stuck on the d5 -pawn. That's just a bad plan to play a fianchetto!} Bd6 {Again, Bg5 is quite harmless (after protecting d5 , we will play ... h6 , and Bh4 is no longer playable to keep the pin).} 6. Bg2 c6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {Black has secured a safe position. Let's examine a possible continuation.} 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Re1 Nf8 {The knight is headed towards e6 or g6 , which is often the case in the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 11. Bg5 Bg4 12. e4 {Despite being a controversial move, I think it's necessary if White wants to do something, taking advantage of the pin on the f6 -knight.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 14. Rxe4 Bf5 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black will get the exchange back, and White has just enough play for the isolated d4 -pawn to keep an approximately balanced game.} *

