ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Qc2 {As usual, this move tries to prevent the idea of ... Bf5 , but it's probably too early here.} ({It's possible to play c6 , most probably transposing into other lines after} 5. Bg5 {or Bf4 . I have another idea though, very unusual and smart!}) 5... Nc6 {It seems to me that this move is the best attempt to take advantage of the move order played by White, with immediate pressure on d4 . Engines already give an edge to Black.} 6. Bg5 {An interesting try, playing for the initiative, but Black can keep an advantage by accepting the pawn.} Nxd4 {White's statistical success in the position arising from 6.Bg5 is directly associated with the low utilization of this critical capture.} 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. O-O-O {That's the point. White has a development advantage to compensate for the pawn.} Bd7 9. Nxd5 {This move is severely countered.} Nb4 {That was the point of 8...Bd7 .} 10. Qb3 Nbxd5 11. Rxd5 Be7 12. Rd1 Ng4 {White has too many problems, and when Black will castle, we will reach an easily won position.} *

