1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bf4 ({We have seen a similar development for White in the chapter on} 5. Bf4 {, but we can no longer take on c4 . The bishop looks decently placed here.  I would still say it's rather dubious, or at least harmless. The reason is that it puts no pressure whatsoever on the f6 -knight (which simplifies the task of keeping the d5 -pawn alive), so it will ease our development. In particular, the bishop on c8 has more chances to develop easily!}) 5... c6 {As against 5.Bg5 , I prefer to start with this flexible move, securing the d5 -square, and keeping every option on the table.} 6. Nf3 {This enables Black to get an easy development.} Bf5 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 {We will see different variations where White needs to settle for the exchange of the light-squared bishop. As it's usually the 'weak' bishop for Black, we are glad to trade it.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 10. h3 {White prevents any ... Nh5 ideas.} O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Rab1 {The minority attack is the most straightforward, but also a well-known way to handle this Carlsbad pawn structure. White wants to weaken our queenside, especially the c6 -pawn. However, without the light-squared bishop, White should be careful, as White doesn't have real control over the c4 -square and as soon as b4 is played, the c4 -square is reachable with ... Nb6 - c4 .} a5 13. Rfc1 Nb6 14. Nd2 Bd6 {Finally, Black also decides to trade the dark-squared bishops.} 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 {White feels knights are more useful, and that's why White decides to trade the bishop here instead, but Black gets a comfortable game.} Qxf6 17. Rf1 Qe6 {The game Moradiabadi-Dominguez Perez, Saint Louis USA 2023 ended in a draw, but Black is already just simply better. White is lacking a real plan.} *

