1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bf4 ({We have seen a similar development for White in the chapter on} 5. Bf4 {, but we can no longer take on c4 . The bishop looks decently placed here.  I would still say it's rather dubious, or at least harmless. The reason is that it puts no pressure whatsoever on the f6 -knight (which simplifies the task of keeping the d5 -pawn alive), so it will ease our development. In particular, the bishop on c8 has more chances to develop easily!}) 5... c6 {As against 5.Bg5 , I prefer to start with this flexible move, securing the d5 -square, and keeping every option on the table.} 6. e3 {The most common.} Bf5 {Once again, when the possibility is offered, we develop the bishop before White manages Bd3 .} 7. Bd3 {Despite being a positional concession, this move is by far the most common.} Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Nh5 {I like this energetic way of handling the position. Black would be glad to trade the bishop, and this also frees the f6 -square for the other knight.} 9. Bg3 ({The most common reply. I would say it's also slightly less accurate than} 9. Be5 {. I find it more difficult to play with Black when we had to play ... f6 , which can be useful, but which is also a weakening move. Here the b8 -knight keeps a route towards e4 .}) 9... Nd7 10. Nf3 Be7 11. O-O Nxg3 {As soon as White has castled, it becomes safe to take on g3 , as there is no longer pressure on h7 .} 12. hxg3 Nf6 {I would already take Black's side for sure. Our next moves are easy, ... O-O and ... Re8 , probably ... Bd6 and ... Ne4 . On the other hand, it's not so clear what White is going to do with the knights, and also the minority attack is not so easy to organize.} *

