ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Qc2 ({That is the other possible move. That's more valid than the line we saw with} 6. Qc2 {. However, let's keep the idea of developing the light-squared bishop, and we have only one way to do so.}) 6... g6 7. Bg5 {Other moves make no real sense. Here, Black needs to be careful!} Be7 {This is the best square for the bishop, solving the pin. It also would be pointless on g7 , facing the d4 -pawn. Now, White has tried different ideas.} (7... Bf5 $2 {would be a mistake.} 8. Qb3 {and Black isn't able to play ... Qb6 because the knight would be hanging on f6 . Protecting the b7 -pawn isn't an easy task.} b6 $6 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. Ne5 {and that's how things escalate quickly. Black is lost already.}) 8. e4 {White tries to open the position. It's not great for the d4 -pawn, which will end up being isolated, but in the meantime, White tries to take advantage of the weakness of ... g6 .} dxe4 {That's my preference. Taking with the knight is also possible but tends to slightly favor White.} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ {Here at least, White develops an initiative.} Qe7 {The queen trade favors Black because of White's isolated pawn, so let's force an endgame.} 11. Ne5 {Black can't decently prevent a queen trade.} Bf5 12. Qe3 Nd7 {Black trades the only annoying white piece and stands better thanks to the bishop pair and the better pawn structure.} *

