ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Qc2 ({That is the other possible move. That's more valid than the line we saw with} 6. Qc2 {. However, let's keep the idea of developing the light-squared bishop, and we have only one way to do so.}) 6... g6 7. Bg5 {Other moves make no real sense. Here, Black needs to be careful!} Be7 {This is the best square for the bishop, solving the pin. It also would be pointless on g7 , facing the d4 -pawn. Now, White has tried different ideas.} (7... Bf5 $2 {would be a mistake.} 8. Qb3 {and Black isn't able to play ... Qb6 because the knight would be hanging on f6 . Protecting the b7 -pawn isn't an easy task.} b6 $6 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. Ne5 {and that's how things escalate quickly. Black is lost already.}) 8. e3 {That's by far the main move for White.} Bf5 {It's allowed, so let's trade the bishops! White has no choice but to accept it.} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 (10... O-O 11. O-O {½-½ Vescovi-Tin, Sharjah 2023.}) 11. Bh6 {That's a logical try, to prevent Black from castling, but we can't say it's long-term.} Bf8 ({I think that's my preference over the other option:} 11... Ng4 {. The reason is that when Black plays ... Ng4 , the only option for the knight later on is to go back to f6 , while the bishop can choose between e7 , d6 , g7 , and even b4 -squares.}) 12. Bxf8 {The main line, but I can't see how it can be a problem for Black.} Kxf8 13. b4 Kg7 14. b5 Qa5 15. bxc6 {And now Black can make use of the fact that White hasn't castled yet.} Rac8 16. O-O Rxc6 17. Ne2 Rhc8 {Black takes over the initiative, as White is unable to fight back on the c-file.} *

