te has tried many moves. Obviously, the minority attack is the main plan for White, but we will also have a look at a couple of other options.} 12. Nd2 Re8 13. f3 {White tries another plan, to quickly advance in the center. I am not sure it's great because Black will be ready for it, but we still need to be careful.} Nf8 14. e4 {The central push can be seen now, or never, because the knight is coming to e6 anyway. Probably it's just better to never play e4 , showing that f3 wasn't such a good idea.} Ne6 15. Be3 c5 {White is unable to play dxc5 because of d4 , winning a piece, and is in trouble.} 16. Rad1 cxd4 17. Bxd4 dxe4 18. Ndxe4 Nxd4 {Massive trades occur, and Black will end up being better thanks to the bishop.} 19. Qxd4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Qxd4+ 21. Rxd4 Rad8 {Black is quickly following with ... f5 to chase the knight and bring the king to the center. The bishop should prove to be stronger in these endgames with pawns on both sides and no clear square for the knight.} *

