ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Bg5 {This is the more popular move, to simply pin the knight. We have a clever solution.} h6 {It's important to start with this move, which will also allow Black to push ... g5 if necessary, at the right time.} 7. Bxf6 ({This can't really be dangerous. So is} 7. Bf4 {, which will be very similar to Bf4 , that we checked already.}) 7... Qxf6 8. Rc1 {This trick has been tried a few times. White aims to gain a pawn with Nxd5 , but it's easy to prevent it.} Nd7 9. e3 Bd6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Qe7 {The queen frees the square for the knight. If White ever wants to do something in the center, White should do it now, before the knight arrives.} 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nf6 {A simple solution. Playing against an isolated pawn allows us to be glad to trade pieces.} 14. Re1 {And now, I would deviate from the game 0-1 Sjugirov-Dubov, chess.com 2022.} Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Qf6 16. d5 c5 17. Nd2 b6 {I would still slightly prefer to take Black's side here. We have a stable position, and the pawn on d5 remains weak and exposed.} *

