1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Bg5 {This is the more popular move, to simply pin the knight. We have a clever solution.} h6 {It's important to start with this move, which will also allow Black to push ... g5 if necessary, at the right time.} 7. Bh4 {That's clearly the most logical retreat, White keeps the pin.} Bf5 {A nice bishop sortie, at the right time!} 8. e3 ({That's less critical for the value of the line, but it remains more played. But as we have already seen in highly similar positions in this chapter (especially after} 8. Qc2 {), we won't focus so much. It's an even better version because Black didn't have to play with ... g6 to manage ... Bf5 , so our kingside is safer, and White doesn't have any possibilities with h4 or Bh6 , among others.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 {Once again, the minority attack is the only plan that seems manageable for White.} a5 {Let's try to prevent it, or at least to make it harder!} 13. Qc2 {White tries to prevent ... a4 , but it's not necessarily going to work.} Re8 14. a3 b5 {This will bring similar positions.} 15. Rfc1 a4 {As soon as the knight gets to c4 , Black's advantage will be indisputable.} *

