ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Bg5 {This is the more popular move, to simply pin the knight. We have a clever solution.} h6 {It's important to start with this move, which will also allow Black to push ... g5 if necessary, at the right time.} 7. Bh4 {That's clearly the most logical retreat, White keeps the pin.} Bf5 {A nice bishop sortie, at the right time!} 8. e3 ({That's less critical for the value of the line, but it remains more played. But as we have already seen in highly similar positions in this chapter (especially after} 8. Qc2 {), we won't focus so much. It's an even better version because Black didn't have to play with ... g6 to manage ... Bf5 , so our kingside is safer, and White doesn't have any possibilities with h4 or Bh6 , among others.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 {Once again, the minority attack is the only plan that seems manageable for White.} a5 {Let's try to prevent it, or at least to make it harder!} 13. a3 a4 14. Qc2 b5 {The next goal is to secure the c6 -pawn, and the knight will be free to reach c4 .} 15. Rbc1 {0-1 Kulikov-Aleksandrov, Kstovo 1998.} Rc8 {This looks like the most useful move.} 16. Rfe1 Nb6 17. e4 {White is not doomed to wait eternally. But now, the only breakthrough is e4 , and the issue is the pawn on d4 that becomes isolated.} Nxe4 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Rxe4 Qd6 {White has just enough compensation for the isolated pawn; the position is balanced.} *

