ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Bg5 {This is the more popular move, to simply pin the knight. We have a clever solution.} h6 {It's important to start with this move, which will also allow Black to push ... g5 if necessary, at the right time.} 7. Bh4 {That's clearly the most logical retreat, White keeps the pin.} Bf5 {A nice bishop sortie, at the right time!} 8. Qb3 g5 {That's why we played h6 in the first place! In the variation Bf5 Qb3 h6? is impossible because White can take on f6 followed by Qxb7 . Here, we are chasing the bishop first (to prevent Bxf6 , damaging the pawn structure), and we follow with .... Qb6 .} 9. Qxb7 {This try backfires severely!} gxh4 10. Qxa8 Qb6 {This traps the queen on a8 , but it also attacks the b2 -pawn, with big damages.} 11. O-O-O Bd6 12. e4 {White is trying their best to confuse Black, but it's quite easy to keep track of the game.} Nxe4 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qxd5 {At least the queen escapes.} Bf4+ {The king on c1 doesn't feel safe.} 15. Nd2 Qc7+ ({The most accurate continuation according to the engines.} 15... Nxd2 {is not necessarily the best but one of the many ways to keep a winning position.} 16. Qxf5 Nc4+ {0-1 Begunov-Korchmar, chess.com 2022.}) 16. Bc4 O-O 17. Qxf5 Qxc4+ 18. Kb1 Nxd2+ {Black has a big material advantage.} *

