ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Nf3 {I also don't like this move. It's too slow, and it will help us develop the bishop to f5 , as often seen in this chapter.} c6 ({We start again with this move. It's important to threaten ... Bf5 , and to meet Qb3 with ... Qb6 . Usually, this position occurs from the Semi-Slav (from the move order d4 d5 c4} 5... c6 {Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 e6 cxd5 exd5 ), and it's well known to be harmless.}) {Let's mention now that e3 and Bf4 have already been covered via e3 and Bf4 respectively.} 6. Bg5 {This is the more popular move, to simply pin the knight. We have a clever solution.} h6 {It's important to start with this move, which will also allow Black to push ... g5 if necessary, at the right time.} 7. Bh4 {That's clearly the most logical retreat, White keeps the pin.} Bf5 {A nice bishop sortie, at the right time!} 8. Qb3 g5 {That's why we played h6 in the first place! In the variation Bf5 Qb3 h6? is impossible because White can take on f6 followed by Qxb7 . Here, we are chasing the bishop first (to prevent Bxf6 , damaging the pawn structure), and we follow with .... Qb6 .} 9. Bg3 Qb6 {Black is already better. White's attack on the queenside has backfired, and now a queen trade is not so appealing, as it would help Black to improve the pawn structure.} 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. e3 Nbd7 12. Ne5 Bb4 13. a3 Ne4 {White can't prevent Black's incoming activity; ... b5 and ... Nb6 will follow!} 14. Bd3 {Here, in the following game, Black secured a safe and long-term advantage.} Nxg3 15. hxg3 Nxe5 16. Bxf5 Nc4 17. Ke2 Bxc3 18. bxc3 b5 {I would hate to be White as in the game 0-1 Fedorov-Shalimov, St. Petersburg 2000. The light-squared bishop can't do much, and the pawn on a3 seems hard to keep alive.} *

