ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. Qc2 {This directly prevents ... Bf5 .} h6 {As against e3 , we start with this move, forcing White to decide what to do with the bishop.} 7. Bh4 Be6 {This idea is simply to develop the bishop first, before bringing the knight to d7 .} (7... g6 {would be in the spirit of our analysis in the previous chapter, managing ... Bf5 . But to see something different and very interesting here, I would like to show a completely different setup.}) 8. e3 Nbd7 9. f3 {This gives a new square to the h4 -bishop, if necessary. So, there is no need to play ... g5 anymore.} Bd6 10. e4 {That's too early, White is underdeveloped.} dxe4 11. fxe4 g5 12. Bf2 Ng4 {White has a febrile position and has to give up the bishop pair.} *

