1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. Qc2 {This directly prevents ... Bf5 .} h6 {As against e3 , we start with this move, forcing White to decide what to do with the bishop.} 7. Bh4 Be6 {This idea is simply to develop the bishop first, before bringing the knight to d7 .} (7... g6 {would be in the spirit of our analysis in the previous chapter, managing ... Bf5 . But to see something different and very interesting here, I would like to show a completely different setup.}) 8. e3 Nbd7 9. f3 {This gives a new square to the h4 -bishop, if necessary. So, there is no need to play ... g5 anymore.} Bd6 10. Bd3 c5 {Let's react in the center when White isn't ready.} 11. Nge2 c4 12. Bf5 O-O 13. O-O Qe8 {The queen gets out of the way of the h4 -bishop, and starts eyeing the e3 -pawn.} 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. a4 {Wesley So has tried this new move recently, but despite his win, I don't think it changes anything in the evaluation of the line. The idea is to prevent ... b5 , but we can insist.} a6 {Black will try to push ... b5 later.} 16. b3 Rc8 {Bringing the rook on the weak c4 -square would be nice.} 17. Rab1 Bb4 18. Be1 Nb6 19. Qa2 {1-0 So-Tabatabaei, Berlin 2022.} Bd6 {We improve over the game, intending ... e5 on the next move.} 20. b4 e5 {Black strikes back in the center.} 21. dxe5 Bxe5 {Black has very active position, and the pawn on e3 is a long-term weakness.} *

