ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. e3 ({The classical follow-up. Black has a wide range of action. In opposition to} 6. Qc2 {, e3 doesn't seem to prevent} Bf5 {, but actually, it would be met with Qf3 followed by Bxf6 , destroying Black's pawn structure. It's a main line for Black and completely playable, but I have never been a big fan of it, even if I know that it is solid. I decided to opt for a recent system, and a very interesting and fighting one!}) 6... h6 {First, we ask a question to the bishop, to know where it goes. When I started playing the Queen's Gambit (with both colors), almost 20 years ago, and for some years after that, I would have said directly that this is a dubious move. In some lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined, when Black brings the knight to d7 and f8 , we can no longer go to g6 (as White will play Qc2 and Bd3 ).  Things evolved though, and now many moves are playable, and concrete and modern lines appeared. In the variation I have decided to show you, it's important to play ... h6 quickly, not to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bf4 ({In the previous chapter, we analyzed the same position but with the pawn on h7 , in the} 7. Bf4 {c6 e3 variation. It can't be bad to have ... h6 already played.}) 7... Bf5 ({In opposition to} 7... Bf5 {, now Qf3 does nothing.}) 8. h3 {With this move, White probably reveals the intention to expand on the kingside with g4 soon.} Bd6 9. Nge2 O-O 10. g4 {That's also a justification of the Nge2 move.} Bh7 11. g5 {Now, in the game 0-1 Ponkratov-Niemann, chess.com 2022, I would prefer to take on g5 immediately.} hxg5 12. Bxg5 {The bishop is in the way of the rook that will arrive on the g-file. To defend, the best attitude is probably to counterattack!} Nbd7 13. Rg1 Qb6 {White already needs to worry about the b2 -pawn.} 14. Qd2 Rfe8 {I don't feel any real danger on the black king.} *

