t to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. h3 {To be honest, this just feels too slow. It also doesn't keep both options open for White, as f3 and e4 won't work well with the h3 move, which creates some weaknesses on the dark squares.} Ne4 {It's not always possible to directly bring the knight to the center, and that's my advice after White's 9.h3 .} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nge2 f5 13. Nf4 {White seems to consider that the well-placed knights are enough to bring an edge. But Black has a space advantage, and we will slowly take back the control of the d5 -square.} Kh7 14. h4 {White secures the knight on f4 and could also use the g6 -square.} Nd7 15. h5 Rd8 16. Nce2 Nf6 {White is stable, but what is the plan exactly? Black can put some pressure against h5 with ... Be6 - f7 , and it will be hard for White to place the king safely, as the h5 -pawn might need the rook on h1 to protect it.} *

