t to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Qc2 ({That's the most played move, but I decided to keep} 9. Nge2 {as the main line. However, there are transpositions between both variations.}) 9... Ne8 {This is a recent plan, and to give some numbers, it has been played only 130 times (at the date of September 2023), out of more than 4000 games. Many strong players started to play this, even Magnus Carlsen twice in 2021, and I like a lot the plans Black is provided with.  The first idea is obviously to trade bishops, which White can refuse. Also, the knight heads towards d6 , to control c4 , e4 , and even f5 , to sometimes manage ... Bf5 , and it frees the f6 -square to the other knight! Now, White can accept to trade the bishops or to bring it back to g3 .} (9... Ne4 {isn't possible here, as it's not protected enough.}) 10. Bxe7 {I feel this eases Black's play, as the bishop doesn't have great prospects right now.} Qxe7 11. Nf3 (11. Nge2 {is the main line of the 9.Nge2 variation .}) 11... Be6 12. O-O Nd7 13. h3 Nd6 {Objectively, what is the plan for White now? Pushing e4 is complicated, as it creates a weak d4 -pawn. The minority attack would weaken the c4 -square, and the knight on d6 is perfectly placed to reach c4 . Black's plan could be to place the queen on f6 , and then start an initiative on the kingside.} *

