1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nc3 {Clearly the most played move. White loses the possibility to play a Catalan, but it seems that most players prefer to play a common Queen's Gambit.} Nf6 ({From beginners to top Grandmasters, this has been played numerous times. Before entering the two main lines which are cxd5 and Bg5 , we will have a look at the sidelines.} 3... Be7 {is another way to play the Queen's Gambit Declined, but I prefer to keep a classical way of playing the opening. It can transpose into the second part after} 4. Nf3 Nf6 {, but White also has options such as} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 {.}) ({Instead, we can mention} 3... c5 {, which should lead to the Tarrasch Defense, and c6 , which is more typical of Semi-Slavs.}) 4. cxd5 ({Let's explore in depth the variations where White takes immediately on d5 . Now,} 4. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 bxc3} c5 {enters the Semi-Tarrasch territory. It has always been considered to be solid for Black, but that's not our topic. Taking on d5 became popular when Kasparov started to play it a lot, scoring several impressive wins with the plan featuring Nge2 and f3 - e4 . The ease with which he crushed his opponents was very appealing, and for a long time, Black was having a hard time. That's why for some time, Black merely entered the Queen's Gambit from a Nimzo-Indian move order ( d4} 5. Nxf6+ {c4 e6 Nf3 , fearing the Nimzo, d5 ), where the knight is already committed to f3 . But this is not necessarily true anymore, and players tend to think that this line is fully playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. e3 ({The classical follow-up. Black has a wide range of action. In opposition to} 6. Qc2 {, e3 doesn't seem to prevent} Bf5 {, but actually, it would be met with Qf3 followed by Bxf6 , destroying Black's pawn structure. It's a main line for Black and completely playable, but I have never been a big fan of it, even if I know that it is solid. I decided to opt for a recent system, and a very interesting and fighting one!}) 6... h6 {First, we ask a question to the bishop, to know where it goes. When I started playing the Queen's Gambit (with both colors), almost 20 years ago, and for some years after that, I would have said directly that this is a dubious move. In some lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined, when Black brings the knight to d7 and f8 , we can no longer go to g6 (as White will play Qc2 and Bd3 ).  Things evolved though, and now many moves are playable, and concrete and modern lines appeared. In the variation I have decided to show you, it's important to play ... h6 quickly, not to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Qc2 ({That's the most played move, but I decided to keep} 9. Nge2 {as the main line. However, there are transpositions between both variations.}) 9... Ne8 {This is a recent plan, and to give some numbers, it has been played only 130 times (at the date of September 2023), out of more than 4000 games. Many strong players started to play this, even Magnus Carlsen twice in 2021, and I like a lot the plans Black is provided with.  The first idea is obviously to trade bishops, which White can refuse. Also, the knight heads towards d6 , to control c4 , e4 , and even f5 , to sometimes manage ... Bf5 , and it frees the f6 -square to the other knight! Now, White can accept to trade the bishops or to bring it back to g3 .} (9... Ne4 {isn't possible here, as it's not protected enough.}) 10. Bg3 Nd6 11. Nf3 ({I don't feel this is the best try, but instead,} 11. Nge2 {is analyzed via 9.Nge2 .}) 11... Be6 12. O-O Nd7 {I tried a few different plans for White, but without much success.} 13. Ne5 Nf6 14. f3 Rc8 {Also against the plan of pushing e4 , I think reacting quickly in the center is necessary.} 15. e4 {We now have another idea.} Nb5 {The pawn on d4 is under attack, so White should take the knight.} 16. Nxb5 cxb5 17. Qf2 Qb6 {The center is under control, and Black creates some threats against d4 . It's hard for White to make some progress.} *

