ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. e3 ({The classical follow-up. Black has a wide range of action. In opposition to} 6. Qc2 {, e3 doesn't seem to prevent} Bf5 {, but actually, it would be met with Qf3 followed by Bxf6 , destroying Black's pawn structure. It's a main line for Black and completely playable, but I have never been a big fan of it, even if I know that it is solid. I decided to opt for a recent system, and a very interesting and fighting one!}) 6... h6 {First, we ask a question to the bishop, to know where it goes. When I started playing the Queen's Gambit (with both colors), almost 20 years ago, and for some years after that, I would have said directly that this is a dubious move. In some lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined, when Black brings the knight to d7 and f8 , we can no longer go to g6 (as White will play Qc2 and Bd3 ).  Things evolved though, and now many moves are playable, and concrete and modern lines appeared. In the variation I have decided to show you, it's important to play ... h6 quickly, not to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Nge2 {Nowadays, this is the most common plan against the Queen's Gambit Declined. The long-term idea is to organize f3 followed by e4 and advance in the center. White doesn't want to play the minority attack and considers the center more important.} Ne8 ({With the same ideas as in Qc2} 9... Ne8 {, Black offers a bishop trade. I think White should decline it, but both options exist.}) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Now, I think that positionally speaking, ... Bg4 to trade the bishop for the knight on e2 should be seen as a threat.} 11. O-O {Castling doesn't prevent the threat!} Bg4 {The bishop wants to be traded against anything, even the knight!} 12. Qc2 Bxe2 {We came here to take, we shouldn't let the knight reach the f4 or g3 -square.} 13. Nxe2 Nd6 {Black has managed to get rid of the light-squared bishop and now needs to develop, to prevent White's possibilities to play e4 or b4 - b5 .} 14. Nf4 Nd7 15. Rae1 Rfe8 16. f3 {White's aim is clear: to push e4 .} Qf6 {Attacking d4 and f4 prevents e3 - e4 .} 17. Nh5 Qg5 18. Nf4 Re7 ({Of course, you can repeat moves with} 18... Qf6 {, but simply improving the position by doubling rooks on the e-file is completely playable.}) *

