t to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Nge2 {Nowadays, this is the most common plan against the Queen's Gambit Declined. The long-term idea is to organize f3 followed by e4 and advance in the center. White doesn't want to play the minority attack and considers the center more important.} Ne8 ({With the same ideas as in Qc2} 9... Ne8 {, Black offers a bishop trade. I think White should decline it, but both options exist.}) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Now, I think that positionally speaking, ... Bg4 to trade the bishop for the knight on e2 should be seen as a threat.} 11. Qc2 ({Here, Bg4 would be met with} 11. f3 {or any knight move.}) 11... Nd6 12. O-O Qg5 ({The most usual continuation has been the simple move} 12... Nd7 {. But here, Black is trying to trade the bishops on f5 .}) 13. Kh1 Bf5 {There is no reason to refrain from this move.} 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. b4 Nd7 16. b5 Rac8 17. bxc6 Rxc6 {White has managed the minority attack, but Black decides to react on the c-file.} 18. Qb3 Nf6 19. Qxb7 Nh4 {Here, engines show a perpetual check.} 20. g3 Qh5 21. gxh4 Rxc3 {Forcing a perpetual check.} 22. Nxc3 Qf3+ 23. Kg1 Qg4+ {That's a common idea when White brings the pieces to the queenside; then the king is lonely.} *

