ly playable, coming forth with different modern ideas.  It's time to examine these plans, but first, we will focus on the sidelines for White on move 5!}) 4... exd5 {As I just said, we accept to enter the theory of the Orthodox Queen's Gambit. It may seem that it will be a simple task to develop the c8 -bishop, but actually, that's only partially true. Whenever it develops, we should be careful about Qb3 , attacking both b7 and d5 . But also, Qc2 or Bd3 are coming fast to prevent ... Bf5 , and ... Bg4 can be easily repelled by means of f3 .} 5. Bg5 {This is the classical continuation in the Exchange Variation of the Queen's Gambit Declined. The goal is to put some pressure on the d5 -pawn. White is usually intending to follow with 6.e3 and 7.Bd3 to avoid the development of the bishop to f5 .} c6 {Black starts by securing the d5 -pawn. Now that we have prevented the threat Bxf6 Qxf6 Nxd5 , the idea is to develop the c8 -bishop. But it's not clear if we will be able to manage this!} 6. e3 ({The classical follow-up. Black has a wide range of action. In opposition to} 6. Qc2 {, e3 doesn't seem to prevent} Bf5 {, but actually, it would be met with Qf3 followed by Bxf6 , destroying Black's pawn structure. It's a main line for Black and completely playable, but I have never been a big fan of it, even if I know that it is solid. I decided to opt for a recent system, and a very interesting and fighting one!}) 6... h6 {First, we ask a question to the bishop, to know where it goes. When I started playing the Queen's Gambit (with both colors), almost 20 years ago, and for some years after that, I would have said directly that this is a dubious move. In some lines of the Queen's Gambit Declined, when Black brings the knight to d7 and f8 , we can no longer go to g6 (as White will play Qc2 and Bd3 ).  Things evolved though, and now many moves are playable, and concrete and modern lines appeared. In the variation I have decided to show you, it's important to play ... h6 quickly, not to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Nge2 {Nowadays, this is the most common plan against the Queen's Gambit Declined. The long-term idea is to organize f3 followed by e4 and advance in the center. White doesn't want to play the minority attack and considers the center more important.} Ne8 ({With the same ideas as in Qc2} 9... Ne8 {, Black offers a bishop trade. I think White should decline it, but both options exist.}) 10. Bg3 {If White aims to create something here, White should keep pieces on the board. That doesn't change the position entirely, but it keeps more pressure on Black's shoulders.} Nd6 {Again, that's the point. The knight controls c4 and e4 and frees the way to the other knight on f6 . Also, it sometimes helps ... Bf5 .} 11. O-O Re8 12. Bf4 ({The point of this move is to continue with Ng3 . Instead,} 12. Qc2 {transposes back into the main line.}) 12... Bf5 {It's now or never, as Ng3 is coming. Here, it's time for a tactical sequence.} 13. Bxd6 {The beginning of a complicated variation. Now, the bishop on f5 is hanging, so Black has no choice.} Bxd3 14. Bxe7 Bxe2 15. Bxd8 Bxd1 {It's important that the bishop on d8 can't attack anything.} 16. Rfxd1 Rxd8 {Engines still slightly prefer White here, but I don't think we risk much objectively.} 17. b4 a6 18. Rab1 Nd7 19. Na4 ({Obviously,} 19. a4 Nb6 {followed by ... Nc4 is an issue. And} 20. b5 {can be met by} cxb5 21. axb5 a5 {, with a dangerous passed pawn.}) 19... b5 20. Nb2 {White should bring the knight back to b2 and d3 .} Nb6 21. a4 bxa4 22. Ra1 a5 {Getting rid of one of the two weaknesses.} 23. Nxa4 Nxa4 24. Rxa4 axb4 25. Rxb4 Ra5 {Among many plans to hold, this one is straightforward. Black wants to push ... c5 .} 26. Rc1 c5 27. dxc5 Rc8 {Black wins the pawn back, and the isolated pawn on d5 isn't enough for White to dream about a win.} *

