t to get the pawn on h7 hanging (to the bishop on d3 ). Now, normally the bishop goes back to h4 , but we have to consider the other options.} 7. Bh4 {White keeps the pin.} Be7 {Now that f6 is protected, Black can play ... Bf5 without fearing Qf3 , destroying the pawn structure.} 8. Bd3 {The most logical move order, preventing ... Bf5 .} (8. Qc2 {also prevents ... Bf5 but it has no independent value.} O-O {and now White's only options are} 9. Bd3 {, which is a direct transposition to Bd3 O-O Qc2 , while Nf3} Ne4 {works too, and after} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Bd3 , we are in a variation we cover in Bd3 O-O} 11. Nf3 {.}) (8. Nf3 $6 Bf5 $1 {There is no reason to refrain from this move. After} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {, we transposed back into the 8.e3 variation .}) 8... O-O {For now, Black has kept many options concerning the knight on b8 and the bishop on c8 . Now, White has several different choices. It's usually at this moment that White needs to show which plan is on the agenda.  The two main plans are Nge2 , with f3 and e4 at some point, when play is directed at the center, and the other plan is Nf3 connected to Rb1 , b4 - b5 , called the minority attack, to create a weakness on the queenside (we have seen this plan several times already).} 9. Nge2 {Nowadays, this is the most common plan against the Queen's Gambit Declined. The long-term idea is to organize f3 followed by e4 and advance in the center. White doesn't want to play the minority attack and considers the center more important.} Ne8 ({With the same ideas as in Qc2} 9... Ne8 {, Black offers a bishop trade. I think White should decline it, but both options exist.}) 10. Bg3 {If White aims to create something here, White should keep pieces on the board. That doesn't change the position entirely, but it keeps more pressure on Black's shoulders.} Nd6 {Again, that's the point. The knight controls c4 and e4 and frees the way to the other knight on f6 . Also, it sometimes helps ... Bf5 .} 11. Qc2 Re8 {It's often nice to start with this logical move, keeping every option open, and having the possibility to attack the e3 -pawn in case of f2 - f3 .} 12. O-O {The bishop on g3 doesn't authorize White to castle queenside, as the launch of the pawns is difficult.} Bf8 {Again, directed against the e3 -pawn. Now, White has tried several options.} 13. Rad1 a5 14. Rfe1 Na6 15. a3 {Preventing ... Nb4 .} Bd7 {Black protects the c6 -pawn before possibly pushing ... b5 .} 16. Nc1 b5 {Securing the c4 -square for the knight.} 17. e4 b4 {Black distracts the knight before taking on e4 . That's why White should give up the dark-squared bishop.} 18. Bxd6 Bxd6 19. e5 Bf8 20. Na4 bxa3 21. bxa3 {Now, in the game ½-½ Rodshtein-Lupulescu, Chartres 2023, there was no reason to refrain from taking the hanging pawn on a3 .} Bxa3 22. Bxa6 Bxc1 23. Rxc1 Rxa6 {Black is a pawn up. It's clear that the knight will find a nice square on c5 , and Black has a few weaknesses, but it just means the position is balanced.} *


