1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. h3 {Normally, I would probably never have analyzed this move, but times are changing, and it appeared that no other than the reigning World Champion used it during his match against Ian Nepomniachtchi last April. Funny thing: this was played on the 10th of April 2023, and we can see almost half of the games in this position, played on the 11th of April in the Titled Tuesday tournament.  However, Ding lost this game, and I doubt it will ever remain a very serious attempt for White, at least among us mortals. To explain this move is far from easy. Let's say it's using a tempo to wait for Black to play, and h3 can also prove useful sometimes, like when White develops the bishop to f4 , to have a square on h2 . Black should play actively.} c5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Tarrasch Defense, where it will be hard for White to justify the move h3 .} ({In the famous World Championship game, Black continued in a Queen's Gambit Accepted style, which is also an option.} 4... dxc4 5. e3 c5 6. Bxc4 {, White is ready to accept an isolated pawn.  After} a6 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nc3 b5 9. Bd3 {, these positions exist with an extra tempo for White (or with a move more useful than h3 ), but it's still a decent position for White if White wants to fight for a very slight edge. Black went on to win in 0-1 Ding Liren-Nepomniachtchi, Astana 2023, which wasn't Ding's best game.}) 5. cxd5 {In this case, White is the side that wants to fight against the isolated pawn.} exd5 6. Nc3 Nc6 ({If dxc5 , then} 6... cxd4 {disrupts White's harmony.}) 7. e3 {Too slow. White blocks their own bishop.} c4 ({White is unable to break Black's queenside because after b3} 7... b5 {, the pawn on b5 is untouchable in view of ... Qa5 +.}) 8. Be2 Bb4 {Black will probably take on c3 at the right time to get the e4 -square for the knight; it also prevents any reaction with e3 - e4 .} 9. O-O O-O 10. Bd2 Re8 {Black has more space and will bring the bishop to f5 to secure the e4 -square. It's hard to see a real plan for White.} *


