1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. a3 ({In the same spirit as} 4. h3 {. But this time, I wouldn't go for ... c5 , as these Tarrasch systems often see White playing an early a3 with e3 . It helps when White wants to take on c5 followed by b4 to chase the bishop.}) 4... dxc4 {In the Queen's Gambit Accepted, it's less clear to me how White will make use of the a3 move.} 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 {Even if White doesn't start with this move, Black can organize ... c5 and ... a6 to threaten ... b5 .} c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black has already won the initiative and has a better development. We will probably try to push ... a6 and ... b5 soon.} *

