1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. a3 ({In the same spirit as} 4. h3 {. But this time, I wouldn't go for ... c5 , as these Tarrasch systems often see White playing an early a3 with e3 . It helps when White wants to take on c5 followed by b4 to chase the bishop.}) 4... dxc4 {In the Queen's Gambit Accepted, it's less clear to me how White will make use of the a3 move.} 5. e3 c5 ({We can also mention that} 5... b5 {is safe for Black. A normal reaction for White is to play a4 at some point, but a full tempo was lost with a3 . However, these positions have a tendency to be equal and a bit drawish after massive pawn trades on the queenside. I would prefer a normal Queen's Gambit Accepted line, with a3 being quite harmless.}) 6. Bxc4 a6 7. O-O Nbd7 {I like this slow, but flexible approach. We have time to decide later about our queenside approach. Sometimes, playing ... b5 too fast will help White achieve a4 (even if it means having lost the full tempo) to create a few weaknesses on the queenside.} 8. Qe2 b5 {White is not able anymore to bring the bishop to e2 , to continue with a4 , so I like ... b5 more now than one move earlier.} 9. Ba2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Bd6 {There is no reason to worry about the c-file, Black has everything under control.} 11. Nc3 Qc7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. b4 {In this case, the position becomes more symmetrical.} Bd6 14. Bb2 Rc8 15. Rac1 Qb8 {The queen reaches a safe place. Black will castle, and the knight on d7 is more flexible than White's on c3 , as it can reach b6 and potentially a4 , c4 , or d5 later.} *

