1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Nbd2 {I doubt this can be a very serious attempt for White. Black probably has a different option, but the Tarrasch Defense makes a lot of sense since the knight is unable to put pressure on d5 .} c5 {White is already under pressure in the center.} 5. e3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {White tries to avoid an isolated pawn, but this doesn't control the e5 -square anymore.} Be7 7. Be2 {Logical, but bringing the knight back to f3 was probably better because of Black's reply.} e5 8. N4f3 Nc6 {Suddenly, Black has a clear initiative in the center.} 9. O-O O-O 10. cxd5 Nxd5 {White is worse due to poor development.} *

