1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Nbd2 {I doubt this can be a very serious attempt for White. Black probably has a different option, but the Tarrasch Defense makes a lot of sense since the knight is unable to put pressure on d5 .} c5 {White is already under pressure in the center.} 5. e3 cxd4 6. exd4 dxc4 {Black forces an isolated pawn.} 7. Nxc4 {I think it's better to take with the knight because it will have to move anyway, while the bishop has a safe square on e2 .} Nc6 {There is a threat of ... Bb4 +, to trade the bishops, and sometimes even get the d4 -pawn.} 8. a3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 {Black has a good version of a white IQP. The knight on c4 (that should be on c3 ) has no control over the d5 -square. It means Black doesn't have to worry about d4 - d5 .} *

