1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Nbd2 {I doubt this can be a very serious attempt for White. Black probably has a different option, but the Tarrasch Defense makes a lot of sense since the knight is unable to put pressure on d5 .} c5 {White is already under pressure in the center.} 5. cxd5 {White tries to force us into an IQP.} cxd4 {An interesting option! Black doesn't want an IQP and takes on d4 instead.} 6. Nxd4 Qxd5 {The queen is nice here, as Nc3 is impossible. Also, it keeps an eye on the g2 -pawn.} 7. e3 Be7 {In order to castle, White has to trade the bishop on d7 .} 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {Black develops while taking back.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Qe2 Rfc8 {In the end, Black has a better development. Even if White manages to organize something for the c1 -bishop, the position would remain symmetrical and harmless for Black.} *

