1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Nbd2 {I doubt this can be a very serious attempt for White. Black probably has a different option, but the Tarrasch Defense makes a lot of sense since the knight is unable to put pressure on d5 .} c5 {White is already under pressure in the center.} 5. cxd5 {White tries to force us into an IQP.} cxd4 {An interesting option! Black doesn't want an IQP and takes on d4 instead.} 6. dxe6 Bxe6 {Black has a quick development, and the pawn on d4 bothers White's development. On the contrary, White will try to proove that it's more of a weakness.} 7. Nb3 Bb4+ {Black starts by trading the bishop. The real idea is more to bring White's queen on d2 in order to take on b3 .} 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Bxb3 {Black gets rid of an attacker of the d4 -pawn and weakens White's pawn structure.} 10. axb3 Nc6 {Black has managed to save the d4 -pawn.} 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 Re8 13. O-O Qb6 {The pawn on d4 is still annoying for White. Black has a slight initiative and will continue with ... Rad8 and probably ... Ne4 - c5 if we want to attack the b3 -pawn once more.} *

