1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Qc2 {This move is relatively flexible, and it contains some potential transpositions into other lines where White plays an early Qc2 .} dxc4 {In general, I am not afraid of the variations where White needs to get the queen to c4 to take the pawn back. That's not an exception (and it's even better like this when White didn't play Qa4 + because we don't have to protect against the check with a move we don't necessarily want to play so early).} 5. e4 {Ambitious, to take the center and recapture with the bishop, but that's not great.} b5 {Black fights to protect the pawn.} 6. a4 {Logical, in order to weaken our queenside and open the a-file.} c6 7. axb5 {Instead, White should develop the Kingside, to castle fast. When White tries to get the pawn back, things can go even worse quickly.} cxb5 8. b3 {White plays on the fact that the c4 -pawn can't move, otherwise, b5 falls. But Black can counterattack against the e4 -pawn.} Bb7 {Black attacks the e4 -pawn.} 9. e5 ({Instead,} 9. Nbd2 Bb4 {leaves White with similar problems.}) 9... Bxf3 {The point is to be able to take on d4 .} 10. gxf3 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Qxd4 {Black wins some material. If White takes on b4 , it's possible to first take the pawn on e5 , and only next the rook on a1 .} *

