1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. Bf4 {It seems a bit strange to develop the bishop so fast while c4 isn't protected and the diagonal a5 - e1 in front of the King is still open. I want to take advantage of both facts!} Bb4+ ({Even though} 4... dxc4 {is also interesting, I like to start with this check. I don't think so many people will play} 5. Bd2 {, which is the computer move, losing a full tempo. Among the many Black options, I like} Be7 {to retreat, while we don't see what the bishop is doing on d2 . Instead, White will probably develop the knight.}) 5. Nbd2 dxc4 {The idea is to follow with ... b5 soon, in order to protect c4 .} 6. e3 b5 7. a3 {It is necessary to ask where the bishop will go.} Ba5 {Everything was playable, but I prefer to keep the pin for now.} 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O Nd5 10. Bg3 Nd7 {Black simply remains better thanks to the extra pawn here.} *

