1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. cxd5 ({This is not a sideline, but we are only going to check the options where White doesn't transpose back into lines we have already seen with} 4. Nc3 {.}) 4... exd5 ({Clearly,} 4... Nxd5 {is met with} 5. e4 {, so we have no choice here.}) 5. g3 {A kind of a Catalan Variation, but it's a bad idea to take on d5 early in the Catalan. The reason is that Black's problem is usually developing the c8 -bishop, and White plans to push e4 at some point. Now that White took on d5 , it would create an isolated d4 -pawn ( e4 will also be harder or impossible because of ... Re8 and ... Bf5 ).} Bd6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Nc3 c6 {Black prevents Nb5 . On the next move, we will develop the bishop to f5 , with a nice position already.} *

