{That's the difference with Kd1 . Here, the rook is not hanging on c2 , so Black is winning.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. cxd5 ({This is not a sideline, but we are only going to check the options where White doesn't transpose back into lines we have already seen with} 4. Nc3 {.}) 4... exd5 ({Clearly,} 4... Nxd5 {is met with} 5. e4 {, so we have no choice here.}) 5. Qc2 ({This makes more sense to me than} 5. Qc2 {in the current chapter. It prevents ... Bf5 .}) 5... Bd6 {Without immediate pressure on d5 , this is a decent option for Black, preventing Bf4 .} 6. Bg5 {Logical too, but we have a reply.} h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nc3 {Black should be careful, as c6 falls after Nxd5 because the bishop is hanging on c8 .} Be6 {Black shouldn't be afraid of Nb5 .} 9. Nb5 {Let's see why this is a mistake.} Bb4+ 10. Nd2 O-O {The best. White isn't afraid to lose the c7 -pawn (and potentially the rook on a8 ).} 11. Nxc7 {The pawn grab doesn't work at all here.} Rc8 12. Nxd5 Rxc2 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 *

