1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. cxd5 ({This is not a sideline, but we are only going to check the options where White doesn't transpose back into lines we have already seen with} 4. Nc3 {.}) 4... exd5 ({Clearly,} 4... Nxd5 {is met with} 5. e4 {, so we have no choice here.}) 5. Qc2 ({This makes more sense to me than} 5. Qc2 {in the current chapter. It prevents ... Bf5 .}) 5... Bd6 {Without immediate pressure on d5 , this is a decent option for Black, preventing Bf4 .} 6. Bg5 {Logical too, but we have a reply.} h6 7. Bh4 Nc6 {The knight attacks the d4 -pawn and can sometimes go to b4 .} 8. Nc3 (8. e3 Nb4 {is good for Black, with ... Bf5 coming.}) 8... g5 9. Bg3 g4 {That was the idea. Black wins the d4 -pawn.} 10. Ne5 Nxd4 11. Qa4+ Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 ({Now, White should probably develop with e3} 12... O-O {, but Black has a nice position anyway.}) 13. Qxc6+ {This makes things worse.} Bd7 14. Qa6 d4 {When the knight moves, ... Bb4 + is a new option. That's why White should have traded it before.} 15. Bxd6 cxd6 16. Nd1 O-O {White's development is too poor.} 17. Qxd6 Qa5+ ({Also} 17... Be6 {is a good move, offering a great endgame for Black.}) 18. b4 Qg5 {Black prepares ... Rfd8 with great play. White's King is far from being safe.} *

