1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 {In this chapter, we are going to deal with many of White's sidelines on move 4 in the current position. First, we can mention that Nc3 is obviously the subject of the latter chapters of our repertoire. e3 will be analyzed in the next chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Then Bg5 will also have its own chapter, and finally, g3 will be dealt with in the chapter about the Catalan Variation. Let's have a look at the rest!} 4. cxd5 ({This is not a sideline, but we are only going to check the options where White doesn't transpose back into lines we have already seen with} 4. Nc3 {.}) 4... exd5 ({Clearly,} 4... Nxd5 {is met with} 5. e4 {, so we have no choice here.}) 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 {According to the engines, that's already not so great. But it simply means this whole idea of Bg5 doesn't work well for White in this move order.} g5 {Black gets rid of the pin to quickly bring the knight to e4 .} 7. Bg3 Ne4 {The threat here is ... Bb4 +, but that doesn't mean we are forced to bring the bishop there.} 8. Nc3 Nc6 (8... Bb4 9. Nd2 {transposes into well-known lines of the Ragozin Defense. Here, Black doesn't need to bring the bishop. White can't take on e4 because White would then need to move the knight and d4 would fall.}) 9. e3 {Let's agree that this is a logical move, but also a mistake.} h5 {Now, Black threatens to win a piece with ... h4 . White has no choice but to move the h-pawn.} 10. h4 Nxg3 {When White is forced to take back with the f-pawn, it's often a good sign to take the bishop.} 11. fxg3 g4 12. Ng1 {The knight tries to redirect itself towards e2 , to protect g3 and f4 to close the dark-squared diagonal towards g3 .} Bh6 {But the attack against e3 comes fast. That's the kind of line we are glad having not played ... Bb4 too soon, and White has some problems with the central pawns.} 13. Qd2 O-O 14. Nge2 Ne7 {The knight goes to f5 to attack both weaknesses. It seems that White will have to bring the King to f2 to protect everything. Black has a great position.} *

