1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. Bd3 {This is the second most played move in the position, but I don't think it's very accurate because it allows us to take on c4 , leading to a Queen's Gambit Accepted with an extra tempo: ... Be7 for Black. It's also sometimes transposing into the main lines of this chapter.} dxc4 {My preference. Black doesn't wait for b3 and forces the good transposition into a Queen's Gambit Accepted.} 6. Bxc4 a6 7. O-O O-O ({I think that to use the extra tempo for Black, the best way is to delay ... c5 . Otherwise,} 7... c5 8. dxc5 {will transpose into theoretical lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted when the bishop will take back on c5 (having lost the tempo of ... Be7 ).}) 8. a4 {White prevents ... b5 , so we go less far.} b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 (10. Nc3 {transposes into the 8.a4 main line .}) 10... Nbd7 11. b3 {A different development than Nc3 , avoiding transpositions into the main lines.} c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black brings the Queen to e7 and has a symmetrical position, but I think the ... a6 / a4 inclusion helps Black because the b4 -square is a weakness.} *

