1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. b3 {That's the classical way of handling the Colle System with White. I am going to focus on the main system for White, as the rest is not so dangerous. White can play in many different ways.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {I would like to clarify things in the center directly.} 7. dxc5 {This is one of the options that Black has to avoid in the main lines , but here it's not very dangerous, the center is traded directly.} dxc4 8. Qxd8 {White doesn't want to take back on d1 with the King.} Rxd8 9. Bxc4 Bxc5 10. O-O Nc6 11. Nc3 b6 {The position is completely equal in this symmetrical endgame.} *

