1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. b3 {That's the classical way of handling the Colle System with White. I am going to focus on the main system for White, as the rest is not so dangerous. White can play in many different ways.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {I would like to clarify things in the center directly.} 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. exd4 {White is ready to accept a hanging pair of pawns in the center because that brings dynamic play. This is the reason why we won't take on c4 immediately, we do it only if we have a reason to. As long as we keep the pawn on d5 , White isn't able to push d4 - d5 .} b6 9. O-O Bb7 ({The bishop is ready to come into play, we will just wait for the right time to take on c4 . Now, I think both Nc3 or Nbd2 are equally important systems, played as often. Let's mention that Qe2 has no independent value, as after} 9... Nbd7 {, White has to transpose into other lines with} 10. Nc3 {or Nbd2 .}) 10. Nbd2 {With this move, White has less pressure over d5 but wants to bring the knight to f1 , or perhaps to f3 after Ne5 .} Nbd7 ({That's a sideline in comparison to} 10... Nc6 {, but I prefer this option. It doesn't bother the bishop on b7 , it protects f6 , and can sometimes go to f8 to protect the King.}) 11. Qe2 Rc8 {Always useful. Sometimes, it opens the way for the Queen to go to c7 and then hide on b8 .} 12. Rad1 {A natural move. White puts pressure on the d-file and it's natural to move the Queen away.} Qc7 13. Rfe1 Rfd8 {Black improves the other rook.} 14. a3 {Sometimes, this move is useful to prevent ... Bb4 .} Bf8 {Black finds a useful plan, to place the bishop in fianchetto and have a better defense around the King.} 15. Ne5 {It's hard to advocate anything else for White.} g6 {Black continues the plan. There is no need to fear Nxf7? Kxf7 Qxe6 , as there is simply nothing for White after Kg7 .} 16. f4 {White tries to cement the knight on e5 .} Nh5 {The f4 -pawn is under attack, so White has to find a way to secure it.} 17. g3 dxc4 {Finally, Black opens the long diagonal for the bishop now that f4 and g3 have been played, weakening it.} 18. bxc4 Ng7 {The knight protects e6 and heads back towards f5 . Black is still in control, and White may have made too many weaknesses here.} *

