1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. b3 {That's the classical way of handling the Colle System with White. I am going to focus on the main system for White, as the rest is not so dangerous. White can play in many different ways.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {I would like to clarify things in the center directly.} 7. Bd3 cxd4 8. exd4 {White is ready to accept a hanging pair of pawns in the center because that brings dynamic play. This is the reason why we won't take on c4 immediately, we do it only if we have a reason to. As long as we keep the pawn on d5 , White isn't able to push d4 - d5 .} b6 9. O-O Bb7 ({The bishop is ready to come into play, we will just wait for the right time to take on c4 . Now, I think both Nc3 or Nbd2 are equally important systems, played as often. Let's mention that Qe2 has no independent value, as after} 9... Nbd7 {, White has to transpose into other lines with} 10. Nc3 {or Nbd2 .}) 10. Nbd2 {With this move, White has less pressure over d5 but wants to bring the knight to f1 , or perhaps to f3 after Ne5 .} Nbd7 ({That's a sideline in comparison to} 10... Nc6 {, but I prefer this option. It doesn't bother the bishop on b7 , it protects f6 , and can sometimes go to f8 to protect the King.}) 11. Qe2 Rc8 {Always useful. Sometimes, it opens the way for the Queen to go to c7 and then hide on b8 .} 12. Rac1 {White prevents ... Qc7 , so we have to find another way to get the Queen out of the d-file.} Rc7 {A clever and usual maneuver. The rook leaves the 8th-rank squares to the Queen. This can also help Black doubling rooks on the c-file.} 13. Rfd1 Qa8 {Black has time to bring the Queen on this nice diagonal.} 14. Ne5 Rd8 {We first increase the pressure on the d-file.} 15. f4 Nf8 {The knight can sometimes reach g6 to protect our monarch. It also frees the way for the d8 -rook.} 16. Ndf3 {It's logical to bring more pieces on the Kingside. The drawback is that it doesn't protect the e4 -square anymore, and our knight is able to get there.} Bd6 17. Qe3 {This protects the f4 -pawn, and the Queen can sometimes reach g3 or h3 . We are following a game for a few moves still.} Ne4 18. cxd5 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 exd5 20. Ng5 {In the game 1-0 Lubbe-Ghosh, Walsrode 2023, White went for a direct attack towards f7 . Black should have trusted his position and play ... f6 .} f6 {This forces the next sequence of moves.} 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Bc4+ Bd5 {Of course, we can't allow Nf7 +, so we don't move the King.} 23. Qxe4 {Playing on the pin of the d5 -bishop.} Bxc4 24. Qxa8 Rxa8 25. Nxc4 Bxf4 {The material is equal as well as this endgame. But I would even prefer Black's side if we can put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} *

