yed as often. Let's mention that Qe2 has no independent value, as after} 9... Nbd7 {, White has to transpose into other lines with} 10. Nc3 {or Nbd2 .}) 10. Nc3 {A logical move. White puts pressure on d5 .} Nbd7 ({As against 10.Nbd2 , I prefer this move instead of} 10... Nc6 {, which is the main line, for the same reasons: it can go to f8 at some point, it doesn't bother the b7 -bishop, and it protects the knight on f6 .  If the bishop was on d6 instead of e7 , I might see things differently, as ... Nc6 allows the knight to go to e7 and potentially f5 . But that's not the case here, and I don't want to spend a tempo playing ... Bd6 .}) 11. Qe2 {White improves the Queen, controls e5 , and enables the rooks to come to the center.} Qc7 {There is no rook on c1 , so Black brings the Queen here immediately. It also provokes Rac1 , but that's not forced and White may understand Black's plan.} 12. Rad1 Rad8 (12... Qf4 {is less efficient than after Rac1 because the pawn on d4 would be safely protected by the rook, and Bc1 becomes an option to challenge it.}) 13. Ne5 {It's hard to advise anything else for White, but we still have the same reply.} dxc4 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. Nb5 Qc6 17. f4 a6 18. Nd4 Bc5 ({Black has the same plan as in the} 18... Nxe5 {line: to take on d4 followed by ... Nc5 .}) *

