yed as often. Let's mention that Qe2 has no independent value, as after} 9... Nbd7 {, White has to transpose into other lines with} 10. Nc3 {or Nbd2 .}) 10. Nc3 {A logical move. White puts pressure on d5 .} Nbd7 ({As against 10.Nbd2 , I prefer this move instead of} 10... Nc6 {, which is the main line, for the same reasons: it can go to f8 at some point, it doesn't bother the b7 -bishop, and it protects the knight on f6 .  If the bishop was on d6 instead of e7 , I might see things differently, as ... Nc6 allows the knight to go to e7 and potentially f5 . But that's not the case here, and I don't want to spend a tempo playing ... Bd6 .}) 11. Qe2 {White improves the Queen, controls e5 , and enables the rooks to come to the center.} Qc7 {There is no rook on c1 , so Black brings the Queen here immediately. It also provokes Rac1 , but that's not forced and White may understand Black's plan.} 12. Rac1 Qf4 {The Queen flees away from the c-file. It's surprisingly fine here, from where it controls the center. In case of g3 , the Queen can stay around, on g4 .} 13. Ne5 dxc4 {Finally, Black opens the bishop's diagonal.} 14. bxc4 ({Of course, it's never possible to take with Qxd4 because of the discovered attack} 14. Nd5 {.}) 14... Rfd8 ({Here,} 14... Nxe5 {is not recommended as in this variation since after} 15. dxe5 Ng4 16. g3 {, the Queen doesn’t have any great square. For instance,} Qf3 {is answered with} 17. Nd5 $1 {and White wins some material.  Instead, Black has to rely on Nd7 , when White can force a draw with Bxh7+ Kxh7} Qxd3 {Kg8 Qxd7 Bxg2} 18. Kg2 {Qg4+= . After the text move, we can keep the game going and still ask White some questions.}) 15. Rfd1 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 {Black threatens to take on e5 , or to bring the knight to c5 . Of course, White can protect the pawn, but that would be passive. Instead, White can go for the tactics.} 17. g3 {Daring Black to take on e5 with the Queen. But we can do it!} Qxe5 (17... Qh6 {is a possible alternative for Black and less forcing. After} 18. Be4 Bxe4 19. Nxe4 Qg6 20. Rd4 Nc5 21. Nd6 {, the position remains complicated; both sides have great knights, which the bishops are, potentially, able to take.}) 18. Nd5 Qd6 {This solves both problems.} 19. Qe4 Nf8 {The knight secures h7 . We don't want to move a pawn and create new weaknesses instead.} 20. Qg4 {White continues the mating threats, forcing our replies.} Ng6 21. Bxg6 {White opens the d-file. We are losing the Queen, but that's fine.} hxg6 22. Nf6+ {White wins the Queen, there's nothing else to try.} Bxf6 23. Rxd6 Rxd6 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Rd1 {Black's rook is quite useful when alone, so White should trade it if possible.} Rad8 26. Rxd6 Rxd6 {To me, Black has no big risk here, while White can sometimes be in trouble with the King because of the weak light squares. Also, the c4 -pawn is just a weakness, as it's blocked on a light square. Anyway, the most likely result is a draw.} *

