1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. Nc3 ({The main position, and a transposition into} 5. Nc3 {Be7 e3 too.}) 5... O-O {White has tried a wild variety of moves here, as on the previous move, and some are similar.} 6. a3 {This feels slow. Black has time to continue development while preventing any ideas of c4 - c5 .} b6 7. b4 {Again, White wants c5 . We can again prevent it.} c5 8. bxc5 bxc5 {Black is better developed so the opening of the center should be to our advantage.} 9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bxc4 Bxc5 {Here, the position is symmetrical, but with a few extra tempi for Black. We can try to play ... Nc6 - a5 to chase the bishop, eventually go to b3 , or play ... Ba6 , depending on where the white bishop retreats.} *

