1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. Nc3 ({The main position, and a transposition into} 5. Nc3 {Be7 e3 too.}) 5... O-O {White has tried a wild variety of moves here, as on the previous move, and some are similar.} 6. Bd3 {By far the main move here. I must admit that it's a bit strange to me because Black can so easily reach a good version of a Queen's Gambit Accepted...} dxc4 {Of course, the bishop has to move again.} 7. Bxc4 {Usually in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, White is supposed to take back on c4 in one move, with the bishop directly on f1 . That's a loss of a full tempo. Also, the knight isn't necessarily well-placed on c3 . The reason is that Black usually tries to push ... a6 and ... b5 (if we are allowed to).  When White would like to challenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. a4 {So here White prevents ... b5 , at least the knight makes sense on c3 . But it's still transposing into lines where Black is normally a tempo down.} b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qe2 c5 {Here, I prefer to play this move before ... Nbd7 . The reason is that White has weakened a few squares on the Queenside, such as b4 and a5 , so the knight might want to get there via c6 .} 11. dxc5 bxc5 {Not too typical of our variation, so it's better to remember this exact position and move! Black secures the b4 -square, which can also allow us to use the b-file for the rook.} 12. e4 Nc6 13. e5 {Now we will deviate from the game 0-1 Plotkin-Ngo, Charlotte 2022.} Nd7 14. Bf4 Nb6 {Black chases the bishop away.} 15. Bd3 Nd5 {And finally, the knight heads back to the center.} 16. Qe4 g6 17. Bh6 Re8 {Black has a few weaknesses around the King, but White doesn't have the pieces right now to use them. Meanwhile, ... Ncb4 arrives fast to open the diagonal for the b7 -bishop.} *

