allenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. a4 {So here White prevents ... b5 , at least the knight makes sense on c3 . But it's still transposing into lines where Black is normally a tempo down.} b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qe2 c5 {Here, I prefer to play this move before ... Nbd7 . The reason is that White has weakened a few squares on the Queenside, such as b4 and a5 , so the knight might want to get there via c6 .} 11. Rd1 Qc7 {The Queen leaves the d-file.} 12. b3 {A slow approach, but I don't like the idea of bringing the bishop to b2 , where it will be blocked by the pawn on d4 .} Nc6 13. Bb2 cxd4 14. exd4 ({The problem is that White can't keep a piece on d4 because of} 14. Nxd4 Ne5 {, taKing the c4 -bishop.}) 14... Nb4 15. Rac1 {White gets d4 - d5 ideas. There is no time for moving the a8 -rook before ... Qb8 , so instead, Black prevents d5 .} Rfe8 {The right idea. Now White also has problems with the Queen in case of d5 .} 16. Ne5 {White threatens Nxf7 followed with Qxe6 +.} Bd6 {The Queen can go to e7 , if necessary. It looks like a good IQP for Black, as White doesn't have a real attack.} *

