1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 ({This is the Colle System, a very old sideline for White. Usually, White even plays it without an early c4 (like d4} 4. cxd5 {Nf3 Nf6 e3 ), but sooner or later c4 remains logical and there will be some transpositions. The point is to protect the pawn on c4 directly, to fianchetto the Queenside bishop, and slowly advance in the center.}) 4... Be7 ({This is not the only option for Black, but I have decided to keep this move because the Colle System can also be reached via Nc3} 4... Be7 {e3 , where the bishop is committed already.}) {Now, I have decided to keep Nc3 as the main line because of the possible transposition and because it's the most played move, but b3 is more in the spirit of the Colle System, and it's also very important.} 5. Nc3 ({The main position, and a transposition into} 5. Nc3 {Be7 e3 too.}) 5... O-O {White has tried a wild variety of moves here, as on the previous move, and some are similar.} 6. Bd3 {By far the main move here. I must admit that it's a bit strange to me because Black can so easily reach a good version of a Queen's Gambit Accepted...} dxc4 {Of course, the bishop has to move again.} 7. Bxc4 {Usually in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, White is supposed to take back on c4 in one move, with the bishop directly on f1 . That's a loss of a full tempo. Also, the knight isn't necessarily well-placed on c3 . The reason is that Black usually tries to push ... a6 and ... b5 (if we are allowed to).  When White would like to challenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. O-O b5 {Usually, in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black starts with ... c5 before ... b5 . But here, I think it's better to start with ... b5 .} ({It gives better chances to use the extra tempo (because of the line} 8... c5 9. dxc5 {, where the e7 -bishop will have to move again to take back on c5 , losing the extra tempo (it usually takes back from f8 ). Here, if Black manages ... c5 , we will take back with the knight in most cases. White has now 3 possible retreats for the bishop.}) 9. Bd3 {This is the main continuation. White controls the center, and allows the Queen to come to e2 .} Bb7 10. a3 {Here too, White would like to prevent ... c5 by playing b4 , and a3 also prevents most ... b4 ideas. But this is slow, and Black has time to play ... c5 .} c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 ({There is no time for} 11... Nbd7 {because of} 12. b4 {.}) 12. b4 Be7 13. Qe2 Nbd7 14. Bb2 {White has leveled the game (even if engines already slightly prefer Black, I think it will be tough to keep a real initiative). Black's only edge is the knight on d7 (if we compare with the one on c3 ) that can reach b6 to go to c4 or d5 at some point.} Bxf3 {An interesting possibility.} 15. gxf3 ({White can't take with the Queen because} 15. Qxf3 Ne5 {wins the bishop on d3 .}) 15... Ne5 16. Rfd1 Nxd3 17. Rxd3 Qb6 {Black keeps a slightly better Kingside.} 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 Rfd8 20. Qg4 Bf8 {The position is still roughly balanced, but I would take Black's side because we have a safer King in the long term.} *

