allenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. O-O b5 {Usually, in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black starts with ... c5 before ... b5 . But here, I think it's better to start with ... b5 .} ({It gives better chances to use the extra tempo (because of the line} 8... c5 9. dxc5 {, where the e7 -bishop will have to move again to take back on c5 , losing the extra tempo (it usually takes back from f8 ). Here, if Black manages ... c5 , we will take back with the knight in most cases. White has now 3 possible retreats for the bishop.}) 9. Bd3 {This is the main continuation. White controls the center, and allows the Queen to come to e2 .} Bb7 10. e4 {The most ambitious try, taKing over the center immediately, but Black has just the time to react in the center.} c5 {When the d4 -pawn disappears, White's center is less impressive.} 11. e5 {With the pawn on e5 , Black sometimes should be careful with the King, but we keep a safe position here.} Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Re1 {White wants to fight the bishop and Queen battery with Be4 .} c4 14. Be4 Qd7 {The problem for White if trading the light-squared bishop is that there will be no chance for an attack on the Kingside. Black will use the great square on d5 and the long-term initiative that the pawn majority brings us on the Queenside.} *

