allenge the b5 -pawn with a4 , then ... b4 attacks the knight on c3 (while normally it's still on b1 ), and there is not necessarily a better square than b1 to go back to d2 .} a6 {Black prepares ... b5 . White should decide whether to allow it or not.} 8. O-O b5 {Usually, in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, Black starts with ... c5 before ... b5 . But here, I think it's better to start with ... b5 .} ({It gives better chances to use the extra tempo (because of the line} 8... c5 9. dxc5 {, where the e7 -bishop will have to move again to take back on c5 , losing the extra tempo (it usually takes back from f8 ). Here, if Black manages ... c5 , we will take back with the knight in most cases. White has now 3 possible retreats for the bishop.}) 9. Bd3 {This is the main continuation. White controls the center, and allows the Queen to come to e2 .} Bb7 10. e4 {The most ambitious try, taKing over the center immediately, but Black has just the time to react in the center.} c5 {When the d4 -pawn disappears, White's center is less impressive.} 11. dxc5 Nbd7 {Black would prefer to take back on c5 with the knight, to attack the center.} 12. b4 {White tries to protect the c5 -pawn.} a5 {White is unable to keep the Queenside intact.} 13. Ba3 axb4 14. Bxb4 Bxc5 {Black takes the pawn back.} 15. a3 Qb6 {Now b5 is hanging, but e4 would fall, and the a3 is also not so great. The position is roughly balanced. Black will bring the rook to d8 or c8 soon. Even if we only traded 3 pawns, I would say the position has already a high chance of ending up in a draw, as there may not be any pawn on the Queenside soon.} *

