1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. e3 {That's a little bit too shy for White, trying to attack the pawn, but it doesn't take possession of the center.} b5 {Of course, we should hold it here.} 6. a4 c6 7. Be2 ({Instead,} 7. Nc3 a6 {transposes to the 6.Nc3 variation .}) 7... Bb4+ {Black develops fast.} 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. O-O {Now that White has castled, the pawn on b5 is hanging.} Qb6 {Black will develop as in the Semi-Slav, with ... Bb7 , ... O-O , ... a6 , and at some point we will try to push ... c5 .} *

