1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. e3 {That's a little bit too shy for White, trying to attack the pawn, but it doesn't take possession of the center.} b5 {Of course, we should hold it here.} 6. Nc3 a6 {Black tries to avoid playing ... c5 . If we can manage ... c5 in one move, this is an improvement. But White can force matters.} 7. a4 c6 {Black protects the b5 -pawn, which is very logical.} 8. axb5 cxb5 9. Nxb5 {Here White prefers to keep the dark-squared bishop on the board.} axb5 {This is a common sacrifice in some QGA and Slav systems.} 10. Rxa8 Bb7 {The rook has no better square than to return to a1 .} 11. Ra1 Bb4+ 12. Nd2 e5 {So far, we continue in the same way as with Bxf6 and ... gxf6 included. Black wants to open the center.} 13. Be2 {The main move, but it's not great.} Qd5 {This was played only once.} 14. f3 {That's not better.} exd4 {The bishop on g5 is hanging.} 15. Bf4 O-O {We keep the pawn on d4 , and we can quickly bring the rook to e8 if the center opens up.} 16. e4 Nxe4 {White has too many hanging pieces if fxe4 .} 17. O-O Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Bc5 {Black had two powerful pawns for an exchange and was completely winning in 0-1 Satkar-Raja, Mumbai 2018.} *

