1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. e4 {White takes control of the center, which makes a lot of sense, obviously. But e5 isn't a real threat, so we have time to react in the center.} c5 (5... b5 $5 {is also an interesting option for Black. But White has developed the following interesting line recently:} 6. a4 c6 7. Nc3 Qb6 8. Be2 {. White can castle quickly followed by d4 - d5 ideas. The position is tense and complicated.}) 6. Bxc4 cxd4 7. O-O {White tries to avoid any check on b4 , before taKing back on d4 .} Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 ({To get the pawn back, White needs to get rid of the bishop pair. Since Bxc6 + is coming next, playing} 8... a6 {instead is less accurate. We will get a worse structure since we have to take on c6 with the pawn, while the c8 -bishop won't get developed either.}) 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Nxd4 Bc5 {As we haven't castled yet, I find it too dangerous to take on e4 , and this looks much safer.} 11. Nxc6 {A natural move, but Black has a surprise.} Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Nxe4 {White has several pieces hanging and will end up with a pawn down.} *

