1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. e4 {White takes control of the center, which makes a lot of sense, obviously. But e5 isn't a real threat, so we have time to react in the center.} c5 (5... b5 $5 {is also an interesting option for Black. But White has developed the following interesting line recently:} 6. a4 c6 7. Nc3 Qb6 8. Be2 {. White can castle quickly followed by d4 - d5 ideas. The position is tense and complicated.}) 6. e5 {Highly similar to the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav, but it's a worse version for White.} h6 {We won't lose a piece so easily, we challenge the bishop.} 7. Bh4 g5 8. Nxg5 ({In case of} 8. Bg3 Nh5 {will get the bishop pair for Black, who has the initiative thanks to the pressure in the center. Instead, the text move is a blunder.}) 8... Qa5+ {Black unpins the knight!} 9. Nc3 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Ne4 {Of course, Black is completely winning with an extra piece.} *

