1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Qa4+ {White decides to attack the c4 -pawn immediately. Black has different ways to continue.} Nbd7 {With this move, Black also prepares ... c5 .} 6. Qxc4 {The natural continuation, but White's development is slow in this line. That's why, we should fight back immediately in the center.} c5 7. e3 a6 {Black threatens ... b5 and a4 doesn't prevent it anyway!} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 b5 {It feels clear that Black takes over the initiative.} 10. Qd3 Bb7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nb6 {Instead, Black can develop the pieces logically with ... Qe7 and ... Rfd8 , but the endgame looks also nice for Black. And it's not easy for White to avoid it. For instance:} 13. Nd4 Bxd4 14. exd4 {This leaves White with a weak isolated pawn.} h6 15. Bh4 Nbd5 16. Bf3 Qb6 {I prefer Black's position, being both solid on the Kingside and active on the Queenside, with long-term play against the weak d4 -pawn.} *

