1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Nc3 {The most natural reply, I would say. White trusts the position, is willing to push e4 , and prevents ... b5 or the venue of the bishop to b4 with check.} ({This is a position commonly played in the Vienna, via the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 dxc4 Bg5 , but the line is known to be almost dubious for White.}) 5... a6 ({Now, let's start by mentioning that e3} 5... b5 {transposes back into the 5.e3 variation , so we don't need to cover this possibility anymore. With the last move, Black prepares ... b5 once more. We are not happy that White just prevented it!}) ({Also, we can mention that indeed,} 5... Bb4 6. e4 {transposes into the classical line of the Vienna.}) 6. e4 {The engines believe this is the best continuation, but in a practical game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. a4 ({Trying to challenge the b5 -pawn.} 7. b4 {is a good option, but I prefer to play for a fast development.}) 7... Bb7 {Black sacrifices the pawn back.} 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 {As e4 is hanging, White can't take on b5 immediately.} 10. e5 h6 {Of course, that will always be the reaction to e5 .} 11. Bh4 ({This was seen in a high-level blitz game, but it's even worse than} 11. Bd2 {.}) 11... g5 12. Nxg5 {The classical temporary piece sacrifice, gaining a pawn for White in the end.} hxg5 13. Bxg5 Nbd7 14. exf6 {The game 0-1 Sevian-So, chess.com 2022, saw the developing Bb4 , but it seems we have a stronger continuation.} b4 {The knight has to move.} 15. Ne2 Nb6 16. h4 Qd5 {Black activates the Queen and secures the c4 -pawn. We remain with a great counterplay on the Queenside and we must be better.} *

