al game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. a4 ({Trying to challenge the b5 -pawn.} 7. b4 {is a good option, but I prefer to play for a fast development.}) 7... Bb7 {Black sacrifices the pawn back.} 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 {As e4 is hanging, White can't take on b5 immediately.} 10. e5 h6 {Of course, that will always be the reaction to e5 .} 11. Bd2 {White forgets the pin, to take on b5 while not fearing ... Bb4 +.} Nd5 12. Nxb5 Nb6 {The knight comes to the rescue of the c4 -pawn. Now, d4 also experiences some problems, and ... c5 is also a good option to trade one of the double c-pawns. Also, the bishop on a8 is a monster!} *

