1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Nc3 {The most natural reply, I would say. White trusts the position, is willing to push e4 , and prevents ... b5 or the venue of the bishop to b4 with check.} ({This is a position commonly played in the Vienna, via the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 dxc4 Bg5 , but the line is known to be almost dubious for White.}) 5... a6 ({Now, let's start by mentioning that e3} 5... b5 {transposes back into the 5.e3 variation , so we don't need to cover this possibility anymore. With the last move, Black prepares ... b5 once more. We are not happy that White just prevented it!}) ({Also, we can mention that indeed,} 5... Bb4 6. e4 {transposes into the classical line of the Vienna.}) 6. e4 {The engines believe this is the best continuation, but in a practical game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. e5 {The most concrete continuation for White (but has a pathetic score around 25%).} h6 {Black isn't planning on losing a piece.} 8. Bh4 {The rest is nothing.} g5 9. Nxg5 ({Once again forced. In case of} 9. Bg3 Nd5 {followed by ... Bb4 and ... Bb7 is much better for Black.}) 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 {White is about to get the piece back, but Black has different continuations.} Nbd7 {The most logical. Black protects the knight but doesn't plan to take back if the pawn comes to f6 .} 11. Qf3 {This could make a difference in White's favor, as the Queen develops and attacks the rook, but in the end, the bishop will reach b7 anyway.} Rb8 12. exf6 Bb7 13. Qe3 Nxf6 {True, Black has lost the option to castle on the Queenside, but we remain with a great position anyway. For instance, let's have a look at the following game.} 14. d5 {Concrete, but wrong.} Nxd5 {Unfortunately for White, this is permitted.} 15. Qd4 Qxg5 {Black sacrifices the other rook for the active bishop.} 16. Qxh8 Nb4 {The price to pay for the exchange is too high for White.} 17. Rd1 Nc2+ 18. Ke2 Ke7 ({Black is getting some ideas of ... Bh6 . Also, it's hard to find a useful move for White. Objectively,} 18... b4 {was strong too.}) 19. Qh7 Bh6 20. Ne4 Qf4 {That's it, White's position collapses.} 21. g3 Bxe4 22. gxf4 Bxh7 {White resigned two moves later in 0-1 Izzat-Illingworth, Cammeray 2018.} *

