al game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. e5 {The most concrete continuation for White (but has a pathetic score around 25%).} h6 {Black isn't planning on losing a piece.} 8. Bh4 {The rest is nothing.} g5 9. Nxg5 ({Once again forced. In case of} 9. Bg3 Nd5 {followed by ... Bb4 and ... Bb7 is much better for Black.}) 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 {White is about to get the piece back, but Black has different continuations.} Nbd7 {The most logical. Black protects the knight but doesn't plan to take back if the pawn comes to f6 .} 11. Be2 {White is trying to challenge the light-squared bishop by coming to the same diagonal.} Bb7 12. Bf3 ({A bad idea in the end, but White follows the initial plan. Instead,} 12. exf6 {is covered in the exf6 Bb7 Be2 line. Now, Black has a surprisingly strong move.}) 12... Nxe5 {Not really a piece sacrifice, as it enables the f6 -knight to avoid its sad destiny.} 13. Bxb7 {Again, going for the most challenging continuation, even if Black can remain much better.} Nd3+ 14. Kf1 Be7 {My preference. Black simply protects the knight and keeps the rook on a8 hanging. But in case of a check on c6 , the King is able to go to f8 , while it had to go to e7 otherwise. White has different options now.} 15. Bxa8 {Objectively, this can't be the best option for White.} Qxa8 16. Qf3 {Black is happy to reach this endgame.} Qxf3 17. gxf3 Nxb2 {Black's Queenside is too powerful, which is much more than enough for an exchange.} *

