al game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. e5 {The most concrete continuation for White (but has a pathetic score around 25%).} h6 {Black isn't planning on losing a piece.} 8. Bh4 {The rest is nothing.} g5 9. Nxg5 ({Once again forced. In case of} 9. Bg3 Nd5 {followed by ... Bb4 and ... Bb7 is much better for Black.}) 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 {White is about to get the piece back, but Black has different continuations.} Nbd7 {The most logical. Black protects the knight but doesn't plan to take back if the pawn comes to f6 .} 11. exf6 {The main and most logical continuation. White decides to take the knight first, before thinKing about something else, to avoid any bad surprises.} Bb7 {We are still in the main line of the Botvinnik Gambit with ... a6 instead of ... c6 . Usually, the game would continue with g3 , but that's impossible here. So that's where the play differs!} 12. d5 {White tries to close the long diagonal, but at the price of a few squares for our pieces.} Nc5 {The best move! The knight is protecting e6 , and can sometimes reach d3 . White scored less than 10% out of 27 games...} 13. dxe6 Nxe6 14. Qe2 {It's not a great idea to keep Queens on the board.} Qd7 {Black prepares ... O-O-O and is not afraid of the rook coming to d1 .} 15. Rd1 Bd6 16. Be3 O-O-O {I don't see how White will finish development and survive.} *

