al game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. e5 {The most concrete continuation for White (but has a pathetic score around 25%).} h6 {Black isn't planning on losing a piece.} 8. Bh4 {The rest is nothing.} g5 9. Nxg5 ({Once again forced. In case of} 9. Bg3 Nd5 {followed by ... Bb4 and ... Bb7 is much better for Black.}) 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 {White is about to get the piece back, but Black has different continuations.} Nbd7 {The most logical. Black protects the knight but doesn't plan to take back if the pawn comes to f6 .} 11. exf6 {The main and most logical continuation. White decides to take the knight first, before thinKing about something else, to avoid any bad surprises.} Bb7 {We are still in the main line of the Botvinnik Gambit with ... a6 instead of ... c6 . Usually, the game would continue with g3 , but that's impossible here. So that's where the play differs!} 12. d5 {White tries to close the long diagonal, but at the price of a few squares for our pieces.} Nc5 {The best move! The knight is protecting e6 , and can sometimes reach d3 . White scored less than 10% out of 27 games...} 13. dxe6 Nxe6 14. Qxd8+ {Probably the lesser evil, to reach an endgame where the initiative against the King is less important.} Rxd8 15. Be3 Nd4 {Black comes after the dark-squared bishop, but White isn't willing to give it up.} 16. O-O-O Nf5 17. Bd2 Bh6 {Eventually, Black would like to trade the bishop and get rid of the f6 -pawn. In the end, we remain with the strongest pawn majority and a powerful bishop on b7 . Let's see how it went badly for White in the following game:} 18. f4 {The bishop on h6 is shut down... or at least that's what White wants!} Rxd2 {A nasty surprise!} 19. Re1+ Kf8 20. Kxd2 Bxf4+ {A pawn is falling already, but it's not over yet.} 21. Kc2 Ne3+ 22. Kb1 b4 {By chasing the knight, Black is willing to continue with ... Be4 + with devastating effects. Black was winning in 0-1 Kornev-Frolyanov, Moscow 2011.} *

