al game, I'm not sure. It doesn't prevent ... b5 , so we have to go for it, as otherwise ... a6 made no sense.} b5 {This resembles a lot the Botvinnik Gambit of the Semi-Slav. So you might be afraid to enter this, as the variations are extremely complicated if you don't know them, but there is a major difference, which is in Black's favor: Black has played ... a6 instead of ... c6 . It's much better because the bishop on b7 will play directly, and ... c5 will come in one move (and the extra move ... a6 is useful to protect the b5 -pawn).} 7. e5 {The most concrete continuation for White (but has a pathetic score around 25%).} h6 {Black isn't planning on losing a piece.} 8. Bh4 {The rest is nothing.} g5 9. Nxg5 ({Once again forced. In case of} 9. Bg3 Nd5 {followed by ... Bb4 and ... Bb7 is much better for Black.}) 9... Nd5 {This is also a good option, but less explored. It's also playable in the Botvinnik Gambit version, but it's better here, as Black obtains good play.} 10. Nxf7 {The theoretical continuation in the Botvinnik Gambit.} Qxh4 11. Nxh8 Bb4 {Having ... a6 instead of ... c6 is a massive improvement for Black, who is better here.} *

