{Black has given up the bishop but has a huge initiative. Also Qg6+ is nothing, as the King escapes to d7 and c6 , leaving the white King unprotected in the end. Meanwhile, ... Qxe5 + is a threat with the knight hanging on h8 .} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Nc3 {The most natural reply, I would say. White trusts the position, is willing to push e4 , and prevents ... b5 or the venue of the bishop to b4 with check.} ({This is a position commonly played in the Vienna, via the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 dxc4 Bg5 , but the line is known to be almost dubious for White.}) 5... a6 ({Now, let's start by mentioning that e3} 5... b5 {transposes back into the 5.e3 variation , so we don't need to cover this possibility anymore. With the last move, Black prepares ... b5 once more. We are not happy that White just prevented it!}) ({Also, we can mention that indeed,} 5... Bb4 6. e4 {transposes into the classical line of the Vienna.}) 6. a4 {White keeps preventing ... b5 . But this time, this is a positional concession, as it weakens the b4 -square and also the a5 and b3 -squares.} Nc6 {Who can use all these weak squares? The knight comes to a5 to protect c4 and keep an eye on the b3 -square.} 7. e4 {That feels wrong, as the pawn on e4 is exposed. But it's a concrete approach that we need to check if the white pawn wants to get even further.} Na5 {We are not afraid of e5 , we prefer to protect the c4 -pawn.} 8. e5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 {As usual, the way to get rid of the pin.} 10. Nxg5 {The usual pseudo piece sacrifice.} Nd5 {The strongest line according to the engine, but not the main option according to the games.} 11. Nxf7 {That's even worse.} Qxh4 12. Nxh8 Bb4 13. Qc2 Qxd4 *

