1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Nc3 {The most natural reply, I would say. White trusts the position, is willing to push e4 , and prevents ... b5 or the venue of the bishop to b4 with check.} ({This is a position commonly played in the Vienna, via the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 dxc4 Bg5 , but the line is known to be almost dubious for White.}) 5... a6 ({Now, let's start by mentioning that e3} 5... b5 {transposes back into the 5.e3 variation , so we don't need to cover this possibility anymore. With the last move, Black prepares ... b5 once more. We are not happy that White just prevented it!}) ({Also, we can mention that indeed,} 5... Bb4 6. e4 {transposes into the classical line of the Vienna.}) 6. a4 {White keeps preventing ... b5 . But this time, this is a positional concession, as it weakens the b4 -square and also the a5 and b3 -squares.} Nc6 {Who can use all these weak squares? The knight comes to a5 to protect c4 and keep an eye on the b3 -square.} 7. e3 {A more timid development, but it will enable White to think about the c4 -pawn instead of going into a frenzy with the e-pawn.} Na5 {Here too, the knight comes to the rescue of the c4 -pawn.} 8. Nd2 Bb4 ({I like to start with this move, as it contains a trap in which White usually falls. However,} 8... c5 {is also safe for Black.}) 9. Be2 ({Instead,} 9. Nxc4 Qd5 {transposes to the main line .}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 c5 {Eventually, Black should push this pawn, to get rid of the d4 -pawn.} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nxc4 {Massive trades are occurring here.} Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Bb4 15. O-O Bd7 {I would still pick Black's side if I had to choose. The b4 -square is weak, ... Rc8 is coming, and sometimes the a4 -pawn remains hanging.} *

