 concession, as it weakens the b4 -square and also the a5 and b3 -squares.} Nc6 {Who can use all these weak squares? The knight comes to a5 to protect c4 and keep an eye on the b3 -square.} 7. e3 {A more timid development, but it will enable White to think about the c4 -pawn instead of going into a frenzy with the e-pawn.} Na5 {Here too, the knight comes to the rescue of the c4 -pawn.} 8. Ne5 {By far the main continuation. The knight is after our c4 -pawn.} Bb4 {Black doesn't seem to care about it and prefers to develop instead. Now, White took immediately most of the time, but there are other options.} 9. Qf3 {Not great. It doesn't create any real threat.} Qd5 {Of course, a trade there is great, to bring the knight and to attack on c3 once more.} 10. Bxf6 Qxf3 11. gxf3 gxf6 12. Nxc4 {In the best case, White ends up in a difficult endgame with the bishop pair for Black.} Nb3 13. Rb1 Bd7 {There is also a worse scenario, where White is paralyzed and loses the a4 -pawn... as well as ending up in an endgame with the bishop pair for Black.} *

