1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {At first sight, it's not easy to understand why White would delay the development of the b1 -knight (as the idea isn't to place it on d2 , where it would be passive).} ({The majority of the games that reach this position are from the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {, where White wanted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense (by playing 3.Nf3 ). And now Nc3 allows so many systems for Black as we already discussed.}) {So, by pinning the knight on g5 , White wants to provoke Be7 to transpose into the Queen's Gambit Declined. But Black also has different options here.} 4... dxc4 {That's my preference. Black immediately dares the opponent to get the pawn back, but Black may be willing to hold it!} 5. Nc3 {The most natural reply, I would say. White trusts the position, is willing to push e4 , and prevents ... b5 or the venue of the bishop to b4 with check.} ({This is a position commonly played in the Vienna, via the move order d4 Nf6 c4 e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 dxc4 Bg5 , but the line is known to be almost dubious for White.}) 5... a6 ({Now, let's start by mentioning that e3} 5... b5 {transposes back into the 5.e3 variation , so we don't need to cover this possibility anymore. With the last move, Black prepares ... b5 once more. We are not happy that White just prevented it!}) ({Also, we can mention that indeed,} 5... Bb4 6. e4 {transposes into the classical line of the Vienna.}) 6. a4 {White keeps preventing ... b5 . But this time, this is a positional concession, as it weakens the b4 -square and also the a5 and b3 -squares.} Nc6 {Who can use all these weak squares? The knight comes to a5 to protect c4 and keep an eye on the b3 -square.} 7. e3 {A more timid development, but it will enable White to think about the c4 -pawn instead of going into a frenzy with the e-pawn.} Na5 {Here too, the knight comes to the rescue of the c4 -pawn.} 8. Ne5 {By far the main continuation. The knight is after our c4 -pawn.} Bb4 {Black doesn't seem to care about it and prefers to develop instead. Now, White took immediately most of the time, but there are other options.} 9. Nxc4 {It feels like a mistake, but that's also the most common move.} Qd5 {A strong move. Black doesn't help the opponent to develop. Instead, the Queen comes to attack c4 , g5 , and g2 .} 10. Bxf6 {More or less forced, not to allow ... Qxg5 .} Nxc4 {A strong intermediate move! The bishop on f6 as well as the b2 -pawn are hanging.} 11. Qe2 {This has been tried twice.} Nxe3 {Black refutes White's idea.} 12. fxe3 {Unfortunately for White, it's very easy to play for us.} gxf6 13. Qf2 Qb3 {0-1 Mardov-Andreikin, chess.com 2022. Black will follow up with ... Rg8 and enjoy a better position.} *

