 concession, as it weakens the b4 -square and also the a5 and b3 -squares.} Nc6 {Who can use all these weak squares? The knight comes to a5 to protect c4 and keep an eye on the b3 -square.} 7. e3 {A more timid development, but it will enable White to think about the c4 -pawn instead of going into a frenzy with the e-pawn.} Na5 {Here too, the knight comes to the rescue of the c4 -pawn.} 8. Ne5 {By far the main continuation. The knight is after our c4 -pawn.} Bb4 {Black doesn't seem to care about it and prefers to develop instead. Now, White took immediately most of the time, but there are other options.} 9. Nxc4 {It feels like a mistake, but that's also the most common move.} Qd5 {A strong move. Black doesn't help the opponent to develop. Instead, the Queen comes to attack c4 , g5 , and g2 .} 10. Bxf6 {More or less forced, not to allow ... Qxg5 .} Nxc4 {A strong intermediate move! The bishop on f6 as well as the b2 -pawn are hanging.} 11. Bxg7 {Logical. White gains a tempo on the rook.} Rg8 {This does accelerate our development, though.} 12. Bf6 Rg6 {The rook keeps chasing the bishop away.} 13. Be5 Nxe5 {Let's get rid of the bishop.} 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Qb3 {The easiest is to trade everything, to reach a comfortable endgame?} Bxc3+ 16. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 17. bxc3 Bd7 {Black has the more active position. The isolated pawns on the Queenside are a problem, and White is still unsure how the bishop should develop because of the g2 -pawn. Black's move should be ... O-O-O , to bring the King near the Queenside pawn majority.} *

