1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g4 {Among the moves that have been played only a few times, this one has adepts among the elite players. Mainly in blitz or rapid, of course, but still, we should be careful how we handle it. The basic idea is to harass the knight on f6 with g4 - g5 keeping in mind that the pawn is indirectly protected because after ... Nxg4 , White can regain the pawn with Rg1 and Rxg7 with a strong initiative.} O-O {Against these super-aggressive systems, I often think that quick and sound development is the best reply. So let's just castle for now, there is no reason to be too scared of g4 and to organize a long castle or not castle at all.} 6. Qc2 {The second most played move but a serious mistake. It is slow and sometimes the Queen is exposed here.} dxc4 {Finally, we can take the hanging pawn; it frees the d5 -square for the knight too.} 7. g5 Nd5 8. e4 Nb4 {Here we can see that the Queen is awkward on c2 .} 9. Qd1 c5 {Black reacts in the center, and I think we can see that White's plan to attack has backfired already. Castling long is already difficult, and the center isn't even fully opened yet!} *

