1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g4 {Among the moves that have been played only a few times, this one has adepts among the elite players. Mainly in blitz or rapid, of course, but still, we should be careful how we handle it. The basic idea is to harass the knight on f6 with g4 - g5 keeping in mind that the pawn is indirectly protected because after ... Nxg4 , White can regain the pawn with Rg1 and Rxg7 with a strong initiative.} O-O {Against these super-aggressive systems, I often think that quick and sound development is the best reply. So let's just castle for now, there is no reason to be too scared of g4 and to organize a long castle or not castle at all.} 6. g5 {The most direct and probably best approach. The knight has no choice but to get to the center, the rest would be too passive.} Ne4 ({White can't take the knight, as it would disrupt the piece harmony. Following} 6... Ne4 {dxe4 , we can take on either d4 or g5 after the attacked knight moves.}) 7. Qc2 {The Queen is stronger on d3 because it protects the c4 -pawn.} Nxc3 8. bxc3 {TaKing back with the Queen isn't the idea. Black would have possibilities of ... Bb4 sometimes, and the Queen cannot threaten the black Kingside from c3 .} dxc4 9. e4 c5 {Again, Black directly tries to open the center.} *

