1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g3 {Of course, this move reminds us of the Catalan Variation. But normally, White doesn't bring the knight to c3 so early. As White is also delaying the castle, we will try to quickly react in the center.} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 {It's quite far from the setup we analyze in the chapter on the Catalan, but no worries, this is a better version for Black than the usual main line of the Catalan. The fact that White has played Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. Qa4 {I think this is the worst of the 3 options, it's not very testing.} a6 {Sometimes, ... a6 doesn't create any threat, as ... b5 isn't protected by the a6 -pawn because of the pin, but here it does!} 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qb3 Bb7 10. O-O c5 {The plan is simple: when White takes this pawn, Black will try to take it back with the b8 -knight, to gain another tempo on the Queen.} 11. dxc5 Nbd7 12. Rd1 {White prevents ... Nxc5 but that's just fine, it's at the cost of the protection of the f2 -pawn, so let's attack it!} Bxc5 {Next move is ... Qb6 .} 13. Ne5 Qb6 {A strong reply anyway!} 14. Bxb7 {White tries to escape, but we can take on f2 safely.} Bxf2+ 15. Kf1 Qxb7 {Black is winning already, but things can get even worse for White.} 16. Nxd7 {Are we losing a piece? Not really.} Qh1+ {Winning immediately.} 17. Kxf2 Ng4# {A nasty surprise.} *

