layed Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. O-O {That's a logical move, hoping that Black isn't going to do anything concrete. We have the time to organize our Queenside, in order to try to protect the pawn on c4 .} Nc6 {Black attacks the d4 -pawn, so both Ne5 and Qa4 are prevented. And the threat is to protect the pawn on c4 with ... Rb8 and ... b5 , when it would be hard for White to get the pawn back.} 8. e4 {The most ambitious continuation. White takes over the center.} Rb8 {Black wants to continue with ... b5 .} 9. Be3 {It's easy to protect our pawn now.} b5 10. a3 {Necessary, to avoid losing the e4 -pawn.} a6 11. Qe2 Bb7 {The situation is difficult for White, who can't push either of the central pawns: playing e5 would create a great square for our knights on d5 , while d5 would just create a weak pawn on d5 . Black's plan is to activate the knight with ... Na5 - b3 .} *

