1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g3 {Of course, this move reminds us of the Catalan Variation. But normally, White doesn't bring the knight to c3 so early. As White is also delaying the castle, we will try to quickly react in the center.} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 {It's quite far from the setup we analyze in the chapter on the Catalan, but no worries, this is a better version for Black than the usual main line of the Catalan. The fact that White has played Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. O-O {That's a logical move, hoping that Black isn't going to do anything concrete. We have the time to organize our Queenside, in order to try to protect the pawn on c4 .} Nc6 {Black attacks the d4 -pawn, so both Ne5 and Qa4 are prevented. And the threat is to protect the pawn on c4 with ... Rb8 and ... b5 , when it would be hard for White to get the pawn back.} 8. e4 {The most ambitious continuation. White takes over the center.} Rb8 {Black wants to continue with ... b5 .} 9. Qe2 Nxd4 (9... b5 {is also an option, but if it's allowed, we can take this pawn as well.}) 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. e5 Nd7 13. Bf4 b5 {For now, Black has two extra pawns. White has to quickly develop an initiative to show some compensation.} 14. Ne4 {White challenges our Queen.} Qb6 15. Rd2 f5 {Weakening the center, but allowing Black to trade a few pieces and to move pieces to the Kingside. I think this is the right reaction.} 16. exf6 Nxf6 {White has compensation for the pawns but will face the hard task of keeping this initiative alive, otherwise, White can quickly end up lost.} *

