1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g3 {Of course, this move reminds us of the Catalan Variation. But normally, White doesn't bring the knight to c3 so early. As White is also delaying the castle, we will try to quickly react in the center.} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 {It's quite far from the setup we analyze in the chapter on the Catalan, but no worries, this is a better version for Black than the usual main line of the Catalan. The fact that White has played Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. O-O {That's a logical move, hoping that Black isn't going to do anything concrete. We have the time to organize our Queenside, in order to try to protect the pawn on c4 .} Nc6 {Black attacks the d4 -pawn, so both Ne5 and Qa4 are prevented. And the threat is to protect the pawn on c4 with ... Rb8 and ... b5 , when it would be hard for White to get the pawn back.} 8. e3 {The slower approach. White protects the pawn and intends to follow with Qa4 or Qe2 to get the c4 -pawn back.} Rb8 ({This renders Qe2 harmless, as} 8... b5 {would be the obvious reply.}) 9. Qa4 {White wants to take on c4 .} Nb4 {Black won't give up the pawn so easily. We want to continue with ... Bd7 , not caring that much about the a7 -pawn.} 10. Ne5 (10. Qxa7 Bd7 11. Ne5 {is just a transposition to 10.Ne5 .}) 10... Bd7 11. Qxa7 Qc8 {Black protects b7 . White needs to find a way to save the Queen quickly.} 12. Nxd7 {It's necessary to escape with the Queen.} Qxd7 13. Qa4 Qxa4 14. Nxa4 Rfd8 {Objectively, this endgame is still slightly favorable for Black. We have the more active pieces and a strong c4 -pawn, but at least White has managed to survive, which isn't always the case in this line.} *

