layed Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. Ne5 {In the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , Black has to play Nc6 to try to equalize, while c5 is well-known to bring a safe advantage for White. But here, things are different!} c5 {I think that's the right decision, to directly fight in the center. As I said, in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , that's not a great move. But here the difference is that White won't be able to take back with the rook on d1 .} 8. e3 ({This move, or any other move apart from} 8. dxc5 {is just weak.}) 8... Nc6 ({That is going to be a much better version than} 8... Nc6 {in the usual line.}) 9. O-O Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 {In positions with this pawn structure, White can sometimes create a nice initiative on the Kingside. Our main problem is the development of the Queenside, so this should be our first task.} Rb8 {Black prepares ... b5 , but White won't allow it so easily.} 12. a4 a6 13. a5 Qc7 {I would still take Black. We will need to push ... b5 and allow axb6 en passant, but we will open the b-file for our rook and will be able to trade the bishops on b7 .} *

