layed Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. Ne5 {In the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , Black has to play Nc6 to try to equalize, while c5 is well-known to bring a safe advantage for White. But here, things are different!} c5 {I think that's the right decision, to directly fight in the center. As I said, in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , that's not a great move. But here the difference is that White won't be able to take back with the rook on d1 .} 8. dxc5 {Even if White is not able to take back on d1 with the rook, that's the right move. White will try to prove a slight edge in a symmetrical position (thanks to the strong bishop on g2 ), but I don't feel it's a realistic goal.} Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White always has many different ways to play these positions but is usually not in a rush to take back on c4 .} 10. Nxc4 Nc6 11. Be3 Bb4+ {An annoying check, and that's why I think White would do better by castling first.} 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Bd7 {The bishop protects the knight against Bxc6 .} 14. Nc3 Nd4 15. Rc1 Bc6 {To me, this solves Black's problems as in the game ½-½ Markus-Saric, Austria 2022.} *

