1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. g3 {Of course, this move reminds us of the Catalan Variation. But normally, White doesn't bring the knight to c3 so early. As White is also delaying the castle, we will try to quickly react in the center.} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 {It's quite far from the setup we analyze in the chapter on the Catalan, but no worries, this is a better version for Black than the usual main line of the Catalan. The fact that White has played Nc3 instead of castling helps our position (as we will see when White has to take back on d1 and won't be able to do it with the rook).} {Now, I checked 3 different options for White: to recapture with the Queen, Qa4 , to recapture with the knight, Ne5 , which is a well-known theoretical move as well in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , and to castle immediately.} 7. Ne5 {In the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , Black has to play Nc6 to try to equalize, while c5 is well-known to bring a safe advantage for White. But here, things are different!} c5 {I think that's the right decision, to directly fight in the center. As I said, in the same position with O-O instead of Nc3 , that's not a great move. But here the difference is that White won't be able to take back with the rook on d1 .} 8. dxc5 {Even if White is not able to take back on d1 with the rook, that's the right move. White will try to prove a slight edge in a symmetrical position (thanks to the strong bishop on g2 ), but I don't feel it's a realistic goal.} Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White always has many different ways to play these positions but is usually not in a rush to take back on c4 .} 10. Nc3 ({I also like this move slightly less than} 10. O-O {because White loses the opportunity to play Be3 . It's not so clear whether White will be able to avoid castling and keep the King in the center.}) 10... Nc6 {The right decision! Anyway, White can't take both pawns on c4 and c6 .} 11. Nxc4 Nd4 {That's how we force White to castle.} 12. O-O Bb4 {The threat is to take on c3 and then on e2 .} 13. e3 {Forced, otherwise, Black could take on c3 and e2 .} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne2+ 15. Kh1 Nxc1 ({Instead,} 15... Nxc3 16. Ba3 {is dangerous because White suddenly has very active pieces!}) 16. Rfxc1 Rb8 17. Rab1 b6 {The position is equal, but White should be careful about not ending up much worse because of the weak c-pawns and the squares available on the c-file.} *

