{I like Black's prospects. We have a great bishop on e5 . The knight will be nice on c5 as well, but a bit pointless too, as it has nothing to attack. Perhaps this is a good moment to highlight White's deep idea behind Bb5 that we've seen previously: with the pawn on a6 , Nc5 would have at least attacked something.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. Qc2 {Even if that's usually the right square for the Queen, it doesn't mean that it should go there immediately! Here, it's probably too soon to say it's safe. Black immediately fights back in the center.} c5 6. cxd5 {Less played. It indeed seems dangerous to already have an unprotected knight on d4 .} cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O {The pawn can't take on e6 because the knight is hanging.} 8. Bg5 h6 {Black decides to offer the choice to give the bishop pair against an isolated pawn.} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. e3 exd5 11. Rd1 {The most logical move.} Nc6 {Immediately challenging the knight on d4 , and this can bring another pawn closer to the center, to protect d5 .} 12. Nxc6 {It's clear that Black has no problem if we are allowed to take on d4 .} bxc6 13. Be2 Rb8 14. O-O Be5 {Black centralizes the bishop and enables the Queen to come to f6 .} 15. b3 Qf6 16. Na4 Rd8 *

