1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. Qc2 {Even if that's usually the right square for the Queen, it doesn't mean that it should go there immediately! Here, it's probably too soon to say it's safe. Black immediately fights back in the center.} c5 6. cxd5 {Less played. It indeed seems dangerous to already have an unprotected knight on d4 .} cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O {The pawn can't take on e6 because the knight is hanging.} 8. Bg5 h6 {Black decides to offer the choice to give the bishop pair against an isolated pawn.} 9. Bh4 Nxd5 {In this case, it's probably better to have included the moves ... h6 and Bh4 before taKing on d5 . It's often nice not to have h7 hanging, and the King already has an escape. That's not much, but I don't see any drawback.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxd5 exd5 {The problem for White is that castling will take a few more moves.} 12. e3 Nc6 {Immediately challenging the knight on d4 .} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 {White isn't in time to take on c6 .} 14. Qxc6 {Let's see why!} d4 {The pawn on e3 is in trouble, and ... Qb4 + is also a threat.} 15. Qxa8 {White is too greedy.} Qb4+ {Next move is ... Bg4 +, winning the Queen.} *

