1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Bf4 {White uses the fact that ... Bd6 now would lose a tempo. But since the bishop on f4 does not put any pressure on our center, we can activate our light-squared bishop in return.} Bf5 {I think it's smart to start with this move here. The reason is that Qb3 isn't a problem, as we will see, and it prevents Qc2 .} 7. Qb3 {When the bishop leaves the c8 -square early, that's always a move we should consider. But here, Black has a thematic sacrifice.} Nc6 {The knight threatens to come to b4 , with deadly threats on c2 .} 8. e3 Na5 {Black forces the Queen to retreat.} 9. Qd1 c6 10. h3 {White prevents ... Nh5 , which would catch the bishop.} Qb6 {Finally, it's Black who takes over the initiative on the b-file.} 11. Qc1 O-O 12. Be2 Nc4 {Black has the initiative, and in case of b3 , then ... Ba3 is a big problem for White.} *

