1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Bf4 {White uses the fact that ... Bd6 now would lose a tempo. But since the bishop on f4 does not put any pressure on our center, we can activate our light-squared bishop in return.} Bf5 {I think it's smart to start with this move here. The reason is that Qb3 isn't a problem, as we will see, and it prevents Qc2 .} 7. h3 {A new move in this position, but a common idea otherwise, to push quickly g4 . With the knight already on f3 , it doesn't feel very scary though.} c6 8. g4 Be4 ({I prefer this move to} 8... Bg6 {, to avoid any Ne5 ideas. Black is not afraid to trade this bishop, as the knight coming to e4 would be great.}) 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Be2 O-O {I don't see much play for White at the moment.} 11. g5 Ne8 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne5 Bd6 {White should be careful about the recently made weaknesses, and the possible problems the King might face, which lacks a safe spot in the long-term. The position is still objectively balanced.} *

