1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Bf4 {White uses the fact that ... Bd6 now would lose a tempo. But since the bishop on f4 does not put any pressure on our center, we can activate our light-squared bishop in return.} Bf5 {I think it's smart to start with this move here. The reason is that Qb3 isn't a problem, as we will see, and it prevents Qc2 .} 7. e3 c6 8. Nh4 {White is not willing to tolerate the bishop on f5 , but this also exposes the knight on an unprotected square.} Bg4 9. Qc2 (9. f3 {is worse because it traps the knight on h4 , and the bishop can simply retreat to e6 .}) 9... Nh5 10. h3 {The only move not to end up worse with White!} Be6 11. Nf3 ({On} 11. Nf3 {, Black would have taken without hesitation on f3 and f4 , creating isolated triple pawns for White.}) 11... Nxf4 12. exf4 {So far we have been following the game 1-0 Gukesh-Nepomniachtchi, Dusseldorf 2023. Now I would prefer to play:} g6 {Black not only threatens ... Bf5 , which is easy to stop, but also prevents f4 - f5 .} 13. Bd3 Bd6 14. g3 O-O 15. O-O-O {This is the most logical continuation, especially since O-O was impossible because of the pawn hanging on h3 .} Na6 16. a3 b5 {Black plays as fast as possible on the Queenside and is ready to open files.} 17. Ng5 {The threat is Nxe6 followed by Bxg6 .} Qf6 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 {Both sides have their chances, and the middlegame promises to be complicated! Of course, Black will push ... b4 as soon as possible.} *

