d it prevents Qc2 .} 7. e3 c6 8. h3 Qb6 {This position is highly similar to a reversed London System, and it's known that these types of positions are roughly balanced.} 9. Bd3 {Here, I don't recommend Qxb2 , as after Bxf5 Qxc3+ Kf1 , Black is a pawn up, but White has tremendous play thanks to the bishop pair.} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 {We have already seen these types of positions several times before. Black will try to get a knight to e4 , while White's main plan is the minority attack.} *

