1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Qc2 {We have already seen many lines where White tries to prevent ... Bf5 , but not yet in this exact position!} O-O ({Instead, if we play} 6... g6 {, White could prevent us from castling with} 7. Bh6 {and I prefer to avoid this possibility.}) 7. Bf4 Nh5 {A smart move, before White is able to secure the bishop here.} 8. Bd2 Nf6 ({Of course, White can repeat moves (we have options to avoid this if necessary, such as} 8... c6 {) . But if White wants to play on, White will have to keep the bishop locked in on d2 or bring it to g5 , thus transposing to} 9. Bg5 {.}) 9. e3 Re8 10. Bd3 b6 11. O-O c5 {In these positions, the bishop on d2 is a bad piece, and Black should be able to have a nice initiative with the hanging pawns.} *

