1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Qc2 {We have already seen many lines where White tries to prevent ... Bf5 , but not yet in this exact position!} O-O ({Instead, if we play} 6... g6 {, White could prevent us from castling with} 7. Bh6 {and I prefer to avoid this possibility.}) 7. Bg5 g6 {White is unable to prevent ... Bf5 , and we castled already, so we are not afraid of Bh6 .} 8. e3 Bf5 9. Qb3 {Not surprisingly, a harmless double attack on d5 and b7 considering the tempo loss. White cannot take on d5 since the bishop on g5 will be hanging in the end, and taKing on b7 is a bad idea, as we can play ... Rb8xb2 .} (9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. O-O c6 {eventually transposes to the 6.Qc2 variation .}) 9... Nbd7 {Come on and take it if you dare!} 10. Qxb7 {It's overoptimistic to take this pawn.} Rb8 11. Qxa7 Rxb2 {Obviously, Black's threats and initiative are more than enough for a pawn. ... Bb4 , and even ... Qa8 , to take over the a-file, are dangerous threats.} *

