. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qb3 {, winning a pawn.}) 7. e3 (7. Qc2 g6 {is a direct transposition to the 6.Qc2 line .}) 7... h6 {I think that's the most accurate approach. Most of the time White will retreat to h4 , transposing to a position we have already seen, and the rest is not very dangerous.} (7... Bf5 {is also possible. White will most probably transpose to similar positions but also has a few extra options.} 8. Nh4 $5 {is one of the possible attempts for White. Here, ... Bh7 isn't allowed (in contrast to the 7...h6  Bh4 variation), and White can try to exploit the f5 -square. (Instead, after} Bd3 9. Bxd3 {Qxd3 , there is nothing new compared to our analysis.) Be6 Bd3 Black is still fine obviously, but things are less clear than after} h6 {.}) 8. Bf4 {It seems rather unusual to return to f4 , as ... h6 was useful anyway for Black.} Bf5 {Now that there is less pressure in the center, it's even easier to develop.} 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 *

