1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We develop following the standard pattern in the Queen's Gambit Declined. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this covers one of the main options for White! Also, Bf4 will be the next chapter's subject, and e3 will be included in the chapter about the Colle-Zuckertort System. Still, White has a few other options that we will discuss in detail now.} 5. cxd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 {isn't a viable option here because of} 6. e4 {, taKing over the initiative in the center.}) 6. Bg5 {This logical move is the main continuation here too.} c6 ({Instead,} 6... Bf5 {is met with the strong} 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qb3 {, winning a pawn.}) 7. e3 (7. Qc2 g6 {is a direct transposition to the 6.Qc2 line .}) 7... h6 {I think that's the most accurate approach. Most of the time White will retreat to h4 , transposing to a position we have already seen, and the rest is not very dangerous.} (7... Bf5 {is also possible. White will most probably transpose to similar positions but also has a few extra options.} 8. Nh4 $5 {is one of the possible attempts for White. Here, ... Bh7 isn't allowed (in contrast to the 7...h6  Bh4 variation), and White can try to exploit the f5 -square. (Instead, after} Bd3 9. Bxd3 {Qxd3 , there is nothing new compared to our analysis.) Be6 Bd3 Black is still fine obviously, but things are less clear than after} h6 {.}) 8. Bxf6 {I don't think this offers White anything. Giving up the bishop pair so early should ease us to get a comfortable position.} Bxf6 9. Bd3 {At least, White has managed to prevent ... Bf5 .} (9. b4 {is met with} Be7 10. Qb3 Bf5 {and Black enjoys a fine development by having prevented Bd3 . Also, the minority attack isn’t that scary here. Note that after} 11. a3 b5 {, Black stops it while} 12. a4 {isn’t permitted, and we will continue with ... a5 or ... Nd7 - b6 .}) 9... O-O 10. Qc2 {This move protects the knight on c3 , so ... c5 isn't strong anymore. But with the Queen here, the minority attacks are less dangerous if Black plans to play on the c-file.} Be6 11. O-O Nd7 12. b4 Rc8 {Black is ready to answer b5 with ... c5 .} 13. Rfc1 Be7 {Black brings the bishop to the active d6 -square and leaves the possibility for the Queen to reach f6 or h4 later, with possible attacks on the Kingside.} *

