retreat to h4 , transposing to a position we have already seen, and the rest is not very dangerous.} (7... Bf5 {is also possible. White will most probably transpose to similar positions but also has a few extra options.} 8. Nh4 $5 {is one of the possible attempts for White. Here, ... Bh7 isn't allowed (in contrast to the 7...h6  Bh4 variation), and White can try to exploit the f5 -square. (Instead, after} Bd3 9. Bxd3 {Qxd3 , there is nothing new compared to our analysis.) Be6 Bd3 Black is still fine obviously, but things are less clear than after} h6 {.}) 8. Bxf6 {I don't think this offers White anything. Giving up the bishop pair so early should ease us to get a comfortable position.} Bxf6 9. Bd3 {At least, White has managed to prevent ... Bf5 .} (9. b4 {is met with} Be7 10. Qb3 Bf5 {and Black enjoys a fine development by having prevented Bd3 . Also, the minority attack isn’t that scary here. Note that after} 11. a3 b5 {, Black stops it while} 12. a4 {isn’t permitted, and we will continue with ... a5 or ... Nd7 - b6 .}) 9... O-O 10. O-O ({The most common move. As against} 10. h3 {, I like Black's prospects when we try to fight directly in the center.}) 10... c5 {It's also completely possible to play other classical plans, but this could reach equality by force.} 11. Rc1 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc6 13. Nxc6 ({If White prefers to protect the knight with} 13. Nce2 {, Black can reinforce the pressure with} Qb6 {.}) 13... bxc6 14. Na4 Bd7 15. b3 Re8 16. Nc5 Bc8 {A complicated position has arisen. Black needs to develop the initiative on the Kingside, but we can also try on pushing ... d4 quickly to open the position for the bishops.} *

