1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. h3 ({White often has to face ... Nh5 to get the bishop in these lines, so here White decides to immediately prepare an escape. But it has to be too slow. And against slow moves, we should react quickly, so Black's next move becomes obvious. I chose the same move against} 6. Rc1 {and Qc2 , to make it easier to remember the lines.}) 6... c5 {That's a possibility against most of White's 6th moves. I chose a different path against the main line e3 , but it remains the best here when White just spent a tempo on h3 .} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {That makes already a big difference, White isn't able to take back on c4 immediately.} 8. e3 Nd5 {Black starts attacKing the bishop. White can't take the knight because then c4 would be safely protected.} 9. Be5 Nd7 10. Bxc4 Nxe5 11. Bxd5 {The only move, otherwise, Black takes on c3 and White ends up with an awful pawn structure.} Qc7 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Be4 Qxc5 {The game is equal, but Black has managed to keep the bishop pair, which compensates for White's better development.} *

