ly prepare an escape. But it has to be too slow. And against slow moves, we should react quickly, so Black's next move becomes obvious. I chose the same move against} 6. Rc1 {and Qc2 , to make it easier to remember the lines.}) 6... c5 {That's a possibility against most of White's 6th moves. I chose a different path against the main line e3 , but it remains the best here when White just spent a tempo on h3 .} 7. e3 ({That's proof that something went wrong already. After} 7. e3 {c5 , nobody would play h3 , however, that's a transposition.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 ({After} 8. exd4 b6 {, Black will take on c4 when the f1 -bishop moves and will get a comfortable isolated Queen pawn.}) 8... Nbd7 {The threat is ... e5 .} 9. Bh2 Nb6 10. cxd5 Nfxd5 {Black has developed quickly and now needs to find a solution for the bishop stuck on c8 .} 11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bf6 13. O-O e5 14. Nf3 Qe7 {The bishop will manage to develop soon, and this position is at least equal for Black.} *

