n b8 is probably better for Black, as it will prevent any c5 - c6 .}) 6... b6 {We challenge the c5 -pawn immediately.} 7. b4 {The logical attempt is to hold the pawn on c5 , but it's going to backfire if Black is precise.} a5 {Again, trying to break on the Queenside.} 8. a3 Ne4 {A strong move! This disrupts White's harmony on the Queenside. First, if taKing on e4 , White will have many hanging pieces in the center. White should try to protect the knight instead.} 9. Qc1 axb4 {Black opens the position. White is underdeveloped and needs to be careful.} 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Qxa1 Nc6 ({Now, if White plays} 11... b5 {Nb4 threatens both ... Nc2 + and ... bxc5 , protecting the knight and gaining a pawn. Black is winning already.}) 12. Qb2 bxc5 13. bxc5 g5 {White already spent some time moving the Queen around. But now Black comes after the bishop and takes more space.} 14. Bc1 Ba6 15. e3 Qa8 {Next move is ... Rb8 , with big threats coming on the Queenside.} *

