n b8 is probably better for Black, as it will prevent any c5 - c6 .}) 6... b6 {We challenge the c5 -pawn immediately.} 7. b4 {The logical attempt is to hold the pawn on c5 , but it's going to backfire if Black is precise.} a5 {Again, trying to break on the Queenside.} 8. a3 Ne4 {A strong move! This disrupts White's harmony on the Queenside. First, if taKing on e4 , White will have many hanging pieces in the center. White should try to protect the knight instead.} 9. Rc1 axb4 10. axb4 Nc6 {Black's goal is to force the pawn to advance in order to weaken the c5 -pawn. If the Queen comes to b3 , the rook will come to b8 at some point to chase it away.} 11. b5 Nb4 {The knight looks trapped here, but Black can take on c5 to protect it, so it's actually safe.} 12. cxb6 cxb6 13. e3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Na2 {The knight leaves the place to the bishop.} 15. Rc2 Bb4+ 16. Nd2 Nc3 {Finally, the knight heads towards e4 , and Black wins at least an exchange. Surely we are winning.} *

