to push directly in the center when White hasn't played e3 yet.}) 6... c5 {A direct reaction in the center for Black!} 7. e3 ({Again, one can wonder if White would play} 7. e3 {c5 Qc2 , but I think there are more concrete moves...}) 7... cxd4 {Black takes a big decision in the center. Now White has to decide how to recapture.} 8. exd4 dxc4 {Black doesn't waste any time because we want to attack the center.} 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. Rd1 Nb4 {Proving the Queen is misplaced on c2 .} 11. Qe2 a6 12. O-O b5 13. Bb3 Bb7 {Black has an active position and has gained a few tempi already.} 14. Ne5 Nbd5 15. Bg5 {Again a loss of time.} Rc8 {Black is well-developed and is threatening to gain a pawn on c3 . I think the only logical plan for White is to bring the rook to d3 , to protect c3 , and start the classical maneuver to bring the rook to the Kingside.} 16. Rd3 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Ne4 {Unfortunately, Black trades more pieces and has a better and safer position here.} *

