1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. Qc2 ({Similarly to} 6. Rc1 {, White decides to wait actively. And similarly to Rc1 , it's best for Black to push directly in the center when White hasn't played e3 yet.}) 6... c5 {A direct reaction in the center for Black!} 7. dxc5 Na6 {Black intends to take back on c5 while developing a piece.} 8. e3 Nxc5 {White has several ways to develop now. The most logical is Be2 , but placing a rook on d1 also makes sense.} 9. O-O-O {This is too dangerous, Black's attack is fast.} Qa5 10. Kb1 Bd7 {There are already different ideas on the Queenside, such as ... Rf(a)c8 or ... Ba4 .} 11. Ne5 Ba4 12. Nxa4 Nxa4 {It's not like White has much counterplay on the other side.} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black was much better in ½-½ Pelletier-Kramnik, Zürich 1999, even if he didn't manage to convert.} *

