to push directly in the center when White hasn't played e3 yet.}) 6... c5 {A direct reaction in the center for Black!} 7. dxc5 Na6 {Black intends to take back on c5 while developing a piece.} 8. e3 Nxc5 {White has several ways to develop now. The most logical is Be2 , but placing a rook on d1 also makes sense.} 9. Rd1 Qa5 {Black actively secures the Queen.} 10. Nd2 Bd7 11. a3 Ba4 12. Nxa4 Qxa4 {That's difficult for White. It's unpleasant to take on d5 because of the knight coming to the center, but Black also has some pressure against the Queenside.} 13. Rc1 Rfc8 {Black was better in the game 0-1 Jumabayev-Oparin, chess.com 2022. If you want to know how, check the Model Games section!} *

