1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. Qc2 ({Similarly to} 6. Rc1 {, White decides to wait actively. And similarly to Rc1 , it's best for Black to push directly in the center when White hasn't played e3 yet.}) 6... c5 {A direct reaction in the center for Black!} 7. dxc5 Na6 {Black intends to take back on c5 while developing a piece.} 8. e3 Nxc5 {White has several ways to develop now. The most logical is Be2 , but placing a rook on d1 also makes sense.} 9. Be2 dxc4 {White just moved the bishop, which is often a signal to take on c4 .} 10. Bxc4 a6 {Black wants to continue with ... b5 and ... Bb7 , so White should prevent it.} 11. a4 {Since this move weakens b4 , Black is profiting from the inclusion of ... a6 / a4 .} Qa5 12. O-O b6 13. Rab1 {It's important to play this move now because Black is not able to bring the knight to e4 , it needs to head back.} Ncd7 {The knight returns to avoid the fork on b4 .} 14. Rfd1 Bb7 15. Ng5 ({This has been played in several correspondence games that all ended in a draw. Be careful: h6} 15. Rxd7 {is winning for White thanks to the mate on h7 .}) 15... Rfd8 {The rook comes to the center.} 16. Bxe6 {An interesting piece sacrifice to weaken our Kingside.} fxe6 17. Nxe6 Rdc8 18. Ng5 {White's most dangerous threat is Qb3 . Black has to prevent this idea.} Bd5 {Simply the only move.} 19. Rxd5 Qxd5 {Black can't take with the knight, as h7 is hanging.} 20. Nxd5 Rxc2 21. Nxe7+ Kf8 22. Nf5 Kg8 {There are still 4 correspondence games in this position, that's why it felt important to mention this 'engine' line. ½-½ Dosi-Latronico, ICCF email 2009.} ({A possible repetition is Ne7+ Kf8 Bd6} 22... Re8 {Ng6+ Kg8} 23. Ne7 {Kf8= .}) *

