1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. a3 ({To my eyes, this is the most interesting move for White apart from} 6. e3 {. I'm not surprised that some of the top Grandmasters have played it. It prevents some of Black's ideas on the Queenside, so it's definitely useful.}) 6... b6 ({After both} 6... b6 {and} 7. c5 {there are possible transpositions to the corresponding e3 lines. Since we go for b6 after 6.e3 , we have to do the same here to avoid transposing to variations outside of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 ({Be careful here! It's not the same as in our main line. The drawback to playing} 8... Qxd5 {is} 9. g3 {, and suddenly the Queen is awkward on d5 , and the move a3 is perfect to avoid ... Bb4 + or ... Qa5 +.}) 9. g3 c5 {Here as well, Black can accept the hanging pair of pawns in the center. We prefer to play ... c5 before ... Bb7 , as b7 is not necessarily the best square for the bishop.} 10. Bg2 Be6 11. O-O Nc6 12. dxc5 bxc5 {The center is solid for Black. We will bring the Queen to b6 , and the rooks to the center.} 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 f6 15. Bf4 Qd7 {Black has no problems here. Chasing the bishop with ... g5 to get the b8 -square for the rook is a possible continuation.} *

