some of the top Grandmasters have played it. It prevents some of Black's ideas on the Queenside, so it's definitely useful.}) 6... b6 ({After both} 6... b6 {and} 7. c5 {there are possible transpositions to the corresponding e3 lines. Since we go for b6 after 6.e3 , we have to do the same here to avoid transposing to variations outside of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 ({Be careful here! It's not the same as in our main line. The drawback to playing} 8... Qxd5 {is} 9. g3 {, and suddenly the Queen is awkward on d5 , and the move a3 is perfect to avoid ... Bb4 + or ... Qa5 +.}) 9. e3 c5 {Black enters a position where having a hanging pair of pawns feels comfortable. If White doesn't take, Black could be willing to advance the c-pawn and create a pawn expansion on the Queenside with ... b5 - b4 at some point.} 10. Be2 {A little bit too slow.} c4 {White shouldn't have allowed this move.} 11. O-O Nc6 12. b3 {White tries to break the Queenside while it still looks possible, but it's already too late!} b5 13. a4 Na5 {That's how Black keeps the pawns alive.} 14. axb5 Nxb3 15. Rb1 a5 16. bxa6 Bxa6 {Black has the more active position now that the c4 -pawn is passed.} *

