1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. a3 ({To my eyes, this is the most interesting move for White apart from} 6. e3 {. I'm not surprised that some of the top Grandmasters have played it. It prevents some of Black's ideas on the Queenside, so it's definitely useful.}) 6... b6 ({After both} 6... b6 {and} 7. c5 {there are possible transpositions to the corresponding e3 lines. Since we go for b6 after 6.e3 , we have to do the same here to avoid transposing to variations outside of our repertoire.}) 7. e3 c5 {Once a3 has been played, Black does not mind the hanging pawns because White's strongest plan against them is to immobilize Black's center with pawns on e3 and b3 . But with the white a-pawn on a3 , this plan will leave the a3 and b3 -pawns rather weak.} 8. Be2 {I wouldn't be too confident with White to keep the tension like this and leave Black with every option opened.} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 {There is no rush for Black. If White takes on c5 at some point, the position will be close to equal.} 11. Qe2 a6 12. Rfd1 b5 13. Ba2 cxd4 {Finally, Black allows the opponent to reach an IQP, but only because it's not a great version. TaKing back with the knight is impossible due to ... e5 .} 14. exd4 Nb6 {Black has great control over the central light squares.} *

