1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. e3 {By far the main move. White protects the center and gets ready to develop the second bishop before castling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. Qc2 {White frees the the d1 -square for the rook. Hard to tell if White wants to castle long yet, but that's an option.} Ba6 {We will have the same approach against Be2 and Bd3 . The idea is to force matters by attacKing the c4 -pawn. And in this case, getting chances to prevent White from castling.} 8. O-O-O {It's very dangerous for White to immediately show which side the King will castle to, especially when it's the Queenside!} dxc4 9. Ng5 {Now, I would leave the game 1-0 Dubov-Svane, Batumi 2019 by playing:} Nbd7 ({Protecting the knight on f6 feels safer than} 9... Nc6 {.}) 10. h4 b5 {Now, Black can fight back on the Queenside.} 11. Nce4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qc2 b4 {Black has various ideas, including ... c5 followed by ... Qa5 , or the straighforward ... b3 , opening some files in front of the white King (and chasing the Queen from c2 , where it attacks the h7 -pawn). It's not obvious how White continues their attack.} ({A sample line is Be5 b3 axb3 cxb3 Qxb3 Qb1 Qd5! Bxa6 Qc6+ Kd2 Qxa6 followed by ... g6 and Black is better. Bxf1 Qc2 , and now you can choose Black's answer according to your preference: Bxg2 Bxf6} 13... g6 {, when White's attack has been averted, or Re8 Bxf6 Bxf6 Qxh7+ Kf8 Rhxf1 Rb8 , with a dynamically equal position.}) *

