1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. e3 {By far the main move. White protects the center and gets ready to develop the second bishop before castling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. Rc1 ({White waits to develop the bishop. Be careful, this time, Ba6 is not very good because White can play} 7. Qa4 {with an advantage for White. Instead, Black continues logically.}) 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 {The main move here, preventing Black from taKing on c4 first.} Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {As in the main line, Black brings the Queen to the center.} 10. a3 {This quiet move prevents ... Bb4 +. But as the rook is on c1 and not a1 , it doesn't prevent Black's next move.} Qa5+ {White can't play b2 - b4 because a3 is hanging.} 11. Nd2 c5 12. Rc3 {An interesting move, intending Nc4 . Black should be ready to capture the knight.} Ba6 13. Nc4 Bxc4 14. Bxc4 b5 15. Be2 Nc6 16. O-O c4 {A double-edged position is now on the board. Black has the initiative on the Queenside, while White has an extra pawn in the center and the bishop pair. Black's plan is to bring the rooks to c8 and d8 , and start thinKing about opening the Queenside with ... b4 .} *

