1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. e3 {By far the main move. White protects the center and gets ready to develop the second bishop before castling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. Bd3 Ba6 {Again, a sideline, but again, very interesting!} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {With Be2 , we checked a highly similar line.} 10. O-O Rc8 {Black protects the pawn and prepares a latter ... c5 .} 11. e4 {Very logical, White occupies the center.} Qb7 12. Rc1 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nd7 {Black's goal is not necessarily ... c5 on the next move. For instance, ... Nf6 is an idea, trying to provoke White into pushing e5 , leaving us with a great d5 -square. Black is equal because even if we have less space, we have no weaknesses at all and good prospects of opening up the position when it will be the best for us.} *

