1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 ({This is the start of the second part of our repertoire. Obviously, this position can be reached via various move orders. It can be the one we have here, or} 4. Nc3 {Nf6 Nf3 . But the main one is probably from the Nimzo-Indian Defense ( d4 Nf6} dxc4 {e6 Nf3} 5. d5 {Nc3 ) . That's a huge crossroad in the 1.d4 theory.}) ({Black can either opt for the Semi-Slav with c6 , the Ragozin with Bb4 , the Vienna with dxc4 , the Semi-Tarrasch with} 4. c5 {, the Queen's Gambit Declined with} Be7 {(our choice here), but also less explored options as Nbd7 , a6 , or even h6 . Needless to say, it's a challenge to be ready against everything with White.}) 4... Be7 {We keep a Queen's Gambit Declined type of development. The good thing is that we have already analyzed Bg5 in a previous chapter , and this avoids one of the main options for White!} 5. Bf4 ({Apart from} 5. Bg5 {, which we already analyzed, this is the main line. White develops the bishop without going for the pin on g5 . The idea is to control some central squares. White doesn't want to take too soon on d5 because it would help the c8 -bishop develop. Instead, White is going to develop quietly. I don't think this is a real crossroads for Black, the best is to castle first and see how White reacts.}) 5... O-O {Now, I have looked at so many ideas for White, even if the clear main line is e3 .} 6. e3 {By far the main move. White protects the center and gets ready to develop the second bishop before castling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. Bd3 Ba6 {Again, a sideline, but again, very interesting!} 8. Qe2 ({This feels like the best idea to me. It's a better version than} 8. Be2 {Ba6 Qa4 because the Queen isn't exposed on a4 .}) 8... c5 {Black can react in the center. If White waits, Black will simply develop with ... Nbd7 , reinforcing the pawns.} 9. dxc5 Nbd7 {A strong move! Black would love to take back on c5 with the knight. Also, we can see a drawback of 8.Qe2 : whenever White takes on d5 , Black takes on d3 , and White has spent a tempo with the Queen for nothing.} 10. cxd5 {White trades some pieces, but probably this is the best.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nxc5 {We recaptured the first pawn, and the other one is waiting on d5 .} 12. Qd4 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 {White has managed to create an isolated pawn for Black, but with precise play, that won't be enough.} 14. O-O Ne6 15. Qd2 Nxf4 16. exf4 Rc8 {With White having double pawns, this can't be much.} 17. Rfd1 Bf6 18. Ne5 Bxe5 19. fxe5 Qe7 {The pawn on e5 is to weak.} 20. Qxd5 Rc5 21. Qd7 Rxe5 {Queens are going to get traded, and the position remains equal.} *

