stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. Bd3 Ba6 {Again, a sideline, but again, very interesting!} 8. Qe2 ({This feels like the best idea to me. It's a better version than} 8. Be2 {Ba6 Qa4 because the Queen isn't exposed on a4 .}) 8... c5 {Black can react in the center. If White waits, Black will simply develop with ... Nbd7 , reinforcing the pawns.} 9. dxc5 Nbd7 {A strong move! Black would love to take back on c5 with the knight. Also, we can see a drawback of 8.Qe2 : whenever White takes on d5 , Black takes on d3 , and White has spent a tempo with the Queen for nothing.} 10. cxd5 {White trades some pieces, but probably this is the best.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nxc5 {We recaptured the first pawn, and the other one is waiting on d5 .} 12. Qd4 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 {White has managed to create an isolated pawn for Black, but with precise play, that won't be enough.} 14. Be5 {This is preventing both the ... Ne6 fork and ... Bf6 . Since the bishop would be well-placed on d4 , we chase it away before the Queen can vacate d4 .} f6 15. Bg3 Qd7 16. O-O Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Rac8 18. Rac1 {One may think it's a bit annoying to play, but Black has too much activity.} Qa4 19. Qxa4 Nxa4 {The intrusion of the knight settles it: Black has enough activity for the isolated pawn.} *

