stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Bg3 {Not a great option, as it's very slow.} Bb7 9. Bd3 c5 {Black has perfect play in the center.} 10. O-O cxd4 11. exd4 Nd7 12. Rc1 N7f6 {Black has reached a safe IQP position. The bishop on g3 is particularly misplaced, as it has spent a couple of moves to get there, and it's not doing much against the black King. Black also has full control over d5 .} *

