stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. Be2 Qa5+ 10. Nd2 Ba6 {Black offers a bishop trade, but we would also like to continue with ... c5 .} 11. O-O c5 12. Nc4 {Most players that have seen this position tried this move, to get the bishop pair, but it's hardly enough.} Bxc4 13. Bxc4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf6 15. Qe4 Nd7 {Black's counterattack is fast.} *

