stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. Bxc7 {That's very dangerous for White, but it's a pawn, and Black should have a clear idea of how to react.} Bb4+ {Forcing White to get more passive.} 10. Nd2 Nc6 {Black develops towards the center. White still can't develop the bishop because g2 is hanging.} 11. f3 {White wants to bring the King to f2 before developing the remaining pieces. Black has no choice but to be very concrete.} Bd7 {This line has been played several times in correspondence games, and Black showed equality.} 12. Kf2 Nxd4 {A well-timed blow.} 13. exd4 {There is no way White can accept the knight.} Qxd4+ 14. Ke1 Rac8 15. Rc1 Qe3+ 16. Be2 Bb5 ({White is simply out of moves. The threat is} 16... Z0 {Bxe2 Qxe2 Bxd2-+ .}) *

