stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. a3 {A few years ago, I thought this was necessary for White to create some problems. I am not sure anymore it's the best, or if it poses Black any problem.} c5 {Black immediately reacts in the center.} 10. Be2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 {This may look clever, but it's not worKing.} Bb7 12. Bf3 Qa5+ {Forcing Black to weaken the Queenside.} 13. b4 ({Again in the wrong direction. White should accept massive trades leading to an equal position with} 13. Qd2 {instead.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 (14. Nxf3 Qa6 {is also better for Black.}) 14... Bxb4+ 15. Kf1 (15. Ke2 Qa6+ {is devastating.}) 15... Nd7 {And White's plan has backfired.} *

