stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. a3 {A few years ago, I thought this was necessary for White to create some problems. I am not sure anymore it's the best, or if it poses Black any problem.} c5 {Black immediately reacts in the center.} 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Rc1 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 {This line is White's best chance. White's Queenside is better developed so White should try to take over the initiative there. Black needs to be precise. The first step is to avoid Rc7 .} Na6 {The knight comes to cover c7 .} 14. Bb5 Bb7 15. Ke2 {It's better for White to not castle in this endgame, the King can be useful in the center.} g5 {This move leaves the game ½-½ Gurevich-Goldin, lichess.org 2020. Black gains some space on the Kingside.} 16. Bg3 Nc5 17. b4 a6 {Black now wants to take the bishop to open the a-file.} 18. bxc5 ({Instead,} 18. Bc4 Nd7 {is fine for Black.}) 18... axb5 19. cxb6 Ba6 {That's Black's point! It's very hard to avoid ... b4 + in a good way. Engines show equality.} *

