stling.} b6 {I had to face this move some years ago when it wasn't popular at all and I couldn't get any advantage. Black is willing to develop similarly to the Tartakower line. The main move for White is to take immediately on d5 , but there are again some alternatives that we need to check now.} (6... Nbd7 {together with} 7. c5 {are the two main moves for Black. But I like the flexibility of our chosen line, which is also more in the spirit of the rest of our repertoire.}) 7. cxd5 {By taKing immediately, White forces us to show how we aim to take back: with a piece, to keep a safe pawn structure, or with a pawn, condemning ourselves to end up in a position with hanging pair of pawns whenever we will push ... c5 ?} Nxd5 {By far, with the knight! Black has just played ... b6 and doesn't want to close the diagonal so soon.} 8. Nxd5 {Same question as after cxd5 . This time the response is less clear, as it's good to have traded a pair of knights in the case of the hanging pawns, but I still prefer to go for the same idea to keep a safe pawn structure.} Qxd5 (8... exd5 {has been played just as often. This move lets the pawn on c7 unprotected, but it's a bit complicated to take it when White is so far from castling.}) 9. Bd3 {Developing the bishop is still the main move. White wants to castle next so let's try to prevent this.} Qa5+ {White obviously can't interpose the check with the Queen, so White has to move the King or retreat with the knight.} 10. Nd2 {The main move, but engines tend to think the position is already slightly preferable for Black!} Ba6 {Again, Black doesn't want to allow White to castle.} 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black prefers to push ... c5 over preventing the castle.} 12. O-O c5 13. Qe2 {White waits for ... cxd4 before playing Nb3 .} cxd4 14. Nb3 d3 {A nice intermediate move. The Queen is worse on d3 , as it will be attacked shortly by a rook.} 15. Qxd3 Qa4 {Now, White can keep a balanced position with Be5 or Qe2 . Instead, let's see how easy it is to go wrong.} 16. Qd4 {White tries to force a draw.} Qxd4 17. Nxd4 {All this has been played in 0-1 Sviridova-Brunner, chess.com 2020. Now, I prefer:} Bf6 {With the very simply threat of pushing ... e5 .} 18. Bg3 Bxd4 {This was the other threat. The endgame is going to be awful for White.} 19. exd4 Rfd8 20. Rfd1 Nb4 {The threat is ... Nc2xd4 .} 21. Rd2 Rac8 {Black is very active, and I think sooner or later, we will win the d4 -pawn.} *

