[PlyCount "30"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. c5 {A decent attempt for White, even if it has only been tried a few times. It's justified by the tempo gained over the bishop.} Be7 8. b4 ({If White doesn't support the Queenside immediately, Black is going to break it with ... b6 and ... c5 . Also,} 8. Bf4 {or Qc2 makes sense, but} Nc6 {prevents b4 .}) 8... Nc6 {Black immediately challenges the Queenside. The knight can sometimes head towards a5 and c4 .} (8... b6 {right now, I think it gives White a nice possibility.} 9. Qc2 $5 a5 10. b5 c6 11. a4 {and White has a nice initiative on the Queenside.}) 9. a3 b6 {The goal isn't really to break the Queenside but to open some files for the pieces.} 10. Bf4 bxc5 11. dxc5 ({Instead,} 11. bxc5 {can be met with} Rb8 {and ... Ba6 later, with active play.}) 11... Ne4 {The missing d4 -pawn can be felt right now. The threat is ... Bf6 .} 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Ra2 {It can be useful for White to move the rook, as that prevents any attack from our dark-squared bishop, and it can be brought on any file on the second rank.} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 f6 {Black chases the bishop and controls the center even better.} 15. Ba1 a5 {The position is double-edged. White has a majority on the Queenside, and Black is stronger in the center. The b7 -bishop will probably change diagonals (by playing ... c6 and ... Ba6 at some point.} *

