1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Qc2 ({In the same spirit as} 7. Nbd2 {, White would like to continue with Nbd2 and e4 , to open up the center.}) 7... b6 {Black prevents the ideas with e4 .} 8. a3 {White prepares c5 followed by b4 . It could be an idea to prevent it by playing ... c5 ourselves, but I think we can allow it.} Bb7 9. c5 Be7 10. b4 a5 {Black is trying to open up the Queenside.} 11. Bb2 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Bxa1 Qc8 {The idea of this move will be seen later. But basically, the Queen can sometimes play on the c-file or can quickly reach b7 or a6 .} 14. Nc3 bxc5 15. dxc5 {This leads to a more interesting position. To avoid ending up being passive and restrained in the center, Black needs to act now.} d4 {This move is justified tactically.} 16. Nb5 Nc6 {Black counterattacks against the b4 -pawn, and its protection will provide us a tempo to push ... e5 .} 17. Qb3 e5 18. Na3 {The knight clears the way for the b-pawn.} Ne4 19. Nc2 Ng5 {Black decides to trade knights off the board.} 20. b5 Na5 21. Qa2 Nxf3+ 22. exf3 (22. Bxf3 {would take all the sting out of the position and after} Bxf3 23. exf3 Nb7 24. Qd5 Bxc5 25. Qxe5 Re8 {, Black has nothing to complain about. In fact, the d-pawn could even prove dangerous.}) 22... Qa8 {Black protects a5 and gets some play on the long diagonal. The pawn on c5 is under attack, so the next move is both very logical and forced.} 23. c6 Nxc6 {That's the point of the whole line here. Black needs this sacrifice to have enough play and not to end up strangled by White.} 24. Qxa8 Rxa8 25. bxc6 Bxc6 {In the end, Black has two passed pawns for a knight and also very active pieces. Engines claim the position is equal, but I think anything can happen here.} ({A sample line is f4 Bxg2 Kxg2} 25... Ra2 26. Rc1 f6 {fxe5 fxe5 , when Black has the clear-cut plan of bringing the King to the center to support the pawns. In many variations, the engines just give back the piece since it's not easy for White to coordinate the pieces, as the a1 -bishop is biting on granite.}) *

