{After Bxc4 Nxc4 Rxc4= , the endgame should end in a draw because of the opposite-colored bishops.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. Qd3 {I had to face this system as White against the strong French GM Etienne Bacrot during the French League 2023. I decided (after some thought because I didn't know this variation), to opt for this interesting move. I knew it probably wasn't the main option, but it was my goal to get something he might not know. Unfortunately, he replied quickly.} Nb4 {White's Queen needs to move again} 9. Qd2 {GM Jumabayev has tried this move twice, without much success, but it also makes some sense. The Queen keeps controlling d4 and keeps an eye on the b4 -knight too.} dxc4 {The pawn was hanging, so Black takes it and sees how White will try to take it back.} 10. Ne5 {White wants the pawn back.} Bxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd2 12. Bxd2 Nfd5 13. Rfc1 {An interesting position has arisen. White is preparing the siege of c4 . Now, in the game 0-1 Jumabayev-Tari, chess.com 2022, I would prefer the text move.} a5 (13... Bd7 {was played in the game.}) 14. a3 Nc6 {If White takes twice on d5 (starting with the bishop), the knight heads back towards d4 , threatening forks on e2 and b3 .} 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Bxd5 {Here, Nd4 is met with Bxc4 protecting both threats for now.} Rd8 {Of course, taKing advantage of the two unprotected bishops on the d-file.} 17. e4 Nxe5 18. Bf4 c6 *

