1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. c5 ({As on the previous move, this is an option, and it's even White's main alternative to} 8. b3 {.}) 8... Be7 9. Rb1 {Logical, to achive b4 .} a5 {So we prevent it, for now.} 10. a3 Ne4 {Black prevents b4 and activates in the center. We can protect the knight, if necessary, with ... f5 .} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 f5 {There is no need to take first on e5 ; the capture on c6 is logical, but it helps us to develop.} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Be3 Ba6 15. f3 Bg5 {By trading the bishops, Black wants to intrude on the dark squares.} 16. Qd2 exf3 17. Bxf3 Bb5 {Black is ready to play ... a4 , to block the Queenside and secure the bishop on b5 . It's active here, and it also protects c6 .} *

