Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. c5 ({As on the previous move, this is an option, and it's even White's main alternative to} 8. b3 {.}) 8... Be7 9. Bf4 {The most played move, but Black has a strong reply!} g5 {We give White no time to bring a knight on e5 , or to do threats with Nb5 , for instance. Instead, the closed center allows us to chase the bishop.} 10. Be3 b6 {A strong move, to immediately challenge the c5 -pawn.} 11. cxb6 axb6 12. a3 {Now, the game 0-1 Klemettinen-Rynkevich, ICCF email 2013 saw Na5 , and while not being a bad move, I prefer another plan.} Bb7 13. Qc2 Ne8 {The knight heads towards d6 .} 14. Rac1 {A logical but unhelpful move.} Nd6 {Now, ... f5 is in the air. Black has an active position and won the war of the pawn structure in the center.} *

