Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. e3 {Quite a decent attempt for White, who wants to get an active pair of hanging pawns in the center that would be able to fight and chase our c6 -knight and d6 -bishop. But right now, there is no rush in taKing on d4 .} Re8 11. c5 {White rushes to force matters.} exd4 {Now that c5 has been pushed, it makes sense to clarify things in the center before White pushes d5 too, closing the e-file.} 12. exd4 Bf8 13. Rb1 {This has been played in the game ½-½ Janik-Bacrot, Vrnjacka Banja 2023. Now, instead of Rb8 , I would rather play:} b6 {A provoKing move, as the light-squared diagonal is weak, but there is no good way for White to take advantage of it. Anyway, if White does nothing, White will see the center being destroyed.} 14. Ne5 Nxd4 {That's the point. Black sacrifices the exchange for a central pawn and some activity.} 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Nxf7 ({While} 16. Bxa8 {transposes back into the main line , this attempt is smarter than one move earlier, as Black can't take a pawn on c5 anymore.}) 16... Kxf7 17. Bxa8 Bg4 ({Not the only move but the more forcing one.} 17... Bf5 {is also an interesting option to investigate, which is less forcing.}) 18. Bd5+ {The only move to survive.} Qxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd1 20. Rxd1 {And now these knights will fork the rooks one way or another.} Ne2+ 21. Kg2 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Nc3 23. Rf5+ {White wants to take the bishop instead of the knight, otherwise, Black has slightly better chances thanks to the passed c-pawn.} Ke6 24. Rxf8 Rxf8 {The position is objectively equal, but I like Black's active pieces and passed c-pawn.} *

