1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. e3 {Quite a decent attempt for White, who wants to get an active pair of hanging pawns in the center that would be able to fight and chase our c6 -knight and d6 -bishop. But right now, there is no rush in taKing on d4 .} Re8 11. Bb2 {Here too, White is waiting while improving the position slightly.} exd4 {A novelty, even if we will transpose into some variations from a different move order.} 12. exd4 Bf5 {Again, to control the e4 and b1 -squares.} 13. Nb5 ({This has been played in the game 0-1 Ju Wenjun-Tari, chess24.com 2022, from the move order exd4 exd4 Re8 Bb2 Bf5} 13. Nb5 {, and now my preference is:}) 13... Nb4 {The d3 -square is unprotected and could prove useful for Black.} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Qb3 a5 16. a3 {But d3 isn't the only weak square...} Bc2 17. Qc3 Ne4 {The Queen is suddenly in trouble and should go to the dangerous e-file.} 18. Qe1 Nxg3 {And eventually, Black gains some material.} *

