Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. e3 {Quite a decent attempt for White, who wants to get an active pair of hanging pawns in the center that would be able to fight and chase our c6 -knight and d6 -bishop. But right now, there is no rush in taKing on d4 .} Re8 11. Bb2 {Here too, White is waiting while improving the position slightly.} exd4 {A novelty, even if we will transpose into some variations from a different move order.} 12. exd4 Bf5 {Again, to control the e4 and b1 -squares.} 13. Nb5 ({This has been played in the game 0-1 Ju Wenjun-Tari, chess24.com 2022, from the move order exd4 exd4 Re8 Bb2 Bf5} 13. Nb5 {, and now my preference is:}) 13... Nb4 {The d3 -square is unprotected and could prove useful for Black.} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. a3 Nd3 16. Bc3 Rad8 {It's far from easy to expel the knight from d3 , and Black intensifies the pressure on the center.} 17. Ra2 {A decent try to chase the knight (which is trapped by the way.} Qa6 {Black comes to rescue the daring knight by attacKing the c4 -pawn.} 18. Qb3 Qb6 {Both the endgame and the repetition (obviously) lead to an equal position.} *

