Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. Nxe5 {An interesting try, with a hidden idea.} Nxe5 11. c5 {OK, well, maybe not so hidden. TaKing back on e5 would lead to a comfortable position for Black with the strong bishop on e5 and the isolated c4 -pawn. Instead, White goes for the bishop chase.} Bxc5 {The only move in the position, the rest is bad for Black. Now, White can take any of the two pieces.} 12. dxc5 {White scored well in this line, but I still think Black's fine.} Qe7 {Black develops, leaves the d8 -square for a rook, and attacks the c5 -pawn.} 13. Bf4 Qxc5 ({Here, players only tried} 13... Rd8 {, but it activates White's Queen. I prefer to grab the pawn first and see how it goes.}) 14. Rc1 Qe7 15. Nd5 {There is nothing better, but that's not a problematic position, objectively.} Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Re8 {It's clear that White can force a draw by trading on e5 , but nothing more. White is still a pawn down and ... c6 (or sometimes even ... Nc6 ) is coming.} *

