Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. d5 {This is the most played move in the position, but I don't think it's great for White, and I find it too obvious. It leaves the c5 -square in Black's hands, and I believe it's a big concession.} Na5 {Already another issue for White: the c4 -pawn is exposed and not so easy to protect.} 11. Qa4 {I am not sure the Queen will be great here.} b6 12. c5 Bxc5 13. Nxe5 {Similarly to c5 , it doesn't feel like a problem here. Black gains some activity against White's center.} Re8 14. Nd3 Bd7 15. Qc2 {1-0 Javakhishvili-Shuvalova, Riga 2021.} Bd4 {A novelty. The point is to push ... c5 on the next move.} 16. Bb2 c5 17. dxc6 {The d5 -pawn was passed, but not very dangerous. I would say that the c5 -pawn was more useful.} Bxc6 18. Bxc6 Nxc6 19. e3 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Qd7 {After some trades, the position remains balanced. Black has a Queenside majority that can prove to be strong in endgames, and a lack of weaknesses, while White has a strong bishop on b2 and an extra pawn in the center.} *

