s the c5 -square in Black's hands, and I believe it's a big concession.} Na5 {Already another issue for White: the c4 -pawn is exposed and not so easy to protect.} 11. c5 {I don't think this trade can be dangerous. White will have the central pawns, but Black also activates very quickly.} Bxc5 12. Nxe5 Re8 13. Nd3 {At least here the knight gains a tempo over the bishop.} Bb6 14. e4 c6 {Before the center becomes too strong, we have to trade a pawn.} 15. Nf4 {Now, I would like to deviate from the game 0-1 Chan-Boyer, Southend 2023, which will be analyzed in the Model Games section.} Nc4 {The knight comes back to center, and Black keeps the tension for now.} 16. Qb3 Nd6 17. Re1 Bf5 ({The e4 -pawn is pinned so this increases the pressure against e4 . Also,} 17... g5 {is strong too, but I feel it's less safe or easy to understand.}) 18. dxc6 bxc6 19. Rd1 Rb8 {Black is threatening to win the Queen with ... Bxf2 +.} 20. Qa4 Ng4 21. Nh3 Be6 {Black might bring the Queen to f6 , with several threats. We have a very active position.} *

