Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. Rb1 {I have decided to keep this as the main line because it seems to be slightly the engine preference. The idea is to put immediate pressure on b7 , to prevent the development of the c8 -bishop.} exd4 {The best idea seems to trade immediately, to force matters.} 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Re8 13. Rd1 Qe7 {These pass moves seemed very natural for both, to activate the pieces. Now, everyone has continued with Bb2 , placing the bishop on its nicest diagonal, but there is another interesting idea for White.} 14. Qe3 {An interesting try! White would like to trade Queens and have both bishops targeting the Queenside.} Be5 {Black avoids a Queen trade for now and wants to continue with ... c6 .} 15. Nd5 {White forces matters by regrouping the pawns.} Nxd5 16. cxd5 Bd6 {Black keeps a solid position, and I don't think White has many chances to break through our defense.} *

