1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined! The very early stage of one of the oldest theoretical debates in chess. In this course, I am going to provide you with a full repertoire starting from this position.} ({Obviously Nc3 and Nf3 are the two main continuations. There are no independent tries here. e3 will transpose into the chapter on the Colle System. g3 is a rare move order to reach the Catalan Variation. Finally, a3 and Bf4 are extremely rare, and we will see similar lines after Nc3} 2... Nf6 {.}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The beginning of the Catalan Variation. It has been popular for decades, and it has to be seen as one of the most reliable systems for White against the Queen's Gambit Declined. I have decided to keep it for the last chapter, as it's a slightly different spirit than the rest of the course.  The basic idea is to slowly develop, starting with the Kingside. White isn't trying to protect the c4 -pawn because in the case of ... dxc4 , White will be able to get it back with Ne5 , Nbd2 , Qc2 , or Qa4 +, depending on the situation, or can also play as a sacrifice by occupying the center with e4 (in a Semi-Slav spirit).  Needless to say, the theory has been developed extensively in the Catalan, but I wanted to show something less explored yet reliable for Black.} Bd6 ({Already a rare move. Usually, the bishop goes to e7 or b4 with check, deciding the final square later. Instead, the two main variations are} 4... dxc4 {and Be7 .}) 5. Bg2 ({A few other moves have been tried with White here, but it usually makes no difference, as it will transpose later. There can't be anything better than} 5. Bg2 {and 6.O-O .}) 5... O-O 6. O-O ({Let's just mention that} 6. Qc2 {can be met with} b6 {directly (as against 7.Qc2 ). There is no threat yet in the center, so let's start by preventing any c4 - c5 ideas.}) 6... h6 {Black simply wants to prevent Bg5 (which will be useful, as White can play Nc3 soon, with real pressure against d5 ).} ({The idea is to continue with Nc3} 6... Nc6 {, to occupy the center. Before analyzing the main line, we will see different sidelines for White.  We should mention something nice for Black: this line can be reached from different move orders. For instance, d4 Nf6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 O-O O-O c4} h6 {, or via Réti move orders. That's an advantage in comparison with lines featuring dxc4 where Black has to look for different lines in the other move orders.}) 7. Nc3 ({Clearly, White's main line, and can also arise from different move orders. It wouldn't be a good idea for Black to continue with b6 , similarly to a line we have already seen because White would get an active position in the center (by} 7. Ne5 {Bb7 Bf4 , with nice pressure) and ideas with e4 coming.}) 7... Nc6 {Our whole system is based on this move. It may seem weird at first sight, and I was very surprised when I first faced it, as it's usually accepted that the knight is misplaced on c6 in the Queen's Gambit systems. But here, it fits Black's plan perfectly, as it can help us react in the center with ... e5 . It also restrains White's expansion on the Queenside when White wants c5 followed by b4 .} 8. b3 {Very logical and by far the main move. White understands that Black's idea could be to take on c4 , so White immediately secures it.} dxc4 {Black is starting the opening of the center by trading these pawns.} 9. bxc4 e5 {That's the whole point of our system. With ... Bd6 and ... Nc6 , Black has developed the pieces to control the center and especially the e5 -square. Black basically would like to leave White with an isolated pawn on c4 .  At the time of writing, it's been played around 100 times (which is still quite low for a variation in the Catalan), but remember this is a very recent variation. The score is roughly balanced. Now, White is at a big crossroads and has tried many different moves.} 10. Rb1 {I have decided to keep this as the main line because it seems to be slightly the engine preference. The idea is to put immediate pressure on b7 , to prevent the development of the c8 -bishop.} exd4 {The best idea seems to trade immediately, to force matters.} 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Re8 13. Rd1 Qe7 {These pass moves seemed very natural for both, to activate the pieces. Now, everyone has continued with Bb2 , placing the bishop on its nicest diagonal, but there is another interesting idea for White.} 14. Bb2 Be6 {This leaves the tracks of the 3 games that reached this position. Black forgets about the b7 -pawn to activate the remaining pieces and hopes to gain the c4 -pawn back later.} 15. Bxb7 {Obviously, the critical attempt.} Rab8 16. Bc6 {Gaining a tempo on the e8 -rook also makes a lot of sense. But the rook can be activated immediately.} Red8 17. Ne4 Bf5 {The only move! The bishop attacks and pins the knight.} 18. Nxf6+ {Of course, stronger than taKing the bishop, as it damages our Kingside pawn structure.} Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 {Black has 5 isolated pawns and is a pawn down, but the exposed b1 -rook is the key to Black's escape.} 20. Bxf6 {Black is temporarily two pawns down.} Bxb1 21. Bxd8 Bxa2 {Black is about to get the other pawn back.} 22. c5 Rxd8 23. cxd6 Rxd6 {The most likely result is a draw (White should be even careful about the a-pawn).} *

