mmediate pressure on b7 , to prevent the development of the c8 -bishop.} exd4 {The best idea seems to trade immediately, to force matters.} 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Re8 13. Rd1 Qe7 {These pass moves seemed very natural for both, to activate the pieces. Now, everyone has continued with Bb2 , placing the bishop on its nicest diagonal, but there is another interesting idea for White.} 14. Bb2 Be6 {This leaves the tracks of the 3 games that reached this position. Black forgets about the b7 -pawn to activate the remaining pieces and hopes to gain the c4 -pawn back later.} 15. Bxb7 {Obviously, the critical attempt.} Rab8 16. Bc6 {Gaining a tempo on the e8 -rook also makes a lot of sense. But the rook can be activated immediately.} Red8 17. Ne4 Bf5 {The only move! The bishop attacks and pins the knight.} 18. Nxf6+ {Of course, stronger than taKing the bishop, as it damages our Kingside pawn structure.} Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 {Black has 5 isolated pawns and is a pawn down, but the exposed b1 -rook is the key to Black's escape.} 20. e4 Bg4 21. Rd5 Be6 22. Rd2 Be7 {Finally, protecting the f6 -pawn, and the pawn on c4 is under attack.} 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {Black has enough play because c4 (and sometimes a2 ) are hanging, while ... Rb8 can also be a nasty threat since it's very difficult to unpin the bishop on b2 and ... Ba3 can be fast.} *

