1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. d4 c5 5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qa4 exd5 8. Nf3 d4 9. Nb1 d3 {Until this move, we have considered all the variations in the first chapter, about the early sidelines. Fridman decides to break immediately in the center, to open White's King, and it's definitely an interesting attempt.} (9... Bc5 {was also strong, and our preference in the chapter.}) 10. e3 ({After} 10. Qb5 dxe2 11. Qxe2+ Be7 {, Black keeps a quick development and the better position. Black wants to castle and place a rook on e8 quickly.}) 10... Bb4+ (10... Bd7 $1 {was probably stronger, to bring the knight to b4 :} 11. Qb3 Nb4 {.}) 11. Bd2 Qd5 12. Bg2 Bg4 {Black's play is concrete. White is unable to protect the knight on f3 and has to move it.} 13. Nh4 ({The right reply. After} 13. Bxb4 $5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qxf3 15. O-O Qg4 16. a3 h5 {, White has a very weak Kingside; it's time to attack it with ... h4 .}) 13... Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Qd7 15. Nhf3 O-O 16. O-O {White has managed to castle. However, the pawn on d3 is still very strong and easy to protect for Black.} b5 {Black offers a pawn to open the b-file.} 17. Qf4 (17. Qxb5 Rab8 18. Qa4 Rxb2) 17... Nd5 18. Ne5 {A huge blunder in a difficult position for Black.} (18. Qe4 {was the best continuation.} Ndb4 19. Rac1 Rfe8 20. Qf4 Nd5 {and Black keeps the initiative.}) 18... Nxf4 (18... Nxf4 19. Nxd7 Ne2+ 20. Kh1 Bxd7 {and Black simply wins a piece.}) *

