1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 {Just another move order that can sometimes lead to our variations.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qc2 g6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Up to this point, we have dealt with the alternatives in the theoretical section. With the previous move, White wanted to distract our bishop to be able to launch the minority attack.} 12. b4 Qd6 13. Rb1 {White has to improve the control over the Queenside before pushing b5 .} ({After} 13. b5 c5 $1 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd4 Rc8 16. Nce2 Nd7 17. O-O Ne5 {, Black has an isolated pawn but a very active position.}) 13... Nd7 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Rfc1 (15. Na4 b5 $5 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. bxc5 Qe6 18. a4 a6) 15... Nb6 {The knight goes to c4 .} 16. Nd2 Qe7 17. Qc2 a6 18. a4 Bg7 19. Ne2 (19. b5 axb5 20. axb5 c5 $1 21. dxc5 Qxc5 22. Ne2 Qxc2 23. Rxc2 Rdc8 {and Black again has active pieces for the isolated d5 -pawn.}) 19... Bh6 20. Re1 ({After} 20. b5 cxb5 21. axb5 Rdc8 22. Qb2 a5 {, the a-pawn is super strong, and the knight on b6 is perfectly placed.}) 20... Qe6 21. Nc1 {Objectively not great. White isn't well-prepared to meet Black's next move.} Nc4 22. Qc3 (22. Nxc4 dxc4 {, the point is that the knight is awfully placed. The threat is also ... Rxd4 , with a pin of the e-pawn.} 23. Ne2 b5 {.}) 22... Nd6 23. Nd3 Bg7 24. Nc5 Qe7 25. Re2 Re8 26. Rbe1 Qc7 27. a5 {White realizes b5 will not happen and prefers to secure the knight on c5 by preventing ... b6 .} Re7 {As b5 is no longer an idea, White plans to push e4 .} 28. Qd3 Rae8 29. f3 Nf5 {Black keeps an eye on both e3 and d4 , thus preventing e4 for now.} 30. g3 (30. g4 $6 Nh4 31. e4 Qf4) 30... h5 31. Kg2 Qc8 (31... b6 $1 {is a nice move, to create a new area of tension on the Queenside:} 32. axb6 Qxb6 {.}) 32. Ndb3 Rd8 33. Rd1 Bf6 34. Qc3 Bg7 35. e4 dxe4 36. fxe4 h4 {The knight can remain on f5 for now.} 37. g4 Nxd4 (37... Nh6 $1 38. h3 Nxg4 39. hxg4 Qxg4+ 40. Kf1 f5 {would have led to very nice winning chances for White thanks to the exposed white King.}) 38. Nxd4 Qxg4+ 39. Kf1 Rd6 (39... h3 $1 40. Rd3 {( Qe3} f5 {) Rd6=∞}) 40. Rd3 ({After} 40. Qe3 $1 Rf6+ 41. Ke1 {, somehow the King escapes, and the position is stable. White should be able to convert this position into a win.}) 40... Qf4+ {Also a mistake. I guess both players were in zeitnot.} 41. Rf2 Qe5 42. Rfd2 (42. Ne2 $6 Qxc3 43. Rxc3 Rd1+ $1 44. Kg2 Bxc3 45. Nxc3 Rc1 {, the knights aren't strong enough to play against a rook and two pawns!}) 42... Qf4+ 43. Rf2 Qe5 44. Rfd2 {Eventually, both players decided to repeat moves, and the game ended in a draw.} *

