{The following game has been played in a blitz event, but it's very interesting anyway.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Be6 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. Nge2 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Qc2 Nxg3 12. Nxg3 h5 {All this has already been analyzed extensively, in the 6.Qc2 variation (the move order was very different here).} 13. O-O-O {A logical reply. It would be weird for White to place the King on the Kingside.} h4 14. Nf5 Qf6 15. Kb1 O-O-O 16. g4 {White tries to secure the knight on f5 . Thus, it's logical to take en passant.} hxg3 17. hxg3 Kb8 {Just as White did a few moves before, Black puts the King in a safer spot.} 18. g4 Bb4 19. Ne2 Rxh1 20. Rxh1 Rh8 {Right now, it seems that Blacks plays for a draw by trading a few pieces.} 21. Rh5 Qd8 22. a3 Ba5 23. Qd1 Nf6 24. Rxh8 Qxh8 {Black has managed to take control of the h-file.} 25. Neg3 Bc7 26. f3 Qh3 (26... Qh2 {was probably stronger, as now} 27. Qh1 {is met with} Bxg3 {, winning some material. Qh1 Bxg3} 28. Nxg3 Nxg4 $1 29. fxg4 Qxg3 {.}) 27. Qh1 Qxh1+ 28. Nxh1 b6 29. Nf2 Ne8 {Black prepares ... f6 to defend the g5 -pawn.} 30. Nh3 f6 31. f4 Bd8 32. b4 Kc7 33. Kb2 Nd6 34. Nxd6 Kxd6 35. f5 {White closes the position. Objectively, it should have been a draw, but Black managed to keep pressing.} Bd7 36. Nf2 Bc7 37. e4 (37. Nd1 {, or many different moves, and White keeps an equal position.}) 37... Ke7 ({Following} 37... c5 $1 38. dxc5+ bxc5 39. bxc5+ Kxc5 40. exd5 Kxd5 {, the bishops are too strong, and the King on d5 is much stronger than its homolog. Black is winning.}) 38. Kc3 (38. exd5 cxd5 39. Nd1) 38... Bg3 39. Nd1 Be1+ 40. Kc2 Kd6 41. Ne3 Bf2 42. Kd2 Bg1 {The position is unpleasant, and White eventually blundered.} 43. Nc2 dxe4 44. Bxe4 c5 {Black opens the position for the pieces.} 45. dxc5+ bxc5 46. Bf3 Ke5 47. Be2 Ba4 {Black is winning, g4 will fall soon, and White decided to give up.} *

