1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Qc2 c5 6. dxc5 d4 7. Nb5 e5 8. Nxe5 a6 9. Na3 O-O ({All this has been analyzed in the theoretical section , where I prefer the move} 9... Bxc5 {.}) 10. g3 (10. Nd3 $5 Bf5) 10... Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxc5 12. Nd3 (12. Nf3 Bf5 13. Qb3 Nc6 14. Bg2 Ne4 15. O-O Rad8) 12... Qc6 13. Rg1 ({After} 13. f3 Bf5 14. Bg2 Qe6 {, it's difficult to castle for White, as e2 is hanging.}) 13... Bf5 {Topalov develops his pieces quickly and actively. He simply pins the d3 -knight.} 14. Bg2 Qc8 15. c5 Nbd7 16. c6 (16. b4 a5 {and White is unable to hold the Queenside. As Rg1 has been played, it will be a problem: the white King has nowhere to go.}) 16... Bxa3 {An important intermediate move. After this move, the Queen on c2 isn't protected, and it pins the c6 -pawn.} 17. bxa3 Ne5 {It's hard to advise White, who decided to give up the Queen for some material.} 18. Nxe5 Bxc2 19. cxb7 {White is getting some pieces back.} Qe6 20. bxa8=Q Rxa8 21. Bxa8 Qxe5 {So, there are two rooks and a pawn for the Queen. But White's main problem is the King on e1 , unable to reach a safe place.} 22. Bf4 Qa5+ 23. Kf1 ({After} 23. Bd2 Qxa3 24. Kf1 h5 25. Kg2 Be4+ 26. Bxe4 Nxe4 {, the King is safer on g2 , but White has passive pieces.}) 23... g5 {A strong move! The bishop doesn't have any great square.} 24. Bc1 (24. Bb8 Qd8 {and Black wins a piece:} 25. Be5 Ng4 {.}) ({In case of} 24. Rc1 d3 {, Black saves the bishop, and the pawn on d3 is a new problem.}) 24... Qc3 25. Kg2 Qc8 {Very safe. The bishop is trapped now!} (25... Qxa1 26. Bxg5 Qxa2 27. Bxf6 Qe6 28. Bxd4 Be4+ {was also winning, but the variation is more complicated.}) 26. Bxg5 (26. Bf3 g4) 26... Qxa8+ {Black has a big material advantage and is completely winning.} 27. f3 Qe8 28. Rge1 Nd5 29. Rac1 Qa4 30. Kg1 f6 31. Bd2 Kf7 32. Kg2 Nb6 {A strong game from Topalov, who kept a cool head in the complications.} *

