1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 (6. Qc2 c5 7. dxc5 Na6 {was the move order we discussed in the course, but it will transpose to the game later.}) 6... Nbd7 7. Qc2 c5 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Rd1 Qa5 10. Nd2 Bd7 11. a3 Ba4 12. Nxa4 Qxa4 13. Rc1 Rfc8 {We covered the game until here in the theoretical chapters. Black directly targets the Queen on c8 . Keep in mind the rook on c8 also can have some problems, as it's not so well protected.} 14. Be2 (14. Qxa4 Nxa4 15. Rb1 a6 $1 16. Bd3 dxc4 17. Bxc4 b5 {is also better for Black.}) 14... b5 ({Interesting, but objectively not the best.} 14... dxc4 $1 {is the right move.} 15. Bxc4 b5 $1 16. Be2 Nd3+ {and Black wins some material, as the rook on c1 is hanging.}) 15. b4 Qxc2 (15... Ncd7 16. Qxa4 bxa4 17. c5 {is not so appealing for Black.}) 16. Rxc2 Nce4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. c5 (18. f3 g5 19. fxe4 gxf4 20. exd5 a5 {, an amazing resource for Black, who destroys the Queenside, and the position remains complicated.}) 18... a5 {Black opens the a-file for the rook.} 19. O-O axb4 20. axb4 g5 ({Not a great move. Better was} 20... Bf6 {to avoid Be5 .}) 21. Be5 f6 22. f3 ({Also a mistake by White. After} 22. Bd4 {, Black would have been in trouble here, as b5 is hanging.}) 22... Nxc5 {Black gains the dangerous c5 -pawn.} 23. Bg3 Na4 24. Rxc8+ Rxc8 25. Bxb5 Nb6 {Now, the endgame is objectively balanced, but I like Black's prospects in the center, and that's what prevailed in the game.} 26. Rb1 e5 27. h4 h6 28. Be1 Kf7 29. Bd3 Ke6 30. g4 Ra8 31. Rc1 Kf7 32. h5 Ra3 33. Bg6+ Kf8 34. b5 Nc4 35. e4 Rxf3 36. exd5 Rf4 37. Bf5 Ba3 38. Rc2 Ne3 39. Rc8+ Ke7 40. Bf2 Nxg4 41. b6 Rxf2 42. Bxg4 Rb2 43. Rc7+ Kd6 44. Rd7+ Kc5 45. b7 Kd4 {The b-pawn is useless, while Black activates the King to help the e-pawn.} 46. d6 e4 47. Kf1 Ke5 {Black gains the d6 -pawn, the game is over.} 48. Rd8 Bxd6 49. Bc8 f5 50. Re8+ Kf4 51. Rd8 Kf3 52. Ke1 Bg3+ 53. Kd1 e3 *

