1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 a6 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bg3 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. a3 Qe7 11. Bxd6 cxd6 12. e3 O-O 13. Bd3 Rac8 14. Qb1 e5 {Up to this point, alternatives have been discussed in the relevant chapter. Black has a great position already, and we are going to see how he converted it. Right now, the threat is to push ... e4 , gaining a piece.} 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bf5 g6 17. Bh3 {To keep the pin, the bishop has to go to a diagonal where it won't have many prospects.} Rcd8 18. Bxd7 {Not forced, but definitely the last moment if White wants to trade the bishop.} (18. O-O Nc5 19. Qc2 e4 $1 {Getting the d3 -square for good.} 20. Nd4 Nd3 {and Black has a pleasant edge.}) 18... Rxd7 19. O-O Rfd8 {Black easily takes over the initiative.} 20. Qc2 Qe6 21. h3 Rc8 22. Qb3 Qxb3 {Black simplifies to enter a favorable endgame.} 23. Nxb3 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Rd3 25. Na5 Rc2 26. b4 e4 {Of course, taKing isn't permitted, as the knight would come too easily to the center.} 27. f4 (27. fxe4 Nxe4 28. f3 Rdd2 {and Black will mate on the second rank.}) 27... Nd5 {Coming to d7 instead was probably stronger, to avoid the Nb7 - c5 maneuver.} 28. Rac1 {White gives away a pawn to get some compensation, but that's not worth it while it was still possible to hold.} (28. Nb7 $1 {was the best defense in a difficult position.} Rdd2 {( Nxe3!? fxe3 Rdd2} 29. Rfd1 {Rg2+ Kh1 Rh2+ Kg1= ) Rfd1= and White holds somehow.}) 28... Rxc1 29. Rxc1 Rxa3 30. Nc6 Rb3 ({A part of the edge slips away.} 30... Rc3 $1 31. Rxc3 Nxc3 32. Nb8 f5 33. Nxa6 Kf7 {would have been completely winning for Black.}) 31. Ra1 Nc7 32. Rd1 Ne6 33. Rd6 Rd3 34. Nd4 ({The rook endgame is hopeless. It was necessary to try something in the knight endgame instead. After} 34. Rxd3 exd3 35. Kf1 Kg7 36. Ke1 Kf6 37. Kd2 g5 $1 38. fxg5+ Kxg5 {, the pawn on h3 is still in trouble, and Black remains better.}) 34... Nxd4 35. exd4 Rxh3 36. Rxa6 Rb3 {Black gains another pawn, and this time, he didn't spoil the advantage for the rest of the game.} 37. d5 Rxb4 38. Kf1 Rd4 39. d6 Kg7 40. Ke2 Rd3 41. Rb6 f5 42. Rb7+ Kf6 43. Rxh7 Rxd6 44. Rb7 Rd3 45. Rb6+ Kg7 46. Rb7+ Kh6 47. Rxb5 Rf3 48. Kf1 Rxf4 {It just takes a little bit of time, but this is hopeless.} 49. Kg2 Kg5 50. Rb3 Rg4+ 51. Kh3 Kf4 52. Kh2 g5 53. Ra3 Rh4+ 54. Kg2 Rh6 55. Rb3 Rd6 56. Ra3 Rd3 57. Ra4 Rd2 58. Ra3 Re2 59. Kf1 Rb2 60. Kg2 Kg4 61. Ra4 Re2 62. Rb4 f4 63. Kf1 Kf3 *

