1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 5. Bb2 d5 6. d4 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O c5 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. Rac1 Rc7 12. Ne5 cxd4 13. exd4 dxc4 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 Bd6 16. Qe2 Bf4 17. Rc2 b5 18. c5 Nd5 {We have discussed the current variation in the theoretical section . Black has managed to disrupt White's hanging pair of pawns in the center and has full control over the d5 -square.} 19. Nf3 {White just prevented the possibility of ... Bxd2 and intends to continue with g3 , forcing ... Bh6 , where the bishop could be quite useless.} Nb4 {Of course, the light squares are already a problem for White, so take the light-squared bishop.} 20. Rc3 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 b4 {The pawn was hanging anyway, and it disrupts White's piece harmony.} 22. Rc2 (22. Rb3 a5 23. Bc1 Bxc1 24. Rxc1 Bd5 {would have been good for Black too.}) 22... e5 {Black uses the pin on the d-file.} 23. d5 {White decides to go for major trades.} (23. Re1 $1 {, simply bringing a new piece into play.} Qd5 24. Qb3 e4 25. Ne5 Bxe5 26. dxe5 a5 {was somehow better for White than the game.}) 23... Qxd5 24. Qxd5 Bxd5 25. Bxe5 Bxe5 26. Nxe5 {Galliamova was probably thinKing she had a good chance of achieving a draw here. Unfortunately, the pawns on the Queenside are poorly placed for her, and the position is very difficult.} f6 27. Rd2 (27. Nf3 Rfc8 28. Rfc1 a5 29. Nd2 a4 {and it's hard to come up with useful moves for White.}) 27... Be6 28. Nd3 Rd8 {Now White also has piece problems.} 29. Rfd1 a5 30. f3 Bf5 {Finally, Black decides to take some material. The pawn on c5 falls after the trades.} 31. Kf2 Rxd3 32. Rxd3 Bxd3 33. Rxd3 Rxc5 34. a3 {White tries to get rid of the Queenside weakness, which is the best attempt. But her rook will be poorly placed on a3 , in front of the passed pawn.} bxa3 35. Rxa3 Kf7 36. Ke3 ({The rook shouldn't move, otherwise,} 36. Rb3 Rc7 {. The rook comes behind the pawn, and things are just getting worse for White.}) 36... Ke6 37. Rb3 {White threatens Rb7 or Rb6 +, depending what Black does.} Kd6 38. Rb8 (38. Rb6+ Rc6 39. Rb7 Ra6 40. Rxg7 a4 41. Rb7 {, the rook should return before it's too late.} a3 42. Rb1 a2 43. Ra1 Kc5 44. Kd3 Kb4 45. Kc2 Ka3 {, Black follows with ... Rc6 + and ... Kb2 , the game is over.}) 38... Rc2 39. g4 Kc7 {I don't like this move, it simply goes in the wrong direction. You can feel the time control was close.} (39... Rc3+ $1 {is more precise, according to the engine.} 40. Ke4 {, anywhere the King goes there are drawbacks. On the fourth rank, Black will have ideas to play ... Rc4 + and ... a4 , to go behind the passed pawn quickly.} a4 41. Rg8 ({In case of} 41. Rb7 Rc7 {, the rook is coming behind the pawn.}) 41... a3 42. Rxg7 Rc4+ 43. Kf5 Ra4 {and Black promotes too fast.}) 40. Rg8 g6 41. h4 (41. Rg7+ $1 Kb6 42. Rxh7 a4 43. Rh8 Kb7 44. h4 a3 45. Rd8 a2 46. Rd1 {doesn't seem to be winning anymore for Black.}) 41... Kb7 ({That's too slow.} 41... Rc3+ $1 {Again, this intermediate move, forcing the King to go somewhere, was the right decision.}) 42. Rf8 {Now f6 falls.} a4 43. Rxf6 ({The final blunder.} 43. Kd3 $1 {This very hard move was the only way to save the day for White:} Rf2 44. Rf7+ Kb6 45. Rxf6+ Kb5 46. Rf7 a3 47. Rxh7 {.}) 43... a3 44. Rd6 a2 45. Rd1 Rc4 {The rook comes behind, and the Kingside pawns are not strong enough for White.} 46. Ra1 Ra4 47. f4 Kc6 {The King goes towards the center, to keep the option to get the pawns or rush towards b2 .} 48. Kf3 Kd5 {The threat is ... Ra3 + followed by ... Ke4 , where Black will collect the pawns. White has to move one of the pawns to go forward with the King.} 49. g5 Kc4 50. f5 {A desperate attempt.} gxf5 51. Kf4 Kb3+ 52. Kxf5 Rxh4 {By taKing this pawn away, Black gets rid of White's counterplay.} (52... Kb2 $6 {Still winning, but not precise at all.} 53. Rxa2+ Kxa2 54. h5 Ra6 55. g6 {and now, the win is tricky.} Ra5+ $1 {The only way.} 56. Kf6 Rxh5 57. g7 Rh6+ 58. Kf7 Rg6 {and Black wins thanks to the h-pawn.}) 53. Rg1 Ra4 {Now things are easy, White won't get a passed pawn, so she decided to resign.} *

