1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. g3 Bd6 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O h6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. b3 dxc4 9. bxc4 e5 10. d5 Na5 11. c5 Bxc5 12. Nxe5 Re8 13. Nd3 Bb6 14. e4 c6 15. Nf4 {This double-edged position has been considered in the chapter about the Catalan . White seems to prevail, as White has the center, but things are not so clear. Black doesn't have any weaknesses and keeps an active position.} Bg4 16. Qd3 g5 {An interesting move. Black gets rid of the knight so that it goes back somewhere passive.} 17. h3 ({Necessary, to get rid of the bishop. After} 17. Nfe2 $2 cxd5 $1 18. exd5 Rc8 {, Black is even more active than before, there is something wrong with White.}) 17... Bd7 (17... gxf4 $2 18. hxg4 fxg3 19. Qxg3 {would be bad for Black.}) 18. Nfe2 cxd5 19. exd5 Rc8 {The balance is hard to maintain for White.} 20. Rb1 {White simply decides to activate a rook.} Nc4 21. Nd4 {White is putting a different piece in a position where it's not protected anymore.} (21. g4 $1 {Surprisingly, this was the only move.} Ne5 22. Qg3 $1 {That's probably the point of White's last move. The Queen finds a safe spot here.} Ng6 23. Be3 {and anything can happen in this position.}) 21... Ne5 {Gaining a tempo on the Queen and discovering an attack on the c3 -knight.} 22. Qd2 Bxh3 {Far from a surprise, there is a tactic for Black.} 23. Rxb6 ({White tries to get rid of the bishop, which could take on d4 .} 23. Bxh3 Bxd4 $1 24. Bxc8 Nf3+ {and Black wins.}) 23... Bxg2 24. Rxf6 (24. Kxg2 axb6 {, a safe extra exchange for Black.}) 24... Bxf1 25. Rxh6 {Both players keeps taKing.} Bd3 {The bishop goes back to protect the King.} 26. Rh5 Bg6 27. Rxg5 Qf6 {White has a pawn for the exchange, but his attack is gone, and Black will start his own.} 28. Kg2 Kh7 29. Qe1 Nd3 {Again, so many pieces are under attack for White.} 30. Qh1+ Kg8 31. Be3 Rxe3 {Several other moves were winning, but this is the strongest, to invade on f2 on the next move. White is lost and resigned.} *

